<H1>Greene Environmental Coalition</H1>
<HR>
<H5><EM>Organization Purpose and History</EM></H5>
<P>The Greene Environmental Coalition (GEC) is a Greene
County, Ohio non-profit corporation with 501 C3 status. In
1991 the organization grew from a weekly discussion and
action group to a formal corporation organized to provide a
clearinghouse for information relating to environmental
matters. GEC focused its efforts on a nearby hazardous waste
burning cement kiln in Greene County, Ohio. As a result of
its efforts two industrial ash dumps polluting surface and
ground water are being cleaned up. The cement kiln was denied
its permit to handle hazardous waste and in November of 1994,
formally moved to exit the hazardous waste business at all
its facilities around the country.<BR>
 </P>
<P>In early 1995, the organization established a structure
more suited to &quot;peace time&quot; activism. GEC is
serving as a small umbrella organization for local grass
roots groups and has taken an active role providing statewide
support for environmental legislation and rulemaking.
Currently the group is working on air and solid waste rules
and hazardous waste legislation.<BR>
 </P>
<P><B>Structure<BR>
</B>Our corporate structure requires a
Board and officers. While the Board approves major
expenditures, the decision making body is the membership.
Most of the current members have been with GEC for several
years. Our average age is over 40. We are gender and
politically balanced. <BR>
 </P>
<P>We maintain an office, meeting room, and library.
Currently we keep office hours from 9 to 12 daily. We can be
reached by telephone at 513.767.2109 or by <A HREF="mailto:gec@sprynet.com">
E-Mail </A> .<BR>
</P>
<P><B>Staff<BR>
</B>GEC has no paid staff, although it has
recently contracted for a project coordinator. Volunteers
from the membership and an occasional intern from the local
university have given thousands of hours to the organization.
The group has recently contracted with a long standing member
to provide six months coordination on expanding our role
within the advocacy community. <BR>
 </P>
<HR>
