<html>

<head>
<title>Sierra Club Home Page</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#B1CFBD">
<h2 align=center>Welcome to the </h2>
<h2 align=center>Home Page of the </h2>
<h2 align=center>Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club </h2>
<p><a name="Topics:"><strong>Topics:</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#The Ohio Sierra Club"><strong>Learn About Ohio's Sierra Club</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#Regional Groups"><strong>Regional Groups</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#Transportation and Liveable Communities Campaign"><strong>Transportation and Liveable Communities Project</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#How To Reach the Ohio Chapter"><strong>How You Can Reach Us</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#Interesting Web Sites, Ohio-Related"><strong>Interesting Web Sites</strong></a></p>
<p><a name="The Ohio Sierra Club"><strong>The Ohio Sierra Club</strong></a></p>
<p>The Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club was chartered in 1968 and has an extensive history of 
grassroots environmental activism in Ohio. More than 16,000 members make up seven regional 
volunteer-driven Sierra Club Groups that work on environmental issues in their areas. These 
Groups meet regularly and sponsor a variety of conservation oriented activities including outings 
events, activist campaigns, and environmental educational programs. </p>
<p>Volunteers work on several campaigns, including the Clean Water Campaign, the Radioactive 
Waste Campaign, the Protect Ohio's Wilds Campaign and the Livable Communities Campaign. To 
find out more about these campaigns &amp; how to get involved in them, please contact the Chapter 
Office. Contact information is found below. </p>
<p>In addition to the volunteer activists, the Ohio Chapter employs two full time professional staff. The 
staff in Columbus work as partners with the volunteers in addressing critical environmental issues in 
the state. This structure is unique to environmental groups in Ohio and well suited to influence 
Ohio's state government. Jeff Skelding is the Chapter's lobbyist and works in the Ohio General 
Assembly to promote the Sierra Club's state legislative agenda. To find out more about the 
legislative program please contact the Chapter office. Margaret Koran directs the Chapter's 
Liveable Communities Campaign . More about this campaign is found below. </p>
<p><a name="Regional Groups"><b>Regional Groups</b></a></p>
<p>Each regional group conducts outings and meetings and publishes its own newsletter bi-monthly. 
Contact the group in your area to become an active Club member. If no phone number is listed, 
please contact the Chapter office. </p>
<p>Western Lake Erie </p>
<p>Northeast Ohio (216) 843-7272 </p>
<p>Portage Trail (Akron) </p>
<p>Salt Springs (Youngstown) </p>
<p>Central Ohio (614) 470-2792 </p>
<p>Tecumseh (Dayton) </p>
<p><a href="http://www.sierraclub.org/chapters/oh/miaimi/">Miami</a> (Cincinnati) (513) 841-0111 </p>
<h6><a href="#Topics:">Return</a></h6>
<p><a name="Transportation and Liveable Communities Campaign"><b>Transportation and Liveable Communities Campaign</b></a></p>
<p>Margaret Koran is a transportation policy analyst and the staff person to contact regarding the 
Livable Communities Campaign. The Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club through the Livable 
Communities Campaign seeks to support transportation policy, land-use planning and economic 
development which is environmentally sound, safe, economical, and socially just. The Campaign is 
also working to increase public participation at all levels of transportation planning. The Ohio 
Chapter encourages environmentally friendly modes of transportation as a way to minimize our 
dependence upon the automobile. </p>
<p>The federal transportation funding law, ISTEA (Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act 
of 1991), will be reauthorized in 1997. ISTEA focuses on linking various modes of transportation 
and encouraging environmentally friendly modes of travel, especially in areas with poor air quality. 
Highway funding still dominates though. There are several current Congressional proposals pending 
which could dramatically affect transportation funding and policy in Ohio. The Ohio Department of 
Transportation favors changes to increase the amount of federal gas taxes that the state gets back. 
Unfortunately, the same bill would end small set asides for projects like bike paths and historic 
preservation. <i>For more information on these bills, please contact the chapter office.</i> </p>
<p>One of ISTEA's best provisions is mandatory public participation at all stages of transportation 
planning, on a local level and state level. In Ohio there are 16 metropolitan planning organizations 
(MPOs) that develop land use and transportation plans for their areas. You can get involved by 
attending meetings to learn more about the planning process. Many have citizen advisory councils 
which you can be a part of. <i>For more information about becoming active at your local MPO, 
please contact the chapter office.</i> </p>
<p>Statewide land use laws are weak and contribute to problems of urban and suburban sprawl. 
Farmland is lost while simultaneously urban centers decay. Halting this pattern will improve the 
quality of life for all Ohioans. An upcoming conference will focus on ways to curb this spiraling 
growth to make a better Ohio. <i>For more information on this conference and other initiatives 
regarding urban sprawl, please contact the chapter office.</i> </p>
<h6><a href="#Topics:">Return</a></h6>
<p><a name="How To Reach the Ohio Chapter"><b>How To Reach the Ohio Chapter</b></a></p>
<p>The staff at the Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club can be reached </p>
<p>By Mail 145 N. High Street </p>
<p>Suite 409 </p>
<p>Columbus, OH 43215 </p>
<p>By Phone (614) 461-0734 </p>
<p>By E-mail General comments/questions: <a href="mailto:ohsc2@igc.apc.org">ohsc2@igc.apc.org </a></p>
<p>Transportation &amp; Livable Communities: <a href="mailto:ohsc@igc.apc.org">ohsc@igc.apc.org </a></p>
<p>By Fax (614) 461-0730</p>
<h6><a href="#Topics:">Return</a></h6>
<p><a name="Interesting Web Sites, Ohio-Related"><b>Interesting Web Sites, Ohio-Related</b></a></p>
