<head>
<title>Rivers Unlimited</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#B1CFC8">
<h1 align=center><img src="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/images/rivers.jpg" alt="Rivers Unlimited" align=bottom></h1>
<hr>
<h1 align=center><i>&quot;Ohio's Most Natural Resource&quot;</i></h1>
<p align=center><i>Rivers Unlimited </i></p>
<p align=center><i>1207 Grandview Ave., Suite 205</i></p>
<p align=center><i>Columbus, OH 43212-3449</i></p>
<p align=center><i>Phone: 614/487-7511</i></p>
<p align=center><i>Fax: 614/487-7513 </i></p>
<p align=center><a href="mailto:riveruoh@aol.com">E- mail: riveruoh@aol.com </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/canoe/index.html"><i>C.A.N.O.E.</i></a><i> 'Citizens Activist Network for the Ohio Environment' - weekly reports</i></p>
<hr>
<p>Rivers Unlimited is a statewide organization that works to protect and restore Ohio's 61,000 miles 
of rivers and streams. Since 1972, we have supported the efforts of citizens and groups working to 
protect their local waterways, and worked on over 100 projects in 36 counties.</p>
<p>In June of 1996, Rivers Unlimited launched its &quot;<a href="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/twenty.html"> Twenty in 2000 </a>&quot; campaign, which is designed to 
double the number of scenic rivers in Ohio by the turn of the century. Though the Ohio Scenic 
Rivers Program was proactive during its founding decade of the 1970s, no waterways have been 
added since 1984. Rivers Unlimited will help citizens generate local support in their communities to 
qualify a waterway for scenic river status.</p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited has also emerged as the statewide leader in developing greenways. Greenways 
are open spaces that connect people, parks, historic sites, and natural areas and frequently follow 
streamside corridors and abandoned rail lines. The organization has recently hired a coordinator to 
direct a two-year statewide <a href="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/greenway.html">Greenways Initiative </a>.</p>
<p><br>
With the relocation of our statewide office to Columbus in mid-1995, Rivers Unlimited has become 
active in influencing a variety of <a href="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/legislat.html">state legislation </a>. We are currently opposing a takings bill and the 
environmental audit privilege bill, and supporting a bill to overturn the antidegradation statute.</p>
<p>Members of Rivers Unlimited receive the newsletter Rivers Quarterly, invitations to special events, 
and regular updates about timely river issues. Network and training opportunities are provided to 
both member organizations and individuals. Join Rivers Unlimited today and join in the growing 
movement to protect and restore Ohio's 61,000 miles of rivers and streams.</p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited also supports a number of <a href="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/local/index.html">local river organizations</a>. </p>
<hr>
<p>For membership, send a tax-deductible contribution of:</p>
<ul COMPACT>
<li>$35 Basic Membership</li>
<li>$50 Family Membership</li>
<li>$100 River Sustainer</li>
<li>$250 River Steward</li>
<li>$15 Student, Senior Citizen, Limited Income </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.greenlink.org/rivers/board.html">Rivers Unlimited's Board of Trustees</a></p>
<hr>
<p align=center>OTHER STATEWIDE RIVER ORGANIZATIONS</p>
