<title>Critical Environmental Issues</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#B1CFC8">

<h2 align="center">Critical Environmental Issues in the Midwest</h2>

<h2 align="center">and Nation</h2>

<h3><a href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/hb604.html"><strong>HB604</strong></a><strong>
| </strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/janlet.html"><strong>RTK
January Update and Letter</strong></a><strong> |</strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/alert1.html"><strong>TRI
Update</strong></a><strong>| </strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/letter.html"><strong>TRI
Citizen's Letter</strong></a><strong>| </strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/tvshow.html"><strong>TRI
TV Program</strong></a><strong>| </strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/ranking.html"><strong>State
Rankings of Enviro Expenditures</strong></a><strong> |</strong><a
href="#Of Special Interest:"><strong>HWIR</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/coastal.html"><strong>Coastal
Alliance</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a
href="http://www.greenlink.org/critical/nwp.html"><strong>NWP</strong></a><strong>
(Nationwide Wetland Permits)</strong></h3>

<p><a name="Update on Brownfields"><strong>Update on Brownfields</strong></a></p>

<p>Apparently there have been changes made to the rules on
Brownfields since the last filing. According to a memo form
Jenifer Kwasniewski, dated Oct. 3, 1996, the pulic comment period
is extended until the end of business (5:00 pm) on Oct. 15, 1996.
The OEPA expects to refile the rules with JCARR later in October
and is likely to be on the Nov. 19th JCARR agenda. To request a
copy of the rules, contact Jenifer Kwasniewski at (614) 644-2279
or e-mail: <a
href="mailto:jenifer_kwasniewski@central.epa.ohio.gov">jenifer_kwasniewski@central.epa.ohio.gov</a>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a name="Of Special Interest:"><strong>Of Special Interest:</strong></a></p>

<p>An unusual alliance of environmentalists and industry is
concerned about the Hazardous Waste Identification Rule (HWIR).
This legislation will reduce the exit level on 376 hazardous
chemicals. The materials would no longer be treated as Subtitle C
requiring oversight by RCRA (Resource Conservation Recovery Act),
but instead will be reduced to Subtitle D. This new
classification would allow the waste to be disposed of in
municipal landfills.</p>

<p>To read more about this important issue and learn why several
groups oppose it, contact <a href="http://www.environment.net">P.E.P</a>.'s
web site. <a href="http://www.greenlink.org/forum/REG-AGENCIES/">Regulatory
Agency Forum </a>(<strong>The forums are available to all
GreenLink members.</strong> If you are not a GreenLink member,
please <a href="http://www.greenlink.org/signup.html">Sign up</a>
now. It's free!)</p>

<p>The September issue of <u>Ohio Environmental Protection Agency
Agenda 96 </u>states: &quot;As chairman of the Environmental
Council of States' waste committee, Director Schregardus has
committed the Agency to assist in this federal rule making, which
potentially will declassify large amounts of low toxicity waste
from hazardous waste management requirements. Contact: Mike
Savage, (614) 644-2917.&quot;</p>

<hr>

