<html>

<head>
<title>OEC</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p><a href="http://www.greenlink.org/images/glnklogo.gif"><img src="glnklogo.gif" alt="GreenLink: wired for the
environment." align=top border=0></a> <br>
</p>
<hr>
<h1 align=center><strong>Brownfields Issues</strong> - Ohio 
Environmental Council</h1>
<hr>
<p align=center><br>
<b>ENVIRONMENTAL COMMUNITY MUST OPPOSE RULES NEW 
BROWNFIELDS RULES</b></p>
<p align=left>Please plan to attend one of three public meetings the week of September 3, 1996. The 
meetings will be held in West Cleveland, Columbus, and Dayton. No specific dates or 
locations have been set yet. The purpose of the meetings is to learn more about the 
Brownfields rules and the public comment period which ends on September 9. The Joint 
Committee on Agency Rule Review is scheduled for September 24. By that time we would 
like to have people tell the Joint Committee on Agency Rule Review why the new rules are 
a very bad idea.<br></p>
<p align=center><b>WHAT IS BROWNFIELDS</b></p>
<p align=left>Brownfields refer to properties that are contaminated with hazardous waste. Many 
Brownfields are located in Ohio's inner cities urban areas.</p>
<p align=center><b>WHAT ARE THE NEW BROWNFIELDS RULES<br>
</b></p>
<p align=left>The Ohio EPA has created a program called a Voluntary Action Program (VAP). This 
program allows private developers to redevelop Brownfields sites. While redeveloping 
these sites is a good idea, the new rules that apply to the VAP program do three things:<br>
<br>
</p>
<ol>
<li>The new rules <b>drastically reduced the cleanup requirements</b> for these properties 
as an incentive to the developers. </li>
<li>The new rules <b>release private property redevelopers from liability</b> if any 
problems arise in the future from contamination left on the property. </li>
<li>The new rules <b>have secrecy provisions </b>in them that will prevent citizens from 
getting critical information about the amount of contamination on the property and 
the way the cleanup is being done. </li>
</ol>
<p align=center><b>ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE ISSUES OF THE VAP</b></p>
<p>Many of the contaminated properties are located in low-income and minority communities 
that have little or no political power. Many of these communities are already overburdened 
by heavily polluting industries, hazardous waste landfills and hazardous waste incinerators. 
The VAP program will allow Brownfields property, after cleanup, to still have high levels of 
very dangerous contaminants in the groundwater and the soil. These contaminants will 
migrate into drinking water and emit pollutants into the air. Susceptible populations like the 
elderly, children, and the ill will be exposed to these contaminants on a daily basis. 
Remember that you do not have to live in the inner city to be affected. These toxic 
contaminants get into underground water and the air and affect all of us.<br>
<b></b></p>
<p align=center><b>WHAT CAN YOU DO TO STOP THE ENVIRONMENTAL INJUSTICE<br>
</b></p>
<p>It is extremely important for the environmental community to quickly organize and stop this 
environmental injustice. This is poor public policy and it will lead to our inner cities 
remaining permanently contaminated. Brownfields can be successfully redeveloped without 
relaxing the clean up requirements. Redevelopment of our inner cities does not have to be 
at the expense of human health.<br></p>
<p>Please contact the following organizations for more information on how you can help.<br>
<b>Ohio Environmental Council	614-224-4900<br>
Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club	614-461-0734<br>
Ohio Citizen Action</b> <b>614-224-4111</b><br>
</p>
<hr>
<h5>Return to:<a href="http://www.greenlink.org/brown/index.html"> Brownfields Home Page</a></h5>
<h5>Return to: <a href="http://www.greenlink.org/">Greenlink<tt>TM</tt> Home Page</a> </h5>
