<body>
<h3 align=center>Testimony For Public Record </h3>
<h3 align=center>Ohio EPA Certification of Corps of Engineers Nationwide Permits</h3>
<p>November 4, 1996 on behalf of:</p>
<p>Sandy Buchanan - Ohio Citizen Action, Vicki Deisner - Ohio Environmental Council, Elaine Marsh 
- Friends of the Crooked River, Clara Marus - League of Women Voters of Ohio, Louis Adams - 
Environmental Network, Julie Sibbing- National Audubon Society, Great Lakes Regional Office, 
Edith Chase - Concerned Citizen, Jeff Skelding - Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club, Tod Ambs - 
Rivers Unlimited, Tony DiNovo - Izaak Walton League/Ohio Division, (Other signatories will be 
added during the public comment period)</p>
<p>My name is Julie Sibbing, I am the Wetlands Coordinator for the Great Lakes Regional Office of 
the National Audubon Society. I come here tonight to present a unified front on behalf of the 
environmental and conservation community in Ohio with regards to the Ohio Environmental 
Protection Agency's re-certification of Corps of Engineers' Nationwide Permits under Sections 404 
and 401 of the Clean Water Act. The Corps of Engineers has requested Section 401 Water 
Quality Certification for 37 existing and 4 new nationwide permits. We appreciate and take very 
seriously this opportunity to contribute our input into the Ohio EPA's decision on whether to certify, 
certify with conditions, or deny each of these permits. </p>
<p>The state of Ohio should take its responsibilities with regards to protecting wetlands, streams, and 
other waters very seriously. Failure to do so will result in damage, not only to ecological systems, 
but to our state's economy and quality of life as well. Where the Federal government leaves our 
resources unprotected, the state needs to step in and pick up the slack. The 401 certification 
process for NWPs gives Ohio a chance to adjust permitting processes to the needs of our state. 
Since we are second in the nation in percentage of original wetlands loss, we need to be a leader in <br>
protecting our wetland and other water resources. </p>
<p>A National Audubon Society Report &quot;The Impact of Individual 404 Permits on Ohio Wetlands 
1990-1995&quot; revealed a net loss of Ohio wetlands, even under the most stringent individual 
permitting requirements. It therefore concerns us greatly that state agencies are not even involved in 
the majority of permits issued for wetland impacts in Ohio. We ask the Ohio EPA to carefully 
consider the impacts to our state's waters of delegating responsibilities to the Corps of Engineers 
through NWPs.</p>
<p><strong><u>General Comments:</u></strong></p>
<p>We are seriously concerned that the Corps of Engineers has completely failed to document the 
impacts of NWPs on our state's aquatic resources. Such information is needed in order for the 
Ohio EPA to make informed decisions about the reauthorization of existing NWPs. We strongly 
encourage the Ohio EPA to work closely with the Corps to make sure that all future impacts to our 
state's aquatic resources are well documented and that significant degradation is not allowed to 
occur.</p>
<p>An overall concern we have with the implementation of the Nationwide permit program in Ohio is 
that currently, several NWPs can be &quot;stacked&quot; (used in combination) to allow bigger impacts than 
allowable under any one NWP. A housing development may use one nationwide for houses, 
another each time a road is crossed, and a third to put in water sewer and power lines. The impacts 
add up quickly. We therefore request that the Ohio EPA do a careful analysis of any extant or 
potential abuses of &quot;stacking,&quot; and to disallow the use of these permits in combination with any 
other NWPs. </p>
<p>Some areas of the state and some types of aquatic habitats deserve special protection from 
degradation. What may be considered an insignificant impact in some areas or in some habitats is 
highly significant in other areas or habitats. We therefore request that the Ohio EPA carefully 
consider denying the use of most or all NWPs in certain targeted areas, including, but not limited to: 
Sandusky Bay and adjacent wetlands, Lake Erie and adjacent wetlands, the Pond Brook 
Watershed, wetlands designated as Category 3 under the soon-to-be completed Wetland Water 
Quality Standards, and streams which are designated as Coldwater, Exceptional Warm Water, or 
Seasonal Salmonid aquatic life habitat in Ohio's water quality standards.</p>
<p>In order to adequately protect water quality in the state, several NWPs that have been certified in 
the past will need to be denied and many others conditioned. This will entail more work for the 
Ohio EPA's Division of Surface Water. Yet current staffing levels in this division are woefully 
inadequate. We request that Director Shregardus dedicate sufficient resources to Surface Water to 
enable them to handle permit applications, enforcement, and follow-through on permits. Inadequate 
staffing levels should not be an excuse to allow continued degradation of our state's waters. <br>
</p>
<h4><strong><u>Specific Comments:</u></strong></h4>
<p><strong>NWP 26 Headwaters and Isolated Wetlands. </strong></p>
<p>Our biggest concern related to the re-issuance of Nationwide Permits centers around NWP 26. By 
focusing this permit on headwater wetlands and isolated wetlands of under 10 acres, the Corps has 
managed to expedite the processing of the vast majority of wetland permits. Unfortunately this has 
been accomplished at the expense of many valuable wetlands and in flagrant violation of Section 
404 (e) of the Clean Water Act.</p>
<p>The Corps, recognizing the highly controversial nature of this permit has offered several options for 
its re-issuance. Yet, already, Arizona, Arkansas, California, Delaware, Florida, Indiana, <br>
Kansas, Louisiana, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, New York, Oregon, Tennessee, Texas, 
Vermont, Washington and Wyoming have stated their intention to reject certification of NWP 26 in 
any form. We request that Ohio follow the lead of these 18 states.</p>
<p>The Corps has not proven that impacts under NWP 26 have been minimal, especially on a 
cumulative scale. Since neither the Ohio EPA nor any of the Corps Districts operating in Ohio keep 
records on such impacts, it is hard to determine the extent of the impact to waters of the state. A 
study conducted by the USFWS Sacramento Field Office found that at least 725 acres of wetlands 
were filled under NWP 26 in the Sacramento region from 1987-1992. This cannot, in anyone's <br>
terms, be considered a minimal effect. The state of California has decided to deny certification to 
NWP 26. Ohio should follow suit. </p>
<p>Even if the Corps, in their re-issuance of NWP 26, reduces its coverage to 3 acres of impact, with 
anything under a third of an acre not requiring notification, significant degradation of water quality 
could occur. One third of an acre is nearly a mile of headwater stream 3 feet across. Three acres of 
wetlands covers an area the size of four football fields. Such vast destruction contributes greatly to 
the degradation of our Ohio wetlands, streams, and lakes and the wildlife that depend upon them. </p>
<p>NWP 26 discriminates against waters based on location and size, a concept that the National 
Academy of Sciences' National Research Council in their report on Wetlands, Characteristics and 
Boundaries has found to be scientifically indefensible. &quot;[t]he scientific basis for policies that attribute 
less importance to headwater areas and isolated wetlands than to other wetlands is weak.&quot; The 
study points out that both isolated and headwater wetlands perform many of the same functions and 
values as wetlands located adjacent to larger waterways, including that of water quality 
improvements.</p>
<p><strong>NWP 29 Single Family Homes:</strong></p>
<p>Another permit that greatly concerns us is NWP 29. Although this permit has not been used 
extensively to date, we anticipate that it will be used much more frequently in the future as 
developers become aware of its availability. Although various Corps districts have interpreted 
&quot;attendant features&quot; differently, a draft memo from Michael Davis, Chief of the Regulatory Branch 
of the Corps, dated August 25, 1995 states the following: &quot;We have listed several examples to be 
considered by the districts as attendant features. These include garage, driveway, storage shed, and 
septic field. In addition, we consider ponds, vegetable gardens, swimming pools, and tennis courts 
as allowable attendant features. Although we also believe that a yard is an appropriate attendant 
feature of a single-family home, we have not identified a size that is acceptable. Corps districts 
should work with the applicant to ensure that adequate, but not excessive, yards are authorized.&quot; 
The memo also states that no regional or case-specific conditions can be made to NWP 29 by 
Corps Districts. The memo also clarifies that attendant features can qualify for NWP 29 
independent of any construction of a single family home and allows for its use in <br>
the construction of a second home on the parcel in several cases.</p>
<p>Taken to this ridiculous extreme, NWP 29 can be used to fill up to a half acre of wetlands for a 
pond, a swimming pool, a tennis court, a second home, or simply to make a yard or vegetable 
garden. Already, on a nationwide basis, NWP 29 has been used to permit a pool, a deck, a boat 
shed, a workshop, and a septic field in wetlands adjacent to Lake Superior in Michigan. If the 
Corps will not condition the use of this permit to a reasonable level, then the Ohio EPA must do so. 
Beyond the geographical restrictions currently in place, and the restrictions on wetlands types, we 
request that the Ohio EPA condition the use of NWP 29 to apply only to the construction of 
single-family homes and to disallow attendant features altogether.</p>
<p>In addition, we request that the maximum fill size be reduced to 0.1 acre. If this permit is to be used 
for single family homes, no greater area should be necessary to accommodate construction.</p>
<p><strong>NWP 12 Utility Backfill and Bedding:</strong></p>
<p>We support all current restrictions on the use of NWP 12 and ask that the Ohio EPA further 
condition its certification by requiring complete revegetation of disturbed areas. This would provide 
an incentive to those performing the work to ensure that sufficient topsoil is backfilled into trenches 
to once again support aquatic vegetation. We also request that the Ohio EPA prohibit the use of 
this permit in conjunction with any other NWPs. </p>
<p><strong>NWP 13 Bank Stabilization:</strong></p>
<p>The Corps has proposed to eliminate the Pre-construction Notification requirement of NWP 13. 
The Ohio EPA should insist that pre-construction notification of impacts under NWP 13 continue. 
This is critical to allowing the Ohio DNR and the U.S.Fish and Wildlife Service to determine if a 
proposed project could negatively affect habitat for threatened and endangered species. Sediment 
loading resulting from such projects can pose a great risk to our state's many declining mollusk 
species. We support the continuation of all current conditions on the permit, with the exception of 
allowances for projects greater than 500 feet in length and in excess of one cubic yard per foot. 
Since the Corps has failed to enforce the conditions on NWP 13 in many areas, we ask that the 
OEPA limit the size of the project permitted to under 500 feet in length and one cubic yard per foot 
of material.</p>
<p><strong>NWP 14 Road Crossings:</strong></p>
<p>We request that conditions be attached to this NWP disallowing its use more than once per 
subdivision and limiting its impact to a third of an acre for a complete project. Without these 
conditions, developers are able to destroy highly significant amounts of wetlands by using the permit 
numerous times in one subdivision, when a shared crossing could be incorporated into the site. 
Another special condition should be that this permit not be used in conjunction with any other 
NWPs. </p>
<p><strong>NWP 18 Minor Discharges and NWP 19 Minor Dredging:</strong></p>
<p>We request that these permits not be used jointly, or in conjunction with any other NWP.</p>
<p><strong>NWP 32 Completed Enforcement Actions:</strong></p>
<p>Since the Corps is seeking to expand this permit to cover administrative settlements, which do not 
have a public notice requirement, we request that the Ohio EPA deny certification for this permit. 
We object to Corps administrative settlements occurring without any state or public scrutiny.</p>
<p><strong>Proposed NWP A - Moist Soil Management for Wildlife:</strong></p>
<p>This NWP should not be used to convert one wetland type to another for the enhancement of 
wildlife habitat. Each wetland type has unique characteristics, functions and values. We request that 
this permit be limited to maintenance of existing management regimes and that the Ohio EPA 
consider including a size limit. Enhancement activities should be permitted under individual permit 
processes due to the potential for significant changes in wetland functionality.</p>
<p><strong>Proposed NWP B - Minimal Effects :</strong></p>
<p>We request that the Ohio EPA deny certification to this proposed permit. Since this NWP is based 
upon USDA rules that have yet to be finalized, the Ohio EPA cannot determine what the effect 
would be on water quality in the state. Without this information, certification should not be 
considered.</p>
<p><strong>Proposed NWP C - Recreational Mining:</strong></p>
<p>We request that the Ohio EPA deny certification to this proposed NWP. Sand and gravel mining 
can be very detrimental to water quality. Furthermore, under the provision for recreational mining, 
the definition of &quot;recreational&quot; is left up to the District Engineer. Mining approved under this permit 
could allow for significant lowering of water quality and uncompensated destruction of fish habitat <br>
in Ohio's wetlands and streams.</p>
<p><strong>Proposed NWP D - Flood Control Structures:</strong></p>
<p>It is uncertain whether this permit is necessary, given the presence of NWP 3 which authorizes the 
repair, rehabilitation, or replacement of any previously authorized structure or fill. Many flood 
control projects were authorized and constructed many years ago, prior to widespread 
understanding and appreciation of the flood control and water storage function of wetlands. As a 
result, projects authorized in the past may not be supported by current natural resource 
management practices. Those projects that are no longer considered appropriate should not be 
perpetuated. The Ohio EPA should very carefully consider the effects of certification of this permit 
and/or any appropriate conditions that may reduce its potential negative impact. </p>
<p><strong>Other Problem NWPs:</strong></p>
<p>We request that the Ohio EPA continue to deny the following NWPs as they have tremendous 
potential to degrade water quality in the state: 16,17,21,23,34, and 40.</p>
<hr>
