<A NAME="INDIANA">
 <B>INDIANA </B></A><B> LOW-LEVEL RADIOACTIVE WASTE GENERATORS</B></P>
<P><B>AND POTENTIAL GENERATORS</B></P>
<P><B>DECEMBER 1995*</B></P>
</CENTER>
<P><BR>
Total number low-level radioactive waste
generators and potential generators in </P>
<P>Indiana as of 4 December 1995: 21</P>
<P><BR>
<B>Academic Generators .</B></P>
<P>1. Ball State University </P>
<P>2. Butler University </P>
<P>3. Indiana State University </P>
<P>4. Indiana University</P>
<P>5. Purdue University Medical Generators</P>
<P>6. University of Notre Dame </P>
<P><B>Medical Generators</B></P>
<P>1. Indiana University Medical School (Evansville)</P>
<P>2. Indiana University Medical School (Gary)</P>
<P>3. Indiana University - Purdue University</P>
<P>4. Veteran's Administration Medical Center, Roudebush</P>
<P><B>Industrial Generators </B></P>
<P>1. Allison Engine Company </P>
<P>2. Bayer, Inc.</P>
<P>3. Bethlehem Steel Corp. </P>
<P>4. Boehringer Mannheim Diagnostic </P>
<P>5. Bristol-Myers Squibb</P>
<P>6. Eli Lilly and Company</P>
<P>7. Lone Star Industries, Inc.</P>
<P>8. Mallinckrodt Veterinary</P>
<P>9. Nucor Steel</P>
<P>10. Pfizer, Inc.</P>
<P><B>Utility Generator</B></P>
<P>1. Public Service Indiana<BR>
 </P>
<P>*This list represents the best efforts of the Midwest
Compact Commission to </P>
<P>determine present and potential generators of low-level
radioactive waste in the </P>
<P>state of Indiana. Some generators actually shipping waste
to disposal sites during </P>
<P>any given period of time is subject to some variation.
The reasons for this </P>
<P>variation include, but are not limited to, the following:
change in product lines or services</P>
<P>offered, substitution of different radioactive or
non-radioactive materials, periodic</P>
<P>maintenance, equipment replacement, decontamination and
decommissioning activities,</P>
<P>and temporary storage of waste pending collection of
amounts sufficient for economical</P>
<P>shipping.</P>
