2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Radioactive
Waste -</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"> Radioactive Waste</H2>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"> In Our Backyard? </H2>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"> On Our Highways &amp; Railways?</H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER"> Why a Constitutional Amendment?</H3></CENTER>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>On June 7, 1995, the Ohio legislature passed a law,
Substitute Senate Bill 19, </P>
<P>which forces Ohio to become the disposal site not only
for its own radioactive </P>
<P>wastes but also that of five other states: Minnesota,
Missouri, Iowa, Wisconsin </P>
<P>and Indiana.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>Most (98% of the radioactivity) of the so-called
low-level radioactive wastes </P>
<P>are produced by the ten nuclear power plants in these
Midwest Compact States. </P>
<P>Some of these wastes are tainted with plutonium, one of
the deadliest materials </P>
<P>known. All are extremely hazardous to life. Many
substances in these wastes </P>
<P>remain radioactive for thousands of years, yet the law
requires monitoring for </P>
<P>only 500 years.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>The Senate Bill requires Ohio to take these radioactive
wastes for 20 years or </P>
<P>until a limit of 2.25 million cubic feet of wastes is
reached. Should the time </P>
<P>expire or the capacity be reached, the decision can be
made without citizen vote </P>
<P>to extend both limits. No community is exempt from being
considered as the final </P>
<P>site for the Midwest Compact's Low-Level Radioactive
Waste Disposal Facility. </P>
<P>Many Ohio communities will be endangered by the
transportation of these wastes </P>
<P>on our highways and railways.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<H3> Citizens Respond by Organizing</H3>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>Driven by concerns for the health of our families and
communities, the health of </P>
<P>the environment, and the safety of travelers sharing the
highways, Ohioans have </P>
<P>formed a citizens' advocacy group. </P>
<P>This alliance, Citizens Protecting Ohio, has developed an
Initiative Petition to </P>
<P>place a Constitutional Amendment on the ballot to prevent
the storage or </P>
<P>disposal of out-of-state radioactive wastes in Ohio. The
Amendment also states </P>
<P>that all Ohio wastes must be stored or disposed of in a
manner that prevents </P>
<P>any contamination of the environment. It further requires
that generators of </P>
<P>the radioactive wastes, not the taxpayers, take financial
responsibility for </P>
<P>the storage or disposal of those wastes. The Amendment
allows for the storage </P>
<P>of wastes for medical treatment and other scientific
uses.</P>
<P>Citizens working together across Ohio can prevail over
the clamor of nuclear </P>
<P>special interests.</P>
<P>Radiation exposure causes cancer, birth defects and
weakened </P>
<P>immunity. </P>
<P>Call: Citizens Protecting Ohio: 614-294-8206 Fax
614-291-3276;</P>
<P>or in your area at: 614-448-3343; 513-836-3331;
216-932-2109; 216-631-0557</P>
<P> <BR>
 </P>
<H3>TEXT OF THE PROPOSED CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT</H3>
<P><BR>
Paragraph (A). <B>OHIO SHALL NOT SERVE AS A HOST STATE
OR A SITE</B></P>
<P><B>FOR STORAGE OR DISPOSAL OF RADIOACTIVE WASTES FROM</B></P>
<P><B>OUTSIDE THE STATE OF OHIO, INCLUDING WASTES WHOSE </B></P>
<P><B>RADIOACTIVITY IS PRODUCED AND USED OUTSIDE OF OHIO.</B></P>
<P>Paragraph (B).<B> IN ORDER TO PROTECT THE PEOPLE'S RIGHT TO
A </B></P>
<P><B>HEALTHFUL AND SAFE ENVIRONMENT FREE FROM RADIOACTIVE</B></P>
<P><B>
CONTAMINATION, IT IS THE POLICY OF THE STATE OF OHIO THAT</B></P>
<P><B>RADIOACTIVE WASTES MUST BE SAFELY STORED AND DISPOSED</B></P>
<P><B>OF IN SUCH A MANNER AS TO PREVENT ANY CONTAMINATION </B></P>
<P><B>OF AIR, SOIL OR WATER.</B></P>
<P>Paragraph (C). <B>RADIOACTIVE WASTES RESULTING FROM
MEDICAL</B></P>
<P><B>DIAGNOSIS OR TREATMENT OR BIOLOGICAL OR EARTH SCIENCE</B></P>
<P><B>RESEARCH ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED WITHIN OHIO MAY BE </B></P>
<P><B>STORED IN LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITIES WHICH OHIO HAS THE
</B></P>
<P><B>AUTHORITY TO REGULATE AND WHICH COMPLY WITH</B></P>
<P><B>PARAGRAPH B OF THIS AMENDMENT.</B></P>
<P>Paragraph (D). <B>THE FINANCIAL RESPONSIBILITY FOR STORING
AND </B></P>
<P><B>DISPOSING OF RADIOACTIVE WASTES SHALL REMAIN WITH THE
</B></P>
<P><B>GENERATORS OF THE WASTES.</B></P>
<P>Paragraph (E).<B> IN THE EVENT THAT ANY PROVISION OF THIS
</B></P>
<P><B>AMENDMENT IS DECLARED BY A COURT TO BE INVALID, SUCH </B></P>
<P><B>DECLARATION SHALL NOT AFFECT THE VALIDITY OF THE </B></P>
<P><B>REMAINING PROVISIONS.</B></P>
<P><BR>
This original document was Paid for by<CITE> Citizens
Protecting Ohio Against a </CITE></P>
<P><CITE>Six-State Radioactive Waste Dump, Margaret B. Grey,</CITE>
Treasurer, 3119 Essex </P>
<P>Rd, Cleveland Heights, Ohio, 44118.</P>
<P>Paid for by Citizens Protecting Ohio Against a Six-State
Radioactive Waste </P>
<P>Dump, Margaret B Grey. Treasurer, 3119 Essex Rd ,
Cleveland Heights, OH</P>
<P>44118<BR>
</P>
