<head>
<title>JCARR's four reasons</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>The Four Reasons JCARR May 
Recommend the Invalidation of a Rule:</h1>
<hr>
<p>1.	The rule exceeds the scope of the agency's <strong>statutory authority</strong> to make rules;</p>
<p>2.	The rule conflicts with the <strong>intent of the legislature</strong> in enacting the statute under which the rule 
is proposed;</p>
<p>3.	The rules <strong>conflict with another rule </strong>of that agency or a different rule-making agency; and,</p>
<p>4.	The agency has not proposed a<strong> complete and accurate rule summary and fiscal analysis </strong>of 
the proposed rule.</p>
<p>Also due to S.B. 33, if the rule summary and fiscal analysis is inadequate and those rules have a 
fiscal impact on school districts, counties, townships, or municipal corporations then, JCARR may 
<strong>on a one-time basis</strong> order an agency to revise the rule summary and fiscal analysis and re-file the 
rule at a later date.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
