<body>
<h1 align=center>CITIZEN ACTION'S</h1>
<h1 align=center>CONSUMER WATCH</h1>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>Chemicals may pollute groundwater in Brownfields Cleanup </h3>
<hr>
<p>By Laura Yeomans<br>
P.O. BOX 8 <br>
Dover, OH 44622-4008<br>
</p>
<p>By Laura Yeomans, Citizen Action Research Director</p>
<p>Ohio EPA is asking for comments from the public on proposed rules for the cleanup of 
Brownfields sites, which are abandoned properties polluted by past industrial use, Under 
the program established by a new state law passed in 1994, companies will be able to 
clean up polluted properties voluntarily, In exchange, Ohio EPA will promise not to sue 
these companies. </p>
<p>The new rules should be changed because they will allow companies to leave pollution on 
properties that could pollute groundwater and present health problems for local residents 
and workers on site </p>
<p>&quot;Groundwater is not going to get cleaned up under this program, &quot; said Marilyn Wall, clean 
water coordinator for the Ohio Sierra Club. Wall served on an Ohio EPA groundwater 
subcommittee writing the Brownfields proposed rules. &quot;They have created loopholes with 
urban settings and loopholes with risk assessment. &quot; </p>
<p>Under the proposed program, a company could ask to have an &quot;urban setting designation&quot; 
for a polluted property, This is a label based on the number of people who depend on the 
groundwater at the site for drinking water. An urban setting designation would mean that 
the company will not have to clean up pollution contaminating groundwater. </p>
<p>In the past, all groundwater resources in Ohio had to be treated as precious resources that 
might some day be used for drinking water. Contamination had to be cleaned up. The 
urban setting designation is part of a new system where certain groundwater resources will 
no longer be protected from pollution. </p>
<p>Wall expressed concern that companies will not have to notify neighbors that a plume of 
chemical contamination is streaming their way and may contaminate their drinking water. </p>
<p>&quot;The industrial faction on the advisory committee didn't want to notify people that a plume 
may be headed in their direction. Companies plan to clean up contamination on site to 
whatever level they choose, &quot; Wall said. &quot;Because of the secrecy provisions of the 
program, the nearby property owner may never know that their property may be 
contaminated. If they do find out, they may not be able to prove where the pollution came 
from, because there is no public record showing pollution found at the Brownfields site. &quot; </p>
<p>Twenty-four Ohio EPA staff people wrote a letter to Ohio EPA iDirector Donald 
Schregardus stating that the volunteer company cleaning up a site &quot;maybe inclined to make 
an `Urban setting' determination based on the best interests of the Volunteer, but not 
necessarily on the best interests of the community or the future economic viability of the 
area. &quot; They recommended, &quot;It is essential that the public be allowed to voice their 
objections or approval when a property is scheduled to receive this designation. &quot; </p>
<p>&quot;Communities have been working to protect groundwater and develop wellfield protection 
programs over the last ten years. This urban setting designation and these Brownfields rules 
will turn back the clock, &quot; said Jane Forrest, a member of the Browntields advisory 
committee and environmental projects director for Citizen Action. </p>
<p>The 24 Ohio EPA staff also urged the director to improve the risk management plan for 
Brownfields sites, saying &quot;.. .The higher risk levels being proposed may result in inadequate 
protection of human health and the environment. &quot;</p>
<p>Jeff Fisher is a toxicologist from the Dayton area. &quot;From a scientific point of view, we don't 
know what the effects of low level contamination are on the human population, &quot; Fisher 
said. The Brownfields program allows companies to leave pollution on site that may cause 
cancer at a level of one cancer per 100,000 people exposed. Many programs use one in a 
million as the risk reduction goal. </p>
<p>&quot;Are people willing to live with levels of contamination that are higher by a factor often?&quot; 
Fisher said, &quot;In the real world, there will be multiple chemicals in the soil. Because the 
Brownfields plans don't address groundwater and don't address mixtures of chemicals, the 
standards will not be very useful. The public needs to get involved and decide what they 
think is appropriate. &quot; </p>
<h5>Laura Yeomans is the research director for Citizen Action. Write to her at P. O. Box 8, Dover, OH 
44622-0008. Please include your phone number and a self addressed stamped envelope.<br>
</h5>
<h5>1995 Laura Yeoman's Permission is granted to newspapers to reprint this column if Yeomans is 
given the byline and is identified as the research director of Citizen Action.<br>
</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</h5>
</body>

