<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B34-168</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA047-000828-B025-225</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.greenlink.org:80/radwaste/rad2.html 206.86.202.14 19970119091851 text/html 19870
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 09:46:33 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 19698
Last-modified: Wed, 21 Aug 1996 15:57:34 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Testimony of Robert M. Soderstrom,
MD</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">Testimony of Robert M. Soderstrom, MD</H2>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
</H2>
</CENTER>I am very pleased to be invited on behalf of the Genesee
County Medical Society 
<P>of Flint, Michigan, to testify on the issue of so-called
low-level radioactive </P>
<P>waste disposal in Ohio. (The Genesee County Medical
Society appointed an </P>
<P>Environmental Health Committee, which I chaired, in the
fall of 1989, and one of </P>
<P>the committee's first actions was to review the issue of
radioactive waste </P>
<P>disposal.) In November 1989, the Board of the Genesee
County Medical Society </P>
<P>unanimously adopted a position in opposition to such a
site in Michigan. Our </P>
<P>reasons were several and were originally outlined in an
article we published in </P>
<P>the July 1990 issue of Michigan Medicine, the official
publication of the </P>
<P>Michigan State Medical Society. The Genesee County
Medical Society is made up of </P>
<P>the 500+ practicing physicians in Genesee County and our
purpose in focusing on </P>
<P>this issue is the preservation of the environment and the
protection of the </P>
<P>public's health. The reasons for our opposition are
several.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>The terminology of the Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Compact is misleading and </P>
<P>confusing. The average person, seeing the title, assumes
that the radiation </P>
<P>levels of the waste to be stored by the Compact are
&quot;low-level&quot; and therefore of </P>
<P>no significant health concern. Nothing could be further
from the truth.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>When one speaks of biologically low levels of radiation
exposure one might be </P>
<P>speaking of the radiation in some medically diagnostic
x-rays, perhaps half a </P>
<P>rad (the rad being a unit of measurement of radiation).
When the Nuclear </P>
<P>Regulatory Commission speaks of &quot;low-level&quot;
waste they mean all that waste from </P>
<P>a nuclear power plant that emits &quot;low-levels&quot;
of radiation in comparison to the </P>
<P>very highly radioactive nuclear fuel itself. Thus, by
their definition, a </P>
<P>non-fuel reactor component emitting 1000 rads/hour is
&quot;low-level&quot; for it is not </P>
<P>a high-level fuel component. However, if 500 rads/hour is
enough to kill a </P>
<P>person, and it is, then 1000 rads/hour is biologically
high-level radiation </P>
<P>indeed! It is critical to the current debate over
&quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste </P>
<P>disposal to understand this crucial difference in the use
of the term </P>
<P>&quot;low-level&quot;. &quot;Low-level&quot; in Nuclear
Regulatory Commission terminology means only </P>
<P>that the waste to be sent to Ohio is not the very highly
radioac!</P>
<P>tive nuclear fuel itself. However, virtually everything
else from a nuclear </P>
<P>power plant can be sent here and much of it is highly
radioactive, long-lived, </P>
<P>and certainly a significant public health threat. Highly
radioactive products </P>
<P>that therefore qualify for a &quot;low-level&quot; waste
dump include components of the </P>
<P>nuclear reactor itself, filters, filter sludges, and
various absorptive resins. </P>
<P>It is this material that constitutes the great majority
of the radioactivity to </P>
<P>be placed in such a dump. While medical radioactive waste
for the most part has </P>
<P>half-lives of minutes, hours, and days, the radioactive
materials from nuclear </P>
<P>power plants have half-lives of tens and hundreds of
years.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>To be more specific, let me list the major isotopes used
in medical diagnosis </P>
<P>and therapy. It is a general rule of thumb that one
should multiply the </P>
<P>half-life of a radioactive product by approximately 10-20
to determine the time </P>
<P>it takes for it to decay to a non-detectable level. Some
of the major isotopes </P>
<P>used in medical diagnosis and therapy are technetium-99m
with a half-life of 6 </P>
<P>hours, gallium-67 with a half-life of 78 hours,
thallium-201 - 73 hours, xenon- </P>
<P>133 - 5 days, indium-ill - 2.8 days, Iodine-123 - 13
hours, 1-125 - 60 days, I- </P>
<P>131 - 8 days, chromium-Si - 28 days, and phosphorus-32 -
14 days. On the other </P>
<P>hand, one of the most common radioactive waste
contaminants from a nuclear power </P>
<P>plant is cesium- 137 with a half-life of 30 years years,
requiring 300 years or </P>
<P>more to decay. Other radioactive waste products include
strontium-90 with a </P>
<P>half-life of nearly 30 years and even some nickel-59 with
a half-life of 80,000 </P>
<P>years and neptunium-237 with a half-life of 2,000,000
years.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>To further demonstrate the immense discrepancy involved
one only needs to look </P>
<P>at the Rogers and Associates Engineering Corporation
study completed for the </P>
<P>Midwest Compact. The study characterized the
radioactivity of the materials to </P>
<P>be stored by the Compact. The study stated that over 20
years utilities will be </P>
<P>disposing of 207,000 curies of radioactive waste in the
dump</P>
<P>site, 84% of the total. Medical sources, however, will
account for only 130 </P>
<P>curies medical waste therefore making up just 0.05% of
the total curies </P>
<P>disposed. Even more importantly, the study showed that
Class A radioactive </P>
<P>waste, which is the least concentrated, constitutes only
20% of the waste coming </P>
<P>from utilities while it makes up 90% of the waste coming
from all other sources </P>
<P>and virtually all of the waste to come from medical
diagnostics, therapeutics, </P>
<P>and research. On the other hand, Class C waste, which is
highly concentrated and </P>
<P>very toxic, constitutes 42% of the radioactive waste
utilities want to put in </P>
<P>&quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste sites.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>It becomes apparent, then, that the debate should not
focus on the very small </P>
<P>contribution of radioactive waste that medicine will make
to such a dump site. </P>
<P>Nor should the need to dispose of short-lived radioactive
materials from </P>
<P>medicine and research serve as a cover for the very, very
different kinds of </P>
<P>radioactive materials utilities want to put in such a
site. Rather, the debate </P>
<P>should focus on the immense amount of long-lived
radioactive materials that </P>
<P>utilities want to call &quot;low-level&quot; in
comparison to their very highly </P>
<P>radioactive nuclear fuel.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>Two of these isotopes from power plants are of real
public health concern, </P>
<P>especially in the first 100 years or so. Cesium- 137 is
very biologically </P>
<P>active, being concentrated from soil and water by plants
and from plants by </P>
<P>plant-eating animals and it therefore represents a
significant threat to the </P>
<P>food chain. It is greatly biomagnified, meaning that it
occurs in greater </P>
<P>concentration in animals higher in the food chain. It was
cesium-137 that was </P>
<P>responsible for the destruction of the reindeer herds in
Scandinavia and the </P>
<P>sheep herds in England following the Chernobyl disaster.
Cesium- 137 has now </P>
<P>been confirmed in great concentration in many fish in
Swedish lakes and in some </P>
<P>areas fishing will not be safe for decades. Cesium-137 is
a major nuclear </P>
<P>reactor contaminant. As previously mentioned, it has a
half-life of 30 years and </P>
<P>requires 300 years to decay to insignificant levels.
Strontium-90 is another </P>
<P>isotope with food-chain implications. Strontium-90,
ingested from gro!</P>
<P>und contamination, is excreted in cow 5 milk and is thus
ingested by human </P>
<P>beings. Strontium-90 also has a 300 year decay
requirement. Either one of these </P>
<P>isotopes, escaping into the environment through land,
water, or air </P>
<P>contamination, represents a significant public health
threat.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>The experience with zinc-65 is a good example of what can
happen when a </P>
<P>radioactive element is biomagnified in the food chain.
During the 1950's and </P>
<P>1960's, coolant water from the Columbia River was
routinely passed through the </P>
<P>nuclear reactors at Hanford, Washington and returned to
the river. The river </P>
<P>water was thereby contaminated with some short-lived
radioactive corrosion </P>
<P>products. One of the Hanford workers was found to have
detectable amounts of </P>
<P>zinc-65 in his tissues as a result of having eaten
contaminated oysters from an </P>
<P>ocean bay on the Washington coast some 200 miles from
Hanford and 30 miles north </P>
<P>of the Columbia River's mouth. The zinc-65, which has a
half-life of about eight </P>
<P>months, was entering the river in the effluent from the
Hanford reactors, then </P>
<P>being carried some 360 river miles to the Pacific where
ocean currents carried </P>
<P>it northward into the bay in extremely minute
concentrations. Oysters, however, </P>
<P>are filter-feeders with a particular chemical affinity
for either stable or radioactive</P>
<P> zinc, and they were concentrating the </P>
<P>zinc-65 at 200,000 times its concentration in the
seawater.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>The health risks of exposure to low-levels of radiation
are well-documented. It </P>
<P>is a complicated and extensive topic and I am only
touching upon it here, but </P>
<P>suffice it to say that in December 1989, the National
Academy of Sciences </P>
<P>published the BEIR V report, &quot;Health Effects of
Exposure to Low Levels of </P>
<P>Ionizing Radiation&quot;. On page six of the report it
says this, quote, &quot;The cancer </P>
<P>risk estimates used in this report are about 3 times
larger for solid cancers </P>
<P>and about four times larger for leukemia than the risk
estimates presented 10 </P>
<P>years earlier. These differences result from a number of
factors, including new </P>
<P>risk models, revised A-bomb dosimetry, and more extended
follow-up of A-bomb </P>
<P>survivors.&quot; It also says, on the same page,
&quot;the risk of exposure in childhood </P>
<P>to radiation is estimated to be about twice as large as
the risk for adults.&quot; </P>
<P>Obviously, this well-documented and extensive national
study demonstrates a </P>
<P>major change in risk estimates for low-level radiation
exposures and the human </P>
<P>organism. Unlike so many other toxics where the risk of
cancer might be</P>
<P>theoretical, the risk of cancers from s~called low-level
radiation exposures</P>
<P>is a definite one.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>We have other concerns about the radioactive waste
disposal site. The Nuclear </P>
<P>Regulatory Commission intends to license these surface
facilities for 100 years </P>
<P>even though they readily admit that such sites will be
radioactive far beyond </P>
<P>100 years, even beyond 500 years. Such a licensing policy
is not responsible. We </P>
<P>feel strongly that if the license is for only 100 years,
then the people of Ohio </P>
<P>should at least be assured that all the radioactivity
will have dissipated by </P>
<P>100 years.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>The site is to close after accepting radioactive waste
from 10 or more </P>
<P>midwestern power plants over a period of 20 years. The
waste management</P>
<P>company will remain on site for five more years and then
leave. Ownership of </P>
<P>and liability for the site then reverts to the people of
the state of Ohio and any </P>
<P>problems that occur at the site after will belong to the
people of Ohio to </P>
<P>solve. Those who have generated the radioactive waste --
those very groups who </P>
<P>are assuring you right now that these sites will not leak
over hundreds of years </P>
<P>-- will be gone from the place, lock, stock, and barrel
in 25 years.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>In 1981, the Environmental Protection Agency published
this statement: &quot;At the </P>
<P>present time, it is not technologically and
institutionally possible to contain </P>
<P>wastes forever or for the long time periods that may be
necessary to allow </P>
<P>adequate degradation to be achieved. Consequently, the
regulation of hazardous </P>
<P>waste land disposal must proceed from the assumption that
migration of hazardous </P>
<P>wastes and their by-products from a land disposal
facility will inevitably </P>
<P>occur.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>In February 1991, the Congressional Office of Technology
Assessment published </P>
<P>its study which focused on the problems inherent in
cleaning up the many </P>
<P>contaminated radioactive waste sites that already exist
around the country, some </P>
<P>of which, as you know, are in Ohio. It said, and I quote,
&quot;It may be impossible </P>
<P>with current technology to remove contaminants from
ground water and deeply </P>
<P>buried soils near many of the installations.&quot;</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>What we have, then, is the Environmental Protection
Agency telling us, on the </P>
<P>one hand, that such a radioactive site is bound to leak
sooner or later, and , </P>
<P>on the other hand, we have the Office of Technological
Assessment telling us </P>
<P>that when it does leak we have no proven way of cleaning
it up.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>It needs to be noted that several nations with major
nuclear programs already </P>
<P>have decided against the use of surface facilities for
so-called low4evel </P>
<P>radioactive waste. Great Britain, West Germany, and
Sweden have officially </P>
<P>stated that only deep geological repositories are
acceptable sites for </P>
<P>radioactive waste of the type the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission wants to put in </P>
<P>an Ohio landfill facility. L. J. Carter, author of
Nuclear Imperatives and </P>
<P>Public Trust, says, on page 367, discussing radioactive
waste surface disposal </P>
<P>facilities, &quot;Although such a disposal method is
consistent with those now </P>
<P>favored in the United States, it compares poorly with the
much more robust </P>
<P>solutions for low-level waste isolation adopted by the
Germans and the Swedes.&quot;</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>While there have been many problems associated with the
previously failed </P>
<P>efforts to store radioactive waste, the major culprit has
been water. It is </P>
<P>water that eventually seeps into storage vaults. It is
water that corrodes </P>
<P>storage containers and casks. It is water that carries
radionuclides off site. </P>
<P>Ohio is a water-rich state with a high water table. It is
criss-crossed by </P>
<P>streams and has a long Great Lakes shoreline. No place in
the United States has </P>
<P>stored radioactive waste without ground or water
contamination for, even 20 </P>
<P>years, let alone 25, 50, 100, or 500 years. Ohio has had
its own experience with </P>
<P>this sorry circumstance. The infamous Fernald site is the
nation's third largest </P>
<P>radioactive waste dump and it has, of course, leaked.
Private drinking wells </P>
<P>south of the Fernald site have had some radiation
readings as much as 250 times </P>
<P>greater than maximum levels set by the EPA. Surface
waters which drain into the </P>
<P>Great Miami River have also been contaminated.
Monitori!</P>
<P>ng has revealed that groundwater has been contaminated
near radioactive</P>
<P>waste burial sites at the Portsmouth, Ohio uranium
enrichment complex. At the </P>
<P>Mound Laboratory near Dayton contaminafion of water
supplies with radioactive </P>
<P>tritium has been a problem.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>I am not suggesting that any of this contamination
occurred purposely. I'm sure </P>
<P>it did not, but it underlines the extreme difficulty
faced when one speaks of </P>
<P>storing radioactive waste for hundreds of years in a
water-logged environment. </P>
<P>I'm sure that in each of these cases the state of Ohio
was assured that leakage </P>
<P>would not be a problem and yet each site today represents
an environmental </P>
<P>catastrophe with complex and costly clean-up problems.
Now the state of Ohio is </P>
<P>being asked to establish yet another radioactive waste
dump site. Now the state </P>
<P>of Ohio is once again being assured that all the problems
associated with </P>
<P>storing radioactive waste over hundreds of years have
been solved. The Genesee </P>
<P>County Medical Society would advise extreme caution in
the face of these </P>
<P>assertions.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>So what do we think should be done? We would ask the
state of Ohio not to </P>
<P>proceed with siting a new dump under the faulty 1980
federal legislation. </P>
<P>Rather, we would ask that Ohio join Michigan and other
states in returning to </P>
<P>Congress and asking for more sensible legislation,
legislation which recognizes </P>
<P>the threat these isotopes represent to the environment
and to human health. The </P>
<P>1980 &quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste legislation
was passed by the U.S. Senate in </P>
<P>a flurry of bills before the Christmas recess of that
year. The Congressional </P>
<P>Record shows that Senators were assured the dump sites
would not include </P>
<P>radioactive materials from nuclear power plants! Perhaps
we should insist upon </P>
<P>reviving that assurance and craft some new national
legislation.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>We should propose that the very short-lived radioactive
waste from universities, </P>
<P>research laboratories, and medicine be uncoupled from the
much more long-lived </P>
<P>waste held by nuclear power plants. Since the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission has </P>
<P>stated that disposal sites developed by state compacts
will be licensed for 100 </P>
<P>years, we would suggest that the federal legislation be
amended to state that no </P>
<P>waste can be placed in these sites which would still be
radioactive after 100 </P>
<P>years. Such a change would allow these compact sites to
accept truly low-level </P>
<P>radioactive waste from universities and research centers
and at the same time </P>
<P>this change would eliminate the possibility of storing
much longer-lived waste </P>
<P>at such sites. Waste which would still be radioactive
after 100 years would be </P>
<P>re-classified as &quot;high-level&quot; waste and would
require the greater control and </P>
<P>isolation placed on other high level radioactive
wastes.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>In our opinion, this single change would do much to
resolve the current </P>
<P>controversy. We are very appreciative of the opportunity
to present our position </P>
<P>today. Thank you.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P><CITE>Robert M. Soderstrom, M.D.</CITE></P>
<P>Chairman, Environmental Health Committee</P>
<P>Genesee County Medical Society</P>
<P>806 Tuuri Place</P>
<P>Flint,MI 48503</P>
<P>April 7, 1992</P>
<P><BR>
 This article, &quot;Testimony by Dr.
Soderstrom,&quot; is supplied by Dr. Velma M. </P>
<P>Shearer, a member of C-PRO (Citizens Protecting Ohio),
513-83&amp;333 1.</P>
