<head>
<title>Untitled</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p><br>
<font size=2>Date: August 28, 1996<br>
<br>
To: Records Management Officer<br>
Ohio EPA<br>
DERR-VAP<br>
P.O. Box 1049<br>
Columbus, OH 43216-1049<br>
<br>
Fr: Greene Environmental Coalition<br>
Box 266<br>
Yellow Springs, OH 45387<br>
<br>
Contact: Bruce Cornett, 513-767-2109, AM; 513-767-5000, PM.<br>
<br>
Re: Comments on Second Wave Rules, Voluntary Action Program<br>
<br>
We regard the Voluntary Action Program (Brownfields), to be of vital interest to the people of Ohio, in 
terms of its environmental and economic consequences and possibilities. The Greene Environmental 
Coalition therefore welcomes the opportunity to comment in open forum on these important rules that 
set forth the implementation requirements of the program. We support the effort to bring as many 
stakeholders as possible together in the preparation and revision of these rules. If environmental 
equity is to be achieved, the Agency must continue to enlarge its effort to bring representatives of the 
public interest into the legislative and rule-making process. While this process is not an easy one, for it 
is usually much more difficult economically for representatives of the public and for environmental 
groups to participate than it is for business interests, we commend the Agency for its effort in this rule 
development process. While certainly a learning process for all involved, and a process with 
significant group process challenges remaining, it does represent a step forward in bringing true citizen 
participation onto the playing field.<br>
<br>
The Coalition believes that the process has resulted in the development of rules that are generally 
protective of the environment in many areas. However, we do have concerns in several areas which we 
feel remain unaddressed in the rule package and that adversely affect the assurance of environmental 
integrity in our State. We have particular concerns in the area of ground water protection, as well as in 
other areas, some of which we will address below. <br>
<br>
<br>
<em>3745-300-01 Definitions</em><br>
<br>
Concern: No reference is made to urban setting in the main definitions chapter. Urban setting 
designation is a crucial concept in the Brownfields program and should be clearly defined as early as 
possible in the rule package.<br>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Include definition of urban setting in the definitions chapter.</strong><br>
<br>
<em><br>
3745-300-02 Eligibility for Participating in the Voluntary Action Program. (Corrected version to be 
refiled with JCARR); Subparagraph D(6), pp.10+. <br>
</em><br>
Concern: The two-year default eligibility provision for the VAP program for properties receiving an 
enforcement letter is not sufficiently protective of the environment. It provides a back-door opening for 
sites that have serious problems which should be cleaned up. Our reading does not detect any 
provision for property owner response to the receipt of an enforcement letter. We feel that all the 
responsibility for follow-up lies with the OEPA, none with the owner. This is unacceptable 
environmental policy.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Establish an owner response requirement within a specific time period upon the 
issuance of an enforcement letter. Otherwise the default eligibility provision should be null and void.<br>
</strong><br>
<br>
<em>3745-300-03 Certified Professionals</em><br>
<br>
Concern: It is unclear if there is any promised or implied immunity from tort liability for certified 
professionals in the proposed rules. Full tort liability for professional error must exist.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Clarify the rule to include full tort liability.</strong><br>
<br>
<br>
<em>3745-300-09 Property-Specific Risk Assessment Procedures; Subparagraph (C), (1), (a), (i), p. 10.</em><br>
<br>
Concern: The Coalition believes that the carcinogenic risk of one in 10,000, or 10(-4), for industrial 
property is less than federal standards call for, even considering the provision for off-property 
receptors. We believe that risk requirements should meet federal standards.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Make sure that risk requirements at a minimum meet Federal standards.<br>
</strong><br>
<br>
<em>3745-300-10 Ground Water Classification and Response Requirements</em><br>
<br>
Introductory Comments: Next to the air we breathe, ground water, particularly that designated for 
drinking water purposes, is our most precious environmental resource. Preserving the quality of our 
drinking water must be a primary concern of all stakeholders in the program. We believe, therefore, that 
assuring the purity of current or potential drinking water sources must be of the highest priority in 
developing VAP rules.<br>
<br>
Concern 1: The Coalition believes that the proposed rules create a disproportionate negative impact for 
those persons living in areas designated urban settings. In particular the one-half mile limit for which 
ground water integrity must be assured in urban settings is not reflective of the realities which exist in 
these areas. In some cases the one-half mile limit may work fine. In other cases, it will almost certainly 
open the door for abuse and threat to persons living in the area. This provision appears to be 
consistent with an effort to tie the Agency's hands with finite limits. We find this is this case to be 
unacceptable.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Rework the one-half mile limit provision to provide the Agency sufficient flexibility 
to protect the drinking water resources of those persons who might be affected now or in the future. 
We believe in responsible clean-up enticements, but not those which arbitrarily endanger water 
safety.<br>
</strong><br>
<br>
Concern 2: Subparagraph (E) Urban Setting Designation Criteria and Process, (1) (c), p. 8<br>
<br>
The provision which waives the wellhead protection requirement if the wellhead owner consents in 
writing is too subject to political pressure. The public is not sufficiently protected.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Remove the waiver provision.</strong><br>
<br>
<br>
Concern 3: Subparagraph (E) (1) (e) (iii), p. 9.<br>
<br>
The provision that not less than ninety percent of the area within one-half mile of the property is 
connected to a community water system is unclear. Does this represent ninety percent of existing 
households or total area or what? And what about the remaining ten percent that is not connected? 
And what about the area beyond the one-half mile limit?<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Clarify the language in the rule and ensure that no one living in the area nor any 
sole source aquifer that extends beyond the one-half mile limit would be subject to increased risk of 
potable water contamination.<br>
</strong><br>
<br>
Concern 4: Subparagraph (E) (2) (b), p. 11<br>
<br>
No requirement exists for a legislative body to reply to the Director's notice that an urban setting 
designation is under consideration. And without a requirement for a public meeting or other public 
input, it is possible that an urban designation could be obtained by default. <br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Strengthen the public input provisions in all cases in which urban setting 
designation is being contemplated. <br>
</strong><br>
<br>
Concern 5: Subparagraph (E) (2) (c) and (d), p.13.<br>
<br>
The requirement in these two subparagraphs that limits public hearings to the Director's discretion is 
not sufficiently protective of the public interest. <br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Require a public hearing </strong><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<em>3745-300-13 Content and Scope of No Further Action Letters</em><br>
<br>
Concern 1: (A) (1) p.1.<br>
<br>
This provision provides for the possibility of an &quot;immaculate conception&quot; of a hazardous waste release 
after the no furhter action letter has been issued. Does this get the Certified Professional off the hook, 
so to speak?<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Clarify this language early on in the chapter</strong><br>
<br>
<br>
Concern 2: (E) (4), p. 2.<br>
<br>
The removal of the Ohio Revised Code as the highest regulatory source provides an inappropriate 
standard of assurance to the public.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Restore the ORC as the primary regulatory source. </strong><br>
<br>
<br>
<em>3745-300-15 Remediation</em><br>
<br>
Concern 1 Subparagraph (D) (1)<br>
<br>
We feel that the five year time frame for attaining applicable standards is too long.<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Reduce the time frame to three years</strong><br>
<br>
<br>
Concern 2 Subparagraph (F) (1)<br>
<br>
It is not clear who is the responsible party. Is it the owner or the volunteer?<br>
<br>
<strong>Recommendation: Clarify the responsibility issue. </strong><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</font><br>
</p>
</body>

