<HEAD>
<TITLE>Twenty
in 2000</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>&quot;TWENTY IN 2000&quot;</H1>
</CENTER>
<P>Twenty in 2000 is a Rivers Unlimited campaign
designed to double the number of rivers in the Ohio Scenic
River Program. There are currently 18 segments of 10 rivers
(a total of 641 miles) that have scenic river status. The
goal of this project is to add ten more rivers to the system
by the year 2000, along with funding for staff to handle the
system's expansion.</P>
<P>The process of designating a river generates
community awareness of the economic, recreational, and
environmental benefits of the stream, and serves as a
reminder of the waterway's value. In addition, any public
projects that affect scenic rivers must be approved in
advance by the Division of Natural Areas.</P>
<P> Although Ohio's Scenic Rivers Program was proactive
during its founding decade of the 1970s, no waterways have
been added since 1984. Many of the streams that qualify are
facing threats and could clearly benefit from
designation.</P>
<P> The Scenic Rivers Program has identified 44 waterways
that meet the basic criteria for designation. Rivers
Unlimited is working with both the Program and with river
advocates across the state to identify the most likely
candidates for addition. Already, two streams are being
studied to determine if they qualify for a scenic river
designation--the Black River in Lorain County and the
Kokosing River in Knox County.</P>
<P> The Ohio Scenic River System consists of the following
ten waterways, along with the length and year the waterway
was designated:</P>
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Little Miami River 105 miles 1969 and
1971</LI>
<LI>Sandusky River 65 miles 1970</LI>
<LI>Olentangy River 22 miles 1973</LI>
<LI>Little Beaver Creek 36 miles 1974</LI>
<LI>Grand River 56 miles 1974</LI>
<LI>Upper Cuyahoga River 25 miles 1974</LI>
<LI>Maumee River 96 miles 1974</LI>
<LI>Stillwater River System 93 miles 1975, 1980, and
1982</LI>
<LI>Chagrin River 49 miles 1979</LI>
<LI>Big and Little Darby Creeks 84 miles 1984</LI>
</UL>
<P> <BR>
 </P>


