<body>
<h1 align=center>CITIZEN ACTION'S</h1>
<h1 align=center>CONSUMER WATCH</h1>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>How clean is clean for abandoned sites?</h3>
<hr>
<p>By Laura Yeomans<br>
P.O. BOX 8 <br>
Dover, OH 44622-4008<br>
</p>
<p>By Laura Yeomans, Citizen Action Research Director<br>
</p>
<p>Neighbors may inhale some of the airborne chemicals that drift from abandoned industrial 
properties found throughout Ohio. Children who climb the fence may absorb the 
cancer-causing chemicals through their skin. Some chemicals seep into the ground 
contaminating water resources used for drinking water.<br>
</p>
<p>In 1994 the Ohio legislature passed a law designed to encourage redevelopment of these 
abandoned Brownfield sites. Under the plan if a new property owner voluntarily cleans up 
the wastes on an abandoned site, Ohio EPA d promise not to sue them in the future. How 
clean should a site be before an owner can build a supermarket, apartment building, or new 
factory?<br>
</p>
<p>Who will cleanup chemicals left in the ground that may migrate into groundwater resources? 
Early in 1996 Ohio EPA will release proposed cleanup standards for abandoned sites, 
after listening to hours of presentations and arguments from an advisory committee of 
county end city government officials end industry and environmental representatives <br>
</p>
<p>In November, Ohio EPA Director Donald Schregardus recommended that cancer-causing 
wastes in abandoned sites be cleaned up to a level scientists estimate would allow no more 
than one additional cancer death for 100,000 neighbors exposed.<br>
</p>
<p>Jon Reid, a toxicologist from the University of Cincinnati Medical Center and an advisory 
committee member, wanted a higher cleanup standard, but is supporting Schregardus' 
cleanup standard. &quot;Ohio EPA doesn't have sufficient resources to treat all the Brownfields 
in the state,&quot; Reid said., &quot;They would just sit there idle until EPA could work with the 
owners to make sure the sites were cleaned up, The idea of this law is to expedite that part 
of the process without sacrificing the health of people in Ohio. In my opinion there is 
enough incentive here for owners to cleanup their sites and have a guarantee that Ohio EPA 
won't cause them to go back and dig up their soil again. &quot;<br>
</p>
<p>&quot;People are already exposed to a variety of cancer-causing chemicals in their communities. 
Another cancer-risk of one in 100,000 is an unacceptable level to add to workers and the 
communities,&quot; said Chris Trepal, co-director of the Earth Day Coalition. &quot;I'm most 
concerned with chemicals left on the site under asphalt or diluted and left on site. A one in a 
million standard for cumulative cancer risk would be more protective of workers health and 
the health of communities surrounding abandoned sites. &quot;<br>
</p>
<p>Several advisory committee members are urging a lower standard. &quot;We have two to three 
dozen Brownfield sites we would like to address in the Springfield area,&quot; said Matt Kridler, 
city manager of Springfield. &quot;We need a realistic [cleanup] goal, that is protective of human 
health that makes economic sense for developers to come forward and remediate their 
sites. As to this date, standards have been so high, so unrealistic, most developers will walk 
away. The end result is that agricultural land is destroyed,&quot; Kridler recommended a one in 
10,000 cancer risk cleanup level.<br>
</p>
<p>In a variety of programs, Ohio EPA uses risk levels that range from one in 10,000 to one in 
a million for allowable additional cancer risks. There are several reasons why .Ohio EPA 
should create high standards, such as one in a million cancer risk level, when setting generic 
standards for the Brownfields program. The Brownfields program will be conducted largely 
without oversight from the public or Ohio EPA. Firms hired by property owners will 
conduct site analysis and cleanup. Only one-fourth of cleanup projects will be audited by 
the agency. </p>
<p>The proposed generic cleanup standard will be used as a guide for the cleanup of industrial 
facilities that are in the middle of industrial parks miles from residential neighborhoods and 
those industrial facilities right next to residential housing. The generic standard must include 
protection for residential communities adjacent to abandoned sites. </p>
<p>There are a number of ways proposed in the rules to allow individual facilities to qualify for 
a lower cleanup standard. For information about the location of public hearings that will be 
held on the proposed cleanup standards March 4-14, write to <em><strong>Ohio EPA ATTN.: 
Brownfields Section, 1800 Watermark Drive, Columbus, Ohio 43215-1099.</strong></em><br>
</p>
<h5>Laura Yeomans is the research director for Citizen Action. Write to her at P. O. Box 8, Dover, OH 
44622-0008. Please include your phone number and a self addressed stamped envelope.<br>
</h5>
<h5>1995 Laura Yeoman's Permission is granted to newspapers to reprint this column if Yeomans is 
given the byline and is identified as the research director of Citizen Action.<br>
</h5>
</body>

