<p align="center"><font face="Arial"><b>Citizen Advisory</b></font></p>

<p align="center"><font face="Arial"><b><u>Ohio EPA Continues
Incinerator Moratorium</u></b></font></p>

<p><font face="Arial"><b></b></font>&nbsp;</p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font face="Arial">The State of Ohio will continue to
        prohibit issuing permits for new hazardous waste
        incinerators for three more years, according to a
        determination released today by Ohio EPA to comply with
        House Bill 604.</font></p>
        <p><font face="Arial"></font>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><font face="Arial">House Bill 604, passed by the
        General Assembly in 1993 at the request of Governor
        George V. Voinovich, prohibited Ohio EPA from issuing
        permits for new hazardous waste incinerators for three
        years. It requires the director of Ohio EPA to publish an
        assessment of commercial hazardous waste incinerator
        capacity every three years, beginning after April
        15,1996.</font></p>
        <p><font face="Arial"></font>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><font face="Arial">&quot;Our assessment shows there is
        minimal environmental impact from hazardous waste
        incinerators,&quot; said Ohio EPA Director Donald R.
        Schregardus. &quot;However, there is also plenty of
        capacity in Ohio and there appears to be a declining need
        for this kind of disposal technology.&quot;</font></p>
        <p><font face="Arial"></font>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><font face="Arial">Ohio EPA based its determination to
        extend the moratorium on several factors, including a
        capacity assessment that Ohio EPA released on June
        5,1996. The following six factors were also taken into
        consideration before a decision was made.</font></p>
        <p><font face="Arial"></font>&nbsp;</p>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p><font face="Symbol"></font><font
                face="Arial"> An evaluation to determine the
                state's capability to respond to the types and
                frequencies of releases of hazardous waste that
                are likely to occur at commercial hazardous waste
                incinerators;</font></p>
                <p><font face="Symbol"></font><font
                face="Arial"> The effect a new commercial
                hazardous waste incinerator may have on outdoor
                air quality;</font></p>
                <p><font face="Symbol"></font><font
                face="Arial"> A review of health studies, risk
                assessments and other impacts of commercial
                hazardous waste incinerators on human health and
                the environment;</font></p>
                <p><font face="Symbol"></font><font
                face="Arial"> A review of the operational records
                of commercial hazardous waste incinerators
                currently operating in Ohio;</font></p>
                <p><font face="Symbol"></font><font
                face="Arial"> The monetary and time commitments
                necessary to construct a new commercial hazardous
                waste incinerator, the amount of long-term
                capital investments available to fund the
                building of a commercial hazardous waste
                incinerator in Ohio, and hazardous waste
                generators' efforts to reduce the amount of
                hazardous waste generated that would be sent to
                commercial hazardous waste incinerators; and</font></p>
                <p><font face="Symbol"></font><font
                face="Arial"> Regulatory and legislative
                concerns.</font></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p align="center"><font face="Arial">George V. V~inovich,
Governor</font></p>

<p><font face="Arial"></font>&nbsp;</p>

<p align="center"><font face="Arial">~~ncy P. Hollister, Lt
Governor</font></p>

<p><font face="Arial">~n'Iec ~ Rape' Donaid R. Schregardus,
Director</font></p>

<p><font face="Arial">The capacity assessment showed that the
state's total authorized incineration capacity is 135,993 tons
per year. Ohio's two commercial hazardous waste incinerators are
expected to take in no more than 67,400 tons of waste per year.
The expected demand for hazardous waste incineration is based on
1993 annual reports by hazardous waste generators (the most
current information available when Ohio EPA began the
assessment), projected demand for hazardous waste incineration
capacity due to anticipated remediation activities of Superfund
sites and one-time cleanups.</font></p>

<p><font face="Arial"></font>&nbsp;</p>

<p><font face="Arial">Copies of the hazardous waste incinerator
capacity assessment and moratorium determination are available at
Ohio EPA's central office, and can be requested by contacting the
Division of Hazardous Waste Management, Ohio EPA, P.O. Box 1049,
Columbus, OH 43218-1049, or calling (614) 644~2917.</font></p>
</body>
