<head>
<title>Citizen Action - Dayton</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p><a href="http://www.greenlink.org/images/glnklogo.gif"><img src="glnklogo.gif" alt="GreenLink: wired for the
environment." align=top border=0></a> <br></p>
<hr>
<h1 align=center><br>
<b>OEPA Puts Public Health and 
Groundwater at Risk</b></h1>
<p align=center><font size=5>by Jane Forrest, Environmental Projects Director for 
Ohio Citizen Action<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2>The proposed rules by OEPA to clean up brownfield sites went too far. Even OEPA staff are not happy 
with how the rules are being proposed and environmental leaders are outraged. After 20 months of 
Steering Committee meetings and public meetings by OEPA, they have come up with rules that will 
undermine protection of groundwater, local government involvement, and lastly will not protect public 
health and the environment.<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2>We need to aggressively push OEPA to set a stringent clean up standard of 1 in 1,000,000 for all sites 
to protect workers, the community at large, and groundwater.<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2>Although OEPA has worked over the past ten years developing a groundwater strategy, pushed local 
governments to adopt wellfield protection and require that no new production wells be in a 
contaminated area. OEPA has developed a classification system that will undermine all of that work 
and commitment towards protecting groundwater.<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2>The OEPA must protect groundwater and should require clean up of the groundwater at 
non-detectable levels to protect future water resources for over 40% of the Ohioans that are dependent 
on it. In the case of co-mingled and off-site plumes they should do those assessments on a case by 
case basis. If there are people drinking the water, the developer should clean up the contamination not 
just provide bottled water or treatment at the tap. No site should be able to get approved by the 
program if there is not adequate monitoring and clean up of groundwater contamination.<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left>This program will undermine clean up of all sites in Ohio, if we do not let our voices be 
heard. Write OEPA by<strong> September 9 </strong>and attend one of the three hearings in the State to 
voice your concerns. If you would like to testify at the upcoming JCARR hearing, call 
OEC, Sierra Club, or Citizen Action and they can alert you to the process and the format 
of the hearing:<font size=4><br>
</font></p>
<p align=left>&nbsp;</p>
<p align=left><font size=2><strong>Write OEPA by Sept. 9</strong></font><sup><font size=2><strong>th</strong></font></sup><font size=2><strong> at:</strong><br>
OOEPA-DERR-VAP<br>
Records Management Officer<br>
PO Box 1049 <br>
Columbus, OH 43216-1049</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2>or attend a public hearing at:<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2><strong>Sept. 4	</strong><br>
Elyria	Lorain County Community College,Science Technology <br>
1005 North Abbe Rd. Room 201<br>
</font></p>
<p align=left><font size=2><strong>Sept. 5</strong><br>
Dayton City Commission Chambers <br>
101 W. Third St. 2</font><sup><font size=2>nd</font></sup><font size=2> Floor<br>
<br>
<strong>Sept. 6	</strong><br>
Columbus	Ohio OEPA headquarters, 1800 WaterMark Dr., Room 1-A&amp;B<br>
By the time you read this the proposed rules should be available for review at the following locations:<br>
</font></p>
<div align=left>
<address><font size=2>Through Ohio OEPA's web page on the internet. The address for the Voluntary Action Program is 
http://www.OEPA.ohio.gov/derr/volunt.html<br>
</font></address>
</div>
<p align=left>Written comments also will be accepted until the close of business on September 9, 1996. 
Comments should be sent to Ohio OEPA, DERR-VAP, Records Management Officer, 
PO Box 1049, Columbus, OH 43216-1049 <br>
</p>
