</DOCHDR>
<title>GreenForum</title>
<b>From:</b> <a href="mailto:gec@sprynet.com">gec@sprynet.com</a><br>
<b>Date:</b> Thu, 17 Oct 96 10:13:00 -0500<br>
<b>To:</b> <a href="mailto:reg-agencies@greenlink.org">reg-agencies@greenlink.org</a><br>
<b>Subject:</b> Conference call on audit policy with EPA Officials<br>
<hr>
<pre>
This message was forwarded to us and we thought it was significant...

Subject:Notes from Conference Call with EPA on October 1
Regarding Environmental Audit Privilege and Immunity Policies

Recently, some members of the Network conducted a conference call with
USEPA. Participants included Richard Parks and Kevin Williams, (WORC),
Sanford Lewis (Good Neighbor Project and NACS), Mike Fogelberg (Network
Against Corporate Secrecy), Mark Woodall (Sierra  Club), David Dempsey
(Michigan Environmental Council,Carol Andress (EDF), and Brian Riedel and
Eric Schaeffer of EPA, Office of Enforcement and Compliance Assurance.

Agenda: The purpose of the call was to discuss EPA's delegation 
activity, petitions to EPA, the direction that environmental audit privilege 
issues are heading, activity in the states and possible federal legislation.

Federal Legislation: EPA does not expect anything to move in Washington
through the conclusion of 1996.  1997 will likely see activity. There is
some indication that a federal bill on privilege may be akin to the South
Carolina law where "facts" and data are not privileged but "analysis" is.
In such an event, EPA will oppose it.  No language is floating yet.  If the
EPA policy is introduced as legislation, EPA not sure what its position will
be. 

Some conservatives may also approach audit legislation from a states' rights 
standpoint, seeking to bar EPA's program delegation-related challenges 
to state environmental audit laws, as described below.

Late session riders on appropriations bills are not likely to be a vehicle
though they are always a possibility.

Delegation: EPA is actively challenging environmental audit privilege and
immunity laws in  Texas, Utah, Idaho and Michigan.  It appears that EPA is
giving priority to challenging corporate secrecy  laws in states where a
delegated federal environmental program is  pending EPA approval OR in
states where citizens file a petition  with the EPA for the removal of a
federal program.  Some states with audit laws and new federal program
approvals have slipped through the cracks however. EPA is responding to
concrete cases to declare its positions on specific types of audit privilege
and immunity provisions in the states under the various environmental
frameworks (CWA, CAA, RCRA), rather than drafting a general statement.

EPA's evaluation of a state's audit law is significantly influenced 
by the interpretation of the law by state attorney generals.  In New 
Hampshire, the AG declared that the statute does not apply to federal laws.
In Virginia, a similar interpretation is likely.  If the states officially
declare that their laws do not apply to situations involving federally
delegated programs, then EPA officials believe they may no longer have
jurisdiction to challenge the audit laws.

EPA has not initiated over-filing in any state but it is apparently under
active consideration.

Any Title V decision will be made at headquarters, through the audit 
privilege task force which includes regional EPA officials.  The regions are 
reportedly pushing very hard for strong action.  EPA plans to exercise
caution in this area and is taking steps to ensure that any action is not ad
hoc, that any  actions be consistent region to region and legally credible.
EPA headquarters is involved in review, as wel as the regional offices.

EPA will continue to review pending state legislation and comment.  
EPA's position offers incentives for states to pass an EPA-type policy.  

Specific state delegation issues
o       Idaho:  Idaho has been informed in an EPA federal register notice
that it will not receive final Title V clean air act delegation unless it
repeals or revises its audit law. The Idaho AG is interpreting the audit law
as Confidential Business Information rather than privilege, an odd position
which is likely to be unacceptable to EPA.   Kevin Williams reported that a
source within the Idaho Department of Environmental Quality  informed him
that Idaho's audit law will likely be extended (it's up for  sunset review
in 1997) unless it poses a serious  threat to state delegation from EPA.
EPA was informed that there may be a petition from organizations in the state. 

o       Colorado:  EPA was informed that there may be a petition from
organizations in the state. NPDES approval is pending in the state so that
timing of the petition may be important.  

o       Michigan:  Dave Dempsey reported that there have been 2 voluntary 
disclosures on minor issues related to materials storage under the state
law. EPA is in the process of responding to a petition filed by
organizations in Michigan.

o       Texas: Texas has been informed in an EPA federal register notice
that it will not receive final Title V clean air act delegation unless it
repeals or revises its audit law. EPA is reviewing a petition by EDF and the
Oil, Chemical & Atomic Workers International Union in Texas challenging the
state's deep well injection permitting program, partly on grounds that TX
audit law impedes state enforcement capabilities.

Survey by National Conference of State Legislators:  EPA indicated that the 
National Conference of State Legislators might conduct an EPA funded survey
of audit bills and practices, their implementation and results.
Environmental groups will be invited to participate in the survey's design.
EPA also plans to have an intern examine violations that have been
voluntarily disclosed in each state that has an audit law on the books.

Federal Audit Disclosures:  EPA reported that there have been 76 
voluntary disclosures under the federal audit policy encompassing 150 
violations. Settlements have been reached in 15 cases.  Brian Riedel is
writing a report. These numbers indicate that companies will to come forward
and disclose violations without the benefit of sweeping  privileges and 
immunities, which do not exist in the EPA policy.    

National Governors' Association Resolution: Eric and Brian said the 
EPA is not significantly concerned by the final  resolution on environmental 
audit privileges adopted by the  National Governors' Association.
Apparently, the resolution asks that the EPA not step in and challenge a
federally delegated  environmental program unless there's an enforcement
issue or the state is not able to meet federal requirements.  EPA feels this
is exactly what they are in fact doing.  

U.S. Supreme Court broadens Privileges in a different context:  On a general
legal note, Eric and Brian informed us that the U.S. Supreme Court recently
decided to extend the psychiatrist/patient privilege to social workers and
their patients by a vote of 7 to 2.  Interestingly, Justice Scalia authored
a blistering dissent. 

EPA committed to providing backup documentation regarding many of the items
discussed. Contact Mike Fogelberg (mfogelberg@igc.org) if you need specific
documentation or Brian Riedel at USEPA: riedel.brian@epamail.epa.gov.

Notes from conference call prepared by joint effort of Kevin Williams, 
Mike Fogelberg and Sanford Lewis.




</pre>
<hr>
