<title>GreenForum</title>
<b>From:</b> Bruce Cornett <a href="mailto:bcornett@interserv.com">&lt;bcornett@interserv.com&gt;</a><br>
<b>Date:</b> Sun, 23 Jun 1996 12:58:07 -0400<br>
<b>To:</b> <a href="mailto:reg-agencies@greenlink.org">reg-agencies@greenlink.org</a><br>
<b>Subject:</b> Violations of Clean Air Act in Maimi Valley<br>
<hr>
<pre>
PRESS ADVISORY
							
DATE: 		Friday, June 21, 1996

For information from Ohio EPA contact the Director, Donald 
Schregardus in Columbus at 614-644-2782

Ohio EPA proposes illegal air emissions increase for 
Fairborn's Southwestern Portland Cement Company

This week the Ohio EPA proposed to increase air emissions for 
one of the largest air polluters in the Miami Valley.  
Southwestern Portland cement Company, owned by Houston, 
Texas-based Southdown Corporation, pressured the Ohio EPA to 
increase its emissions of dangerous particulates from 48 tons 
per year to over 200 tons per year.  This is over a 400 
percent increase.  

The Ohio EPA also proposes to increase the "visible 
emissions" from 15 percent to 20 percent.  This means more 
smoke out of the stack. 

The Agency also proposes to remove all emissions limits on 
cancer causing heavy metals and organic hydrocarbons.

The Ohio EPA claims that this change just takes the facility 
back to its original permit before it started burning 
hazardous waste.  Unfortunately, that is exactly what this 
illegal change does.  It throws our air program right back 
to the 1980s when the Miami Valley enjoyed some of the worst 
air in the nation. 
 

"There is an ongoing question about the company's 
competence," said Michael Jones of GEC.  "Citing 'sloppy 
science' and inconsistencies in the risk analysis, the Ohio 
Hazardous Waste Facility Board voted in 1994 to deny the 
company the right to handle hazardous waste at the Fairborn 
facility, and we don't think anything has changed with regard 
to the company's competence," he continued. "It looks like 
the OEPA is just trying to lower the permit standards 
to a point where the company just won't be in violation so 
often." 

The proposed permit also gives the company the right to 
incinerate tires.  The company proposes to bypass the 
recently adopted Ohio EPA rules on "recovering energy" from 
tires which requires shredding the tires in order to mix them 
with coal.  The company proposes to simply toss the whole 
tire into the end of the burner and let the smoke and 
unburned hydrocarbons go up the stack.  This "sham 
recycling" has the potential to release thousands of pounds 
of cancer causing chemicals into the Miami Valley.  
Ironically, if the tires contain any chlorine, dioxin may be 
created by the very air pollution control equipment put in 
place to protect us.  The company's air pollution control 
equipment operates at the same temperature as the notorious 
Montgomery County incinerator's equipment, which was the 
source of extremely high dioxin emissions.  But this permit 
will not test for dioxins, or organic hydrocarbons.  It won't 
even check for heavy metals during tire burning, as long as 
the total increase in metals emissions is less than 2000 
pounds per year.  2000 pounds of Arsenic, Beryllium, Cadmium, 
Chromium VI, Lead, Mercury, Nickel, and Zinc.  

Knowing the public will not accept this rollback in 
environmental protection, the Ohio EPA has proposed this 
change without holding a public hearing.  Review of the 
agency files reveal that Southdown, their lobbyists,  and the 
Agency have been collaborating on this change since the 
company failed an air emissions test last summer.  


There is no legal precedent for rolling back and allowing 
such dramatic increases in air emissions.  In fact, it is 
specifically against Federal law.  The clean Air Act clearly 
states that significant increases in air emissions are 
cause for the stringent New Source Review (NSR) mandates of 
the Clean Air Act (On April 12 Ohio EPA incorporated the 
Federal Requirements for NSR into its own rules; thus the 
Agency is violating its own rules in addition to the Federal 
Rules.) 

Bruce Cornett, Program Coordinator for the Greene 
Environmental Coalition said," we first learned of this 
permit by closely monitoring the official journal of 
OEPA Director, Donald Schregardus.  We have asked the agency 
to remove the conditions allowing the sham recycling of 
tires, to remove the increase in particulate emissions. We 
have also asked for a public hearing, so the people of 
the Miami Valley can speak up about the dangers to their 
health as well as the danger to their economic well being if 
the US EPA steps in and places sanctions on the entire Miami 
Valley.  And furthermore, citizens would be afforded the 
opportunity to testify against giving such a pollution permit 
increase for the benefit of one Texas corporation that wasn't 
fit to handle hazardous waste and now can't even meet its 
permit conditions."   


* The Greene Environmental Coalition has been extensively 
involved in litigation concerning Southdown's environmental 
transgressions.  Currently the group has brought the company 
into Federal Court to ensure the proper cleanup of a landfill 
that has been leaching dangerous chemicals into a Greene 
County stream near the Fairborn wellfields.
</pre>
<hr>
<address> Violations of Clean Air Act in Maimi Valley / Bruce Cornett <bcornett@interserv.com> </address><hr>
