<html>

<head>
<title>TRI - Letter</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>From: Paul Orum &lt;orump@RTK.NET </p>
<p>Date: Mon, 02 Dec 1996 13:42:17 EST</p>
<p>To: Interested parties</p>
<p>From: Paul Orum (<a href="mailto:orum@rtk.net">orum@rtk.net</a>)</p>
<p>Working Group on Community Right-to-Know</p>
<p>Re: Getting EPA's information organized</p>
<p>Date: Nov 21, 1996</p>
<p>The U.S. EPA is requesting public comments on what is potentially the most far reaching reform of 
environmental information the agency has ever attempted. EPA is considering how to establish an 
electronic pointer system linking all data collected under Federal environmental statutes. The 
agency is both accepting written comments and holding public meetings for people to speak. The 
meeting will be on:</p>
<p>December 10 in Chicago (at U.S. EPA Regional HQ, 77 West Jackson Blvd, Metcalfe Bldg.); 
andDecember 12 in Washington, DC (at U.S. EPA Education Center Auditorium).</p>
<p>TO SPEAK AT EITHER OF THESE MEETINGS YOU MUST REGISTER BY DECEMBER 
5 BY CALLING EPA AT 703-218-2700.</p>
<p>Below are an article and sample letter to EPA. For additional information see the Federal Register 
notice at 61 FR 52587 or at http://www.epa.gov/opptintr/key_id/index.htm.</p>
<p>INFORMATION REFORMS NEED HELP</p>
<p>The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is requesting public comments on what is 
potentially the most far reaching reform of environmental information the agency has ever 
attempted. If successful, EPA's &quot;facility identification&quot; (or key identifiers) initiative will set up an 
electronic pointer system for linking all data collected under Federal environmental statutes.</p>
<p>Despite spending over $300 million each year on environmental information, EPA cannot Readily 
form an environmental profile of an industrial facility or link information across more than a dozen 
separate program offices. What is more, facilities must often report information to the states rather 
than to EPA.</p>
<p>So how can EPA link-up information reported under the Clean Water Act, Clean Air Act, Toxics 
Release Inventory, Safe Drinking Water Act, and many other requirements? EPA wants to start by 
establishing a reliable identification number for every regulated facility in the country, together with a 
core set of &quot;key identifiers&quot; for each facility. These basic identifiers include facility name, address, 
contact name, parent company, industrial sector, geographic coordinates, regulatory status (permit 
numbers), etc. EPA discusses 10 such elements in its notice. These elements will enable people to 
readily obtain environmental information on, for example, a local factory, its parent company, an 
entire industry, or a zip code or watershed. The initiative also furthers consolidated &quot;one-stop&quot; 
reporting.</p>
<p>However, the effort suffers from a lack of strong direction. EPA is considering alternatives that 
simply won't achieve the goal of integrating information-such as an option that would set up 50 
separate state systems! The agency's notice presents five major alternatives, but only one, a formal 
rule (option D), can provide the commitment and stability of decision-making needed to succeed. 
Further, several important identifiers are missing from EPA's notice (see sample letter). </p>
<p>Please send EPA a short letter to move the initiative forward.</p>
<p>1. 61 FR 52587 or http://www.epa.gov/opptintr/key_id/index.htm.</p>
<p>SAMPLE LETTER</p>
<p>Administrator Carol Browner TSCA Document Office</p>
<p>U.S. EPA (1101) U.S. EPA (7407)</p>
<p>401 M Street, SW 401 M Street, SW</p>
<p>Washington, DC 20460 Washington, DC 20460</p>
<p>Re: Docket OPPTS-00186</p>
<p>The [name of organization] urges EPA to move forward with its facility identification (key 
identifiers) information reform initiative. Our [# of] members rely on information collected by states 
and EPA for effective protection of public health and the environment.</p>
<p>EPA's facility identification initiative will enable people to readily find information on environmental 
conditions where we work, live, and play. The initiative should let people easily obtain information 
from any of EPA's data collections on any regulated facility, parent company, industry, chemical, 
geographic area, or regulatory requirement. </p>
<p>However, we are troubled by EPA's lack of strong direction, and urge the agency to move forward 
with reforms that:</p>
<p>[1] Establish an effective national registration system for every facility that EPA regulates, and 
collect basic key identifiers information from each.</p>
<p>[2] Establish a unified national system, not multiple, inconsistent state data systems.</p>
<p>[3] Develop a formal rulemaking that establishes EPA's commitment, guarantees state compliance, 
and makes facilities responsible for maintaining their information.</p>
<p>[4] Include information reported under all Federal environmental laws, whether collected by states 
or EPA.</p>
<p>[5] Add critical elements not addressed in EPA's notice, including tax identification number, 
effective date, and certifying corporate officer, and assure easy links to data elements and files on <br>
chemicals (CAS number), permit numbers, and accidents.</p>
<p>Sincerely,</p>
<p>[your name and address]</p>
</body>

</html>
