<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HEAD>
<TITLE>STATE LEGISLATION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>STATE LEGISLATION</H1>
</CENTER>
<P>Rivers Unlimited works to influence public policy and legislation when it relates to the health of Ohio's rivers and waterways. </P>
<P> Anti-degradation (Section 6111.12 of Ohio Revised Code): The anti-degradation rule, passed as a hidden rider in the 1993 budget bill, would allow increased levels of pollution in 96% of Ohio's 61,000 miles of rivers and streams. Rivers Unlimited organized a coalition of 30 conservation, environmental, and recreation groups to oppose these rules. Additionally, Rivers Unlimited, with the backing of seven other groups, filed a lawsuit in December 1995 which would prevent the EPA from implementing these destructive new rules. </P>
<P> Environmental Audit Privilege (S.B. 138): This bill, under consideration in the 1996 legislative session, would allow industries that do voluntary audits to shield any civil violations that they find from public view. Rivers Unlimited strongly opposes this bill because most responsible businesses already have good environmental audit programs. The only effect this law would have is to encourage unscrupulous companies to do business in Ohio where they can hide their shady activities from the public and regulators and potentially dump illegal pollutants into our waterways.</P>
<P> Takings (H.B. 533): This bill was drafted and circulated by the Ohio Farm Bureau, who along with other proponents, argue that environmental regulations which restrict a property owner's ability to develop her/his land have had that land &quot;taken.&quot; However, there are no documented cases of takings in Ohio. Takings legislation would create a huge bureaucracy which would conduct cost/benefit analyses each time any local or state government considers an action that would protect public health, safety, or the environment that involved private land.</P>
<P></P>
<HR>
