<html>

<head>
<title>TRI - Right to Know</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>From: Paul Orum &lt;orump@RTK.NET </p>
<p>Date: Mon, 02 Dec 1996 13:40:56 EST</p>
<p>Action Alert!</p>
<p><strong>Expand Community Right-to-Know</strong></p>
<p>The U.S. EPA has announced in an Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (ANPR) that it 
intends to expand community right-to-know about the use of toxic chemicals at industrial facilities. 
This important step will support pollution prevention and inform people about potential toxic 
exposures on the job, in consumer products, and from transportation accidents.</p>
<p>We have advocated this step for years. Now that EPA has taken it, public support is essential. The 
proposal faces immense opposition from the chemical industry. To show support send short 
comments to EPA by December 30 (sample outline below).</p>
<p>Comments can be short. We suggest:</p>
<p>1. Support EPA's intention to add chemical use and worker exposure data to the Toxics Release 
Inventory (TRI) and urge the agency to move forward without delay.</p>
<p>2. Explain that the information will help you (the community, workers, consumers, environmental 
managers, government, etc.) to better understand toxic exposures and prevention opportunities.</p>
<p>3. Give one or two examples of how you would use the data. For sample ideas see the list of &quot;uses 
of use data&quot; on the reverse.</p>
<p>Send three copies to:</p>
<p>Docket OPPTS-400106</p>
<p>TSCA Document Receipt Office (7407)</p>
<p>U.S. EPA, Room E-G099</p>
<p>401 M Street, SW</p>
<p>Washington, DC 20460</p>
<p>EPA's announcement is available from:</p>
<p>EPA's TRI Homepage at http://www.epa.gov/opptintr/tri</p>
<p>The Federal Register, October 1, 1996, page 51322.</p>
<p>Uses of Use Data</p>
<p>Chemical use data, or &quot;materials accounting,&quot; tracks the flow of chemicals through an industrial 
facility. It will fill holes in current right-to-know programs for measuring pollution prevention and 
assessing potential toxic exposures on the job, in consumer products, and from transportation 
accidents. Basic materials accounting and related TRI expansion will help the public, industry, or 
government to:</p>
<p>[1] understand where toxic chemicals go (in products as well as in waste);</p>
<p>[2] assess potential toxic exposures not covered by TRI, to workers on the job, to consumers 
through products, and to communities from transportation of raw materials brought on-site;</p>
<p>[3] develop prevention opportunities inside the factory and shift attention from managing pollution 
to preventing it;</p>
<p>[4] verify and improve confidence in TRI emissions data and pollution reports filed under other 
laws (such as the Clean Water Act, Clean Air Act, etc.);</p>
<p>[5] assist prevention planning by providing measures of source reduction and chemical use 
efficiency (e.g. changes in waste per unit of chemical used);</p>
<p>[6] link use of the chemical to its life cycle of costs and impacts, both &quot;upstream from the factory 
(for chemicals brought on-site) and &quot;downstream&quot; (for use and disposal of chemical in products);<br>
</p>
<p>[7] demonstrate competence to manage chemicals;</p>
<p>[8] identify facilities with the greatest need for extended producer responsibility programs;</p>
<p>[9] encourage transfer and use of cleaner technologies; and,</p>
<p>[10] improve public understanding and worker-community-industry dialogue by giving all parties 
more equal information for environmental decision making.</p>
<p>Prepared by:</p>
<p>Working Group on Community Right-to-Know</p>
<p>218 D Street, SE</p>
<p>Washington, DC 20003</p>
<p><a href="mailto:orum@rtk.net">orum@rtk.net</a></p>
</body>

