<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>RTK _ Jan. Letter</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p>From: Paul Orum <a href="mailto:orump@RTK.NET">orump@RTK.NET</a></p>

<p>Date: Mon, 06 Jan 1997 </p>

<p>RIGHT TO KNOW EXPANSION STALLED AT WHITE HOUSE</p>

<p>A sample letter follows this brief explanation:</p>

<p>In August of 1995, President Clinton directed the EPA to
expand the public's right to know, including to sources of
pollution that are currently exempt from Federal toxics release
reporting requirements. EPA acted accordingly, and last summer
proposed to add seven new industries -- all major sources of
toxic pollution -- to the Community Right to Know reporting
requirements. </p>

<p>In June 1996, Vice President Gore and EPA Administrator
Browner held a press conference together to announce this major
expansion of right to know. These new sources of pollution
include hazardous waste incinerators, utilities, chemical
distributors, and major sections of the <br>
mining industry.</p>

<p>Well over 2,000 citizens and organizations from across the
country commented to EPA in support of this proposal. EPA worked
to finalize this proposal and make it law by the end of 1996 so
that polluters could begin their public reporting for the 1997
calendar year.</p>

<p>However, the proposal is now &quot;stuck&quot; at the Office
of Management and Budget (OMB) -- the agency that serves as a
last stop in approving all major regulations. Generally,
regulations get &quot;stuck&quot; at OMB when industry complains
about them loudly enough. We need to ensure that the White House
stands up for expansion of community right-to-know, which Clinton
campaigned for last year.</p>

<p>SAMPLE LETTER TO VICE PRESIDENT GORE ( <a
href="mailto:vice.president@whitehouse.gov">vice.president@whitehouse.gov</a>)</p>

<p>The Honorable Al Gore</p>

<p>The White House, Office of the Vice President</p>

<p>Washington, D.C. 20501</p>

<p>Dear Vice President Gore:</p>

<p>I appreciate your efforts to expand the public's right to know
about toxic pollution, but am concerned that the Environmental
Protection Agency's proposal to add currently exempt industries
to the Community Right to Know Act has become stalled. We need
your help to ensure that this regulation is finalized promptly
and not weakened.</p>

<p>I was thrilled last summer when you and EPA Administrator
Browner announced the proposal to add seven new industries to the
Community Right to Know Act. The June 26, 1996, announcement said
that EPA hoped to finalize the regulation before the end of 1996
so that the newly added companies could begin reporting for the
1997 calendar year. We may only be in the first weeks of 1997 but
the Administration's failure to meet the 1996 deadline means that
the data on toxic pollution from these new industries will be
delayed for another full calendar year. As a result, the public's
right to know about major sources of toxic pollution, such as
hazardous waste incinerators, utilities and important sections of
the mining industry, will not be fulfilled until well into 1999. </p>

<p>EPA's proposal is sound and important. I am concerned that
industry pressures are slowing the process down. Please work to
ensure that this rulemaking is finalized promptly. Thank you
again for you continued efforts to expand the public's right to
know.</p>

<p>Please send me a written response.</p>

<p>Sincerely,</p>

<p>[Your name, organization, and address]</p>

<p>Also fax copies of your letter to:</p>

<p>Sally Katzen, Administrator, OIRA, Office of Management and
Budget, Old Executive Office Building, Room 350,Washington, DC
20503</p>

<p>Fax: (202) 395-3047</p>

<p>This right-to-know fact sheet was prepared by U.S. PIRG; 218 D
Street, SE; Washington, DC 20003.</p>

