<TITLE>GREENWAYS
INITIATIVE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>GREENWAYS INITIATIVE</H1>
</CENTER>
<P><BR>
In March of 1996 Rivers Unlimited received a
grant from the George Gund Foundation for a two-year project
to generate momentum for a statewide greenways initiative. In
June of 1996 the organization hired long-time river advocate
Elaine Marsh of Bath Township to direct the project. Elaine
can be reached at ohgreenway@aol.com</P>
<P> <B>What are greenways?</B></P>
<P>Greenways are linear open spaces that tie together
people, parks, historic sites, and natural areas. They follow
streams, abandoned rail lines, canals, and other
transportation corridors. Greenways serve as buffer strips
and are rivers' last line of defense against pollution and
runoff. They also provide wildlife with habitat and migration
corridors. </P>
<P>Some greenways are created as commuting/recreational
corridors. This brings economic, cultural, and ecological
benefits to the communities in which they are created. </P>
<P><B>Rivers Unlimited's Greenways Initiative</B></P>
<P>Rivers Unlimited completed an Ohio Greenways Scoping
Study in in conjunction with the Conservation Fund. This work
has effectively brought together the major stakeholders in
Ohio, mapping existing and planned greenways. The study also
recommends new and extended greenways along rivers to connect
many of Ohio's 500 parks, historical sites, natural wonders,
and other attractions.</P>
<P> The greenways project will focus on four goals over the
next two years:</P>
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Completing a report detailing the economics
of greenways in Ohio;</LI>
<LI>Collecting case studies on greenways in Ohio;</LI>
<LI>Convening a statewide conference in 1997;</LI>
<LI>Creating an Ohio Greenways Blueprint for Action.</LI>
</UL>
<P><B>The Greenways Project Management Team, which is made up
of leaders of various conservation and recreation groups,
helps to guide the project. The Team includes:</B></P>
