<HEAD>
<TITLE>LEGISLATION
INTRODUCED TO TRANSFER</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>LEGISLATION INTRODUCED TO TRANSFER DISPOSAL
RESPONSIBILITY TO THE SECRETARY OF THE INTERIOR</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>On May 7, 1996, a bill (H.R. 3394), the
Low-Level Radioactive Waste Federal Responsibility Act of
1996, was introduced by Representative Jerry Lewis (R-CA).
The bill would transfer the disposal responsibility for
commercial low-level radioactive waste (LLRW) to the US
Secretary of the Interior for &quot;waste generated within
any state <B>outside</B> a sited compact region.&quot; </P>
<P>The proposed legislation mandates that the Secretary
establish a disposal facility on land owned by the federal
government. The Secretary could contract with the Department
of Energy (DOE) for temporary storage of LLRW at a facility
established by DOE, and may contract with DOE for disposal,
or may contract with any state for the same services at their
licensed facility. The Secretary would take physical
possession of LLRW beginning on January 1, 1997, whether a
contract with the Secretary of Energy has been completed.</P>
<P>A sited compact region, i.e., a region in which there is
located an operating disposal facility (Barnwell, SC and
Richland, WA), will continue to be such until it ceases to
accept waste. Any state that is not in a sited compact region
may provide in-state disposal of LLRW within its borders, and
is not required to accept out-of-state LLRW except under
contract to the Interior Secretary.</P>
<P>The rates are to recover the actual costs (disposal,
administrative, and contractual) and may be based upon volume
or radioactivity, or a combination of the two, but not to
exceed $500 per cubic foot of waste disposed.*</P>
<HR>
<P>*LLW Notes, Idaho National Engineering Laboratory,
May 1966.</P>
<P>Comments: H.R. 3394 may hold some possibilities for the
disposal of LLRW (I commit to further study):</P>
<P>1. The responsibility for disposal falls first to a
congressional decision to transfer control</P>
<P>to the Department of the Interior;</P>
<P>2. The control of the &quot;free state&quot; wastes would
be under one federal agency;</P>
<P>3. Standards can be prioritized;</P>
<P>4. Classifications of wastes can be established on the
basis of radioactivity and longevity</P>
<P>(rather than the current classifications of A, B and
C);</P>
<P>5. Consistent surveillance and liability can be
established and supervised by an agency</P>
<P>with expected long-life term; and </P>
<P>6. Consistent health and safety measures can be
established across the states.</P>
<P>As prepared by <CITE>Dr. Velma M. Shearer,
7/27/96</CITE></P>
<HR>
