<HEAD>
<TITLE>NUCLEAR
REGULATORY COMMISSION OPTION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION OPTION</H2>
<P>At an All Employee's Meeting of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission (NRC) on October 18, 1994, Chairman Ivan Selin
spoke to many of NRC's issues including those issues in
planning stages and in implementation phases.</P>
<P>One issue among the many of significant concern, was
directed toward the development of low-level radioactive
waste disposal facilities. He indicated that progress was
being made, though slow and too expensive, and that within
the next few years, the &quot;compacts will be well underway
to building low-level waste sites adequate to handle all of
the low-level waste generated in the United States. The
reason for my confidence is mostly that there isn't that much
low-level waste; two or three sites could handle all the
waste if it weren't for the politics.&quot;*</P>
<P>Selin's recommendation of consolidation was most alarming
to state officials of Pennsylvania which is close to choosing
a site for its low-level radioactive waste disposal, and
could end up as one of the three sites. According to Bruce
Dallas, spokesman for the Pennsylvania Department of
Environmental Resources, &quot;The consolidation recommended
by NRC could hamper a project that already is years behind
schedule and highly distrusted by the public.&quot;**</P>
<P>California could be one of the three sites since it has
chosen Ward Valley as its site, pending transfer of title of
federal land to the state of California. Bills are pending in
both the US Senate and US House of Representatives for
transfer of the title.*** Further investigation of the site
is being required, since Ward Valley has similar soil
characteristics as the Beatty, NV site where leakage is
already occurring.</P>
<P>Texas may be one of the three, since they have vowed to
build a site whether under a Compact or not, or whether
Congress approves their Compact plans or not.</P>
<P>Ohio, as the first host state of the Midwest Compact,
faces the possibility of being named a consolidation site
with its designation of a disposal site in 1998.</P>
<P>While the NRC has no authority to stop construction of a
disposal site, it can use persuasion to convince a state to
accept waste from other states.</P>
<HR>
<P>* Ivan Selin, US Nuclear Regulatory Commission,
Office of Public Affairs, October 18,</P>
<P> 1994</P>
<P>** Garry Lenton, Harrisburg Patriot-News, January 29,
1995</P>
<P>*** LLW Notes, Vol. 11, Number 4, May 1996. The bills
are:</P>
<P>S. 1596, introduced on March 7, 1996, and sponsored by
Senator Frank Murkowski </P>
<P>(R-AK) and Bennett Johnston (D-LA);</P>
<P>H.R. 3083, introduced on March 14, 1996, and sponsored by
Brian Bilbray (R-CA) and </P>
<P>co-sponsored by Representatives Carlos Moorhead (R-CA),
Duncan Hunter (R-CA),</P>
<P>Randy Cunningham (R-CA), Bill Thomas (R-CA), Don Young
(R-AK), Dan Schaefer</P>
<P>(R-CO), and Joe Barton (R-TX).</P>
<HR>
<P>Note: California and the other states in their
compact have cited the LLRW disposal site at Ward Valley as
&quot;desparately needed&quot; by cancer and other patient
groups, the medical and academic communities, and the
biotechnology community. The truth is -- that by requiring
the Department of the Interior to do independent in-depth
studies of the leaks at Beatty, NV (where the soils are
similar to Ward Valley) the Interior Department and the
President are taking prudent precaution to protect California
citizens directly, and indirectly to protect citizens of
other states across the United States.</P>
<P>As prepared by<CITE> Dr. Velma M. Shearer,
7/15/96</CITE></P>
<HR>
