<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD
HTML//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HEAD>
<TITLE>FACT
SHEET: THE ISSUE OF RADIOACTIVE WASTE DISPOSAL IN
OHIO</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>FACT SHEET: THE ISSUE OF RADIOACTIVE ASTE
DISPOSAL IN OHIO AN OHIO INITIATIVE PETITION, 1996</H2>
</CENTER>
<P></P>
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>On June 7, 1995 the Ohio General Assembly
passed Sub. S.B. 19 enabling Ohio to receive commercial
low-level radioactive wastes from five other states (Indiana,
Iowa, Minnesota, Missouri and Wisconsin) as the first Midwest
Compact host state.</LI>
<LI>The capacity of the disposal site has been designated
2.25 million cubic feet with expansion permitted by decision
of the Midwest Compact Commission, the Ohio Low Level
Radioactive Waste Development Authority and its Board of
Directors in the event a second host state fails to meet its
schedule.</LI>
<LI>The designated period for receiving radioactive waste is
20 years, and an extension of that time period is solely the
decision of the Commission, the Development Authority and
their Board of Directors.</LI>
<LI>Likewise, the decision to import wastes from states
other than the five above is the decision of the Commission,
the Development Authority and their Board of Directors.</LI>
<LI>The co-mingling of short- and long-lived radioactive
wastes, whether Class A, B, or C will require that Ohio
assume liability after the expiration of Long Term Care
Funds.</LI>
<LI>Radioactive medical treatment and research wastes are
being exploited as the preponderant reason for the disposal
siting, regardless of the fact that 80% by volume and 95% by
radioactivity (1989 figures) is generated by the nuclear
power industry.</LI>
<LI>The allowable levels of radioactivity at the disposal
site are designated as ALARA (as low as reasonably
achievable), and the Director of Health and the Public Health
Council rather than the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
determine solely the achievable level.</LI>
<LI>All decisions regarding the disposal facility siting,
operations, monitoring, and closing are to be made by the
Commission, the Development Authority, its Board of
Directors, and its appointed Councils, Review Boards, and
other appointees with only the most minimal input by a few
designated citizens.</LI>
<LI>Ohio children and future citizens will be faced with the
variables of ALARA, the uncertainties of nuclear waste
transport, the whims of political appointees to Boards and
Councils, and the questionable integrity of a closed
system.</LI>
</UL>
<P><B>IT IS IMPERATIVE THAT:</B></P>
<P>1. Citizens
participate in decisions whether Ohio can accept radioactive
wastes from other states for disposal at a facility on its
soil;</P>
<P>2. Citizens support the Initiative Petition of 1996 to be
able to vote in the November 1998 ballot to prohibit the
establishment of a disposal facility in Ohio which would
receive radioactive wastes from the five states as named
above and other states in addition.</P>
<HR>
<P>SOURCES:</P>
<P>Sub. S.B. 19, 121st General Assembly, as passed and
signed by Governor George Voinovich on June 7, 1995.</P>
<P>NUREG-1200. Low-Level Waste Disposal Licensing Program.
Standard Review Plan 4.1, Receipt and Inspection of Waste.
March 1994, p.1-4.Per: Dr. Velma M. Shearer</P>
 
