<HEAD>
<TITLE>BIPARTISAN
INVOLVEMENT NEEDED</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>BIPARTISAN INVOLVEMENT NEEDED</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>Educational institutions, agencies and
organizations, previously thought to be bipartisan, have
become involved in unbalanced presentations on the low-level
radioactive waste issue.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P><B>Ohio State University Research Foundation</B> was
awarded on June 10, 1992 a one-year Phase I contract in the
amount of $274,722 from the Midwest Low-Level Radioactive
Waste Compact to educate Ohio residents on the low-level
radioactive waste issue. This was the first phase of a four
phase &quot;Statewide Educational Program on Low-Level
Radioactive Waste.&quot;* If the University's intent is to
educate and inform, neutrality is essential. OSU's production
of a colorful edition on glossy paper may be attractive, but
it fails to present information objectively on both sides of
this complex issue, even failing to utilize the radiation
standards as presented in the BIER V Report of 1990. Rather
it promotes the pro-Compact policy choice to the exclusion of
other choices available. Such one-sided presentations are
neither defensible as appropriate expenditure of funds nor
supportable as worthy activities of an institution of higher
education where rigorous thought and critical examination of
information is said to be a priority.</P>
<P><B>The Ohio Cooperative Extension Service</B>, as the
University's &quot;communication network&quot; to the people
of Ohio, is also in danger of being used as a public
relations tool for promoters of one policy choice within the
low-level radioactive waste issue.</P>
<P><B>The League of Women Voters</B> has publicly endorsed
the Midwest Low-Level Radioactive Waste Compact. In November
1987 the League of Women Voters Education Fund announced that
it had received a major grant of $274,287 from the Department
of Energy for citizen education on nuclear waste issues.**
Further funding has come from developers and Compact
Commissions. The League is clearly partisan on this issue and
therefore cannot be regarded as a neutral, impartial
presenter of balanced information. Though chosen for this
project because of the League's &quot;national membership and
familiarity with legislative process,&quot; the League is
clearly demonstrating a partisan position of the nuclear
waste issue.</P>
<P>Recently, the League of Women Voters indicated its
oposition to the proposed Constitutional Amendment as
certified by Ohio's Attorney General on April 12,
1996.***</P>
<HR>
<P>Sources:</P>
<P>*Greg Larson Memo to Commissioners and Staff, Midwest
Interstate Low-Level Radioactive Waste Commission, November
19, 1933</P>
<P>**League of Women Voters Edcuation Fund News Release,
November 2, 1987</P>
<P>***League of Women Voters Cincinnati Area, April 1996. p.
5</P>
<HR>
<P>Note:</P>
<P>&quot;Do not accept a bribe,</P>
<P>for a bribe makes people blind to what is right</P>
<P>and subverts the cause of those who are in the
right.&quot; Exodus 23:8.</P>
<P><CITE>Dr. Velma M. Shearer7/15/96.</CITE></P>

