<HEAD>
<TITLE>History
of the Low-Level Radioactive Waste Legislation and Its
Impacts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>History of the Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Legislation and Its Impacts</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>In 1980, just before the Christmas recess, the
U.S. Senate, in a flurry of bills, passed
&quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste legislation. This
law, the Low-Level Radioactive Waste Policy Act (P.L.
96-578), made each state responsible for providing for the
disposal of low-level radioactive waste generated within its
borders. The States were permitted to enter into such
compacts as seemed necessary to provide for disposal
facilities for low-level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>Low-level radioactive waste was defined as radioactive
wastes not defined as high-level radioactive waste,
transuranic waste, spent nuclear fuel, or by-product
material.</P>
<P>The consent of Congress was granted in 1982 creating the
Midwest Low-Level Radioactive Waste Commission with a voting
member from each state. The selection and expenses of each
member became the responsibility of each member's respective
state. Each state was permitted to levy a surcharge on all
users of a regional facility to cover the annual budget, and
the Commission was to develop a management plan to accomplish
the tasks and to designate a host state. A host state could
request relief as host if no appropriate site existed within
its boundaries. If a host state was to fail to fulfill its
obligations as a host state, it could have its membership in
the Compact revoked. Sixteen states were eligible to be in
the Midwest Compact. Seven joined: Indiana, Iowa, Michigan,
Minnesota, Missouri, Ohio, and Wisconsin.</P>
<P>By late 1984, it was evident that regions without waste
sites were not progressing rapidly enough to have new
facilities operating by the deadline of 1986. A change in the
law appeared necessary in order to allow time for the
construction of the additional disposal sites foreseen in the
1980 Act. Of the three eligible sites, Hanford, Washington
and Beatty, Nevada were both temporarily closed, and
Barnwell, South Carolina had reduced the annual volume of
waste it would accept by 50 percent. The three sited states
agreed to continue to make their sites available to the
entire country for an additional seven years -- but only if
the unsited states and regions showed specific progress
toward developing new disposal capacity. The final date when
sited States could exclude waste from outside their regional
borders was extended to January 1993. In exchange, the
unsited States were required to meet a series of specific
dates, or milestones, in order to avoid penalties and
possible loss of access.</P>
<P>The Low-Level Radioactive Waste Policy Amendments Act of
1985 (P.L. 99-240) provided for a deadline in naming the
first host state, a deadline of January 1, 1993 for the host
state to take title to wastes with a deadline of January 1,
1996 for waste disposal. Michigan was named the first host
state in the Midwest Compact. By January 1, 1990, the host
state was to have applied to the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission for a license to operate. On May 5, 1992, the
&quot;take-title&quot; provision was declared
unconstitutional by the U.S. Supreme Court.</P>
<P>Article VI provided that if a party state found that no
potential facility site exists within its borders the
Commission could relieve that state of its responsibility.
Michigan so claimed this disability and was relieved of
membership in the Compact in July 1991. Ohio was then named
the host state, with the proviso that it too could withdraw
by 1997. Its membership in the Compact could then be revoked
by the Commission for withdrawal. Penalties would be
calculated for Ohio, as they were for Michigan.</P>
<P>NRC's rule making for regulating low-level radioactive
waste disposal resulted in the addition of a new part to
Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations -- 10 CFR Part
61, &quot;Licensing Requirements for Land Disposal of
Radioactive Wastes.&quot;. It set forth the procedures,
criteria, terms and conditions on which the NRC will issue
licenses for new disposal sites. In general, it covers the
following topics: </P>
<P>* the performance objectives;</P>
<P>* technical requirements for the siting, design,
operations, environmental monitoring, and closure activities for a near-surface facility;
</P>
<P>* classification of wastes;</P>
<P>* technical requirements on waste form;</P>
<P>* institutional requirements;</P>
<P>* financial assurance requirements, and</P>
<P>* administrative and procedural requirements for
licensing a facility.</P>
<P>The Midwest Interstate Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Commission established its own set of By-Laws which were
adopted on March 1, 1984; amended April 17, 1985; amended
February 12, 1986; amended May 1, 1986; amended December 5,
1986, effective January 1, 1987; amended June 30, 1987. Among
the items outlined in the By-Laws are: eligibility for
membership, representation on the Commission, officers,
meetings, procedures, voting, committees, finances, reports,
availability of information to the public, amendments,
adjudication, etc. The By-Laws were again amended in June
1993, redefining some terms, and, in general, stating
requirements in more definitive terms.</P>
<P>On June 7, 1995, the Ohio Legislature passed by partisan
vote Substitute Senate Bill 19 (Sub. S. B. No. 19) to
establish an administrative structure and process for the
siting, development, and operation of a regional low-level
radioactive waste disposal facility, including the
establishment of siting criteria, to amend the Midwest
Interstate Low-Level Radioactive Waste Compact, and to
authorize the Department of Health on behalf of the state to
seek agreement state status with the United States Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.</P>
<P><B>Within this law are provisions which are of particular
concern:</B></P>
<P>1. The import and export of radioactive wastes -- the
Commission by vote can, (a) import</P>
<P>for disposal within the region, waste generated outside
the region, (b) export for disposal </P>
<P>outside the region, waste generated inside the region,
and (c) dispose of waste generated</P>
<P>within the region at a facility within the region that is
not a compact facility.</P>
<P>2. States to be required to fill unfunded remedial action
and long-term care funds -- the </P>
<P>question is whether any of the generators will exist
throughout the 500 years of the care</P>
<P>period to be able to pay into the fund. Citizens will be
the only other resource.</P>
<P>3. The acceptance period may be extended beyond twenty
years and the capacity of the </P>
<P>facility may be increased -- the decision to extend
either the period or the capacity will be</P>
<P>made by the Commission, the Ohio Low-Level Radioactive
Waste Development Authority </P>
<P>and its Board of Directors -- not by a consent of a
majority of Ohio citizens.</P>
<P>4. If the Compact is dissolved, the host state can
continue to operate the facility -- the host</P>
<P>state has the option to continue operating a facility or
in opening and operating a previously</P>
<P>closed facility as a non compact facility. No
specifications are given as to who in the host </P>
<P>state makes the decision to continue to operate the
facility, or who will give the necessary</P>
<P>surveillance.</P>
<P>5. The Compact prevails over state laws -- if the law of
a party state conflicts with this </P>
<P>Compact, the Compact shall prevail to the extent of the
conflict. The host state citizens </P>
<P>have no voice in the matter.</P>
<P>6. The waste classifications are Class A, B, and C -- all
of the classes of wastes contain</P>
<P>some high-level wastes, e.g., plutonium-239, a highly
toxic substance, even in Class A.</P>
<P>A reclassification of the wastes would permit a more
appropriate surveillance period for</P>
<P>each classification.</P>
<P>7. The definition of &quot;low-level radioactive
waste&quot; as radioactive waste that is not </P>
<P>classified as high-level radioactive waste is
inappropriate -- a non-fuel reactor component</P>
<P>emitting 1000 rads/hour is thus classed as low-level
waste since low-level is defined as</P>
<P>any waste that is not spent nuclear fuel, transuranic
waste, or by-product material (uranium</P>
<P>and thorium mill tailings). If 500 rads/hour is enough to
kill a person, then 1000 rads/hour</P>
<P>is biologically high-level indeed.</P>
<P>8. Appointments to the Ohio Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Facility Development </P>
<P>Authority (of 12 members) are by the Governor (4
appointments), the Speaker of the </P>
<P>House (4), and the President of the Senate (4) -- though
educational qualifications are</P>
<P>named for most members, the appointees to the Authority,
being political appointees,</P>
<P>suggests a closed system.</P>
<P>Legislation was introduced on May 7, 1996, H.R. 3394
called the Low-Level Radioactive Waste Federal Responsibility
Act of 1996, to repeal the Low-Level Radioactive Waste Policy
Act of 1980 and to provide for the Secretary of the Interior
to have the authority and sole responsibility of disposing of
the commercial low-level radioactive waste. The disposal
would be on federal lands, or a contract could be made with
the Department of Energy (DOE) to store or dispose of the
radioactive wastes at a facility established by DOE. Any
state that is not in a sited compact region (Barnwell, South
Carolina or Richland, Washington) may provide for in-state
disposal of low-level radioactive waste generated within its
borders, and, if so, it may not be required to accept
out-of-state low-level radioactive waste except under
contract with the Interior Secretary -- This bill may be the
opportunity to reclassify the radioactive wastes by longevity
and concentrations of radioactivity, a safer and more
manageable disposal and surveillance process.</P>
<P>Prepared by<CITE> Dr. Velma M. Shearer7/5/96 </CITE></P>
