<p><a href="#THE COAST ALLIANCE: WHO WE ARE ">What is the Coastal Alliance?</a></p>
<p><a href="#Survey Results">Survey Results</a></p>
<p><a href="#OHIO&#146;S COASTAL RESOURCES FACTS AND FIGURES ">Interesting Facts and Figures Concerning Coastal Revenues</a></p>
<p><a name="THE COAST ALLIANCE: WHO WE ARE ">The Coastal Alliance: Who We Are</a></p>
<p>The Coast Alliance is a non-profit corporation formed in 1979 by a number of groups and 
individuals concerned about the effects on the U.S. coasts of unprecedented development pressure. 
The Coast Alliance was founded for the purpose of increasing public awareness of the coast&#146;s 
immense value, bringing new and important scientific facts about coastal ecology to public attention, 
encouraging groups across the country to work for protection of valuable coastal resources, and 
urging federal, state and local governments to strengthen policies and programs to protect coastal 
ecosystems. </p>
<p>With many issues of immense importance facing the coasts today, the Coast Alliance is dedicated 
to increasing public awareness of the problems and prospects of this country&#146;s coasts. Through its 
network of concerned activists on the Atlantic, Pacific, Gulf of Mexico and Great Lakes coasts, the 
Coast Alliance provides information on activities affecting our nation&#146;s invaluable shores, lakes and 
ocean waters. </p>
<p>For more information please contact us at the following address: COAST ALLIANCE, 215 
Pennsylvania Avenue, SE, Washington, DC 20003 Telephone: 202/546-9554 Fax: 202/546-9609 
e-mail: coast@igc.apc.org </p>
<p><a name="Survey Results"><strong>Survey Results</strong></a></p>
<p>On Saturday, September 21, 1996, the &#147;Charting the Course&#148; workshop was held in Cleveland, 
Ohio. The purpose of this full-day workshop was to bring together concerned organizations and 
citizens to evaluate the draft Ohio Coastal Management Program (CMP) and to prepare for the 
ODNR public hearings on the draft coastal program document, which were held in October. </p>
<p>Prior to the workshop, participants were asked to review one of the following sections from 
Chapter 5 of the draft Ohio Coastal Management Program: </p>
<p>1) Coastal Erosion and Flooding; Ecologically Sensitive Resources </p>
<p>2) Ports and Shore Area Development; Recreation and Cultural Resources</p>
<p>3) Fish and Wildlife Management; Water Quality and Water Quantity </p>
<p>4) Environmental Quality; Energy and Mineral Resources </p>
<p>Copies of the draft 300-page program document are available free of charge from the State of 
Ohio. You may mail in your request for the document at the following address: Ohio Coastal 
Management Program Office Ohio Department of Natural Resources 1952 Belcher Drive, Building 
C Columbus, OH 43224-1386 FAX: 614/267-2981 Public Comments on the Ohio Coastal 
Management Program must be submitted by November 15, 1996 to the following address: Joe 
Uravitch Coastal Programs Division SSMC-4, Room 11109 1305 East-West Highway Silver 
Spring, MD 20910 301/713-3155 x 195 </p>
<p>Coast Alliance will be preparing public comments, which will be drafted by late October. If you 
would like to see our comments, to sign onto them or to use them to draft your own comments, 
please call, write or e-mail us at: Coast Alliance 215 Pennsylvania Ave, SE, 3rd Floor Washington, 
DC 20003 (ph) 202/546-9554 (fax) 202/546-9609 (e-mail) coast@igc.apc.org </p>
<p><strong>Top Ten Priority Actions </strong>That Should Be Taken to by the Participants of the Ohio Coast 
&#147;Charting the Course&#148; Workshop, Ohio, Sept. 21, 1996 </p>
<p>*Numbers in the parentheses indicate the number of votes received* </p>
<p>(23) All Wetlands are Important - so few are left, encourage restoration in lieu of mitigation 
(unproven) of wetlands - restore wetlands (diked)</p>
<p>(19) Resolve Problem of Inter-agency Conflicts; - local governments, public, IJC, LWV, OEC 
should work together </p>
<p>(19) Educate Local Officials, Planning Commissions, etc., About Coastal Zone Management 
Program - mandatory education </p>
<p>(17) Public Ignorance and Apathy - educate politicians, civic leaders, churches, teachers, realtors, 
developers, media, farmers - emphasize and promote economic benefits of ecotourism - encourage 
public participation in political issues and campaigns - promote stewardship - 4 E&#146;s: economy, 
environment, ethics, aesthetics</p>
<p>(15) Nonpoint Source Pollution: Plan is Lacking; Implementation Is Needed When There&#146;s a Plan </p>
<p>(14) Protect Supply of Native Fish by: - water quality protection - predator species elimination and 
the control of damaging exotics - stocking to restore viable levels of fish - creating artificial reefs 
(14) Shoreline Protection - ODNR should purchase shore areas - enhance staff of ODNR (13) 
Public Assess (the following ways could be used to obtain public property) - brownfields - state 
acquisition - regional planning - liability and litigation issues addressed (13) Encourage 
Nonstructural Measures for Erosion Control - use technical assistance to encourage nonstructural 
measures </p>
<p>(12) Recreational Development versus Natural Areas - protect and add to natural areas, using 
multiple financing - regional planning and cooperation - protect and preserve inland lakes so less 
pressure on Lake Erie The Following are the Remaining Issues Discussed at the Workshop as 
Possible Problems in the draft Ohio Coastal Management Program That Need to be Addressed 
*The numbers in the parentheses indicates the number of votes received by each issue* </p>
<p>(11) Request final public review and comment of the final revised draft of the coastal erosion areas 
(after property owners appeal) </p>
<p>(9) Need a coordinating body, for cooperation of agencies &#150; formal structure needed - example: 
Lake Erie Commission: has no power, could coordinate if empowered </p>
<p>(8) Encourage conservation easements (conservancy district)</p>
<p>(7) Lack of cooperation and planning among all &#147;players&#148; (government, interest groups universities) 
- identify players - encourage cooperation and coordination </p>
<p>(7) Lack of collection and dissemination of information - up-to-date inventory of flora and fauna, 
especially endangered - work with universities - use of technology, i.e. lands at, website - data 
must include all costs (social and environmental) </p>
<p>(7) Reduce impermeable surfaces in the coastal zone </p>
<p>(6) EPA part of problem &#150; not controlling bioaccumulative chemicals of concern </p>
<p>(5) Water quantity: Need (soon) an Inventory of water resources - inventory of water quality </p>
<p>(5) Provide education and easy access to the public - public participation enhancement </p>
<p>(5) Encourage alternative sources of energy: wind, conservation</p>
<p>(4) Develop incentives to encourage compliance with erosion goals and policies - local and state 
cost share - state could develop incentives - North Carolina limits impermeable surfaces to less 
than 20% of developed area in coastal areas </p>
<p>(4) Prohibition on oil and gas development (in Lake Erie) </p>
<p>(3) Enforcement of US regulations on commercial fishing </p>
<p>(3) Enforcement clarification needed throughout the program - need to increase enforcement 
capacity over areas not now included (in coastal erosion area) </p>
<p>(3) Nuclear power plants should not be used for weapons production</p>
<p>(3) If power plants change mission or ownership, state consistency review should be required </p>
<p>(2) No water diversion </p>
<p>(2) Coastal zone is drawn too narrowly </p>
<p>(2) Erosion increases with high lake levels - wind set-up leads to erosion - calculate erosion risk 
including wind set-up </p>
<p>(2) Need to identify decision makers who can be made accountable</p>
<p>(2) Encourage and enforce public access to natural lakeshore areas and developed areas</p>
<p>(2) reintegrate wetlands with the Lake Erie ecosystem</p>
<p>(1) What is the Ohio Safe Drinking Water Act? </p>
<p>(1) Discourage solid, infectious and hazardous waste facilities siting near shorelines and watersheds </p>
<p><a name="OHIO&#146;S COASTAL RESOURCES FACTS AND FIGURES "><strong>OHIO&#146;S COASTAL RESOURCES FACTS AND FIGURES </strong></a></p>
<p>Source: Coast Alliance, State of the Coasts: A State-By-State Analysis of the Vital Link Between 
Healthy Coasts and a Healthy Economy, 215 Pennsylvania Ave., SE, Washington, D.C. 20003. 
202/546-9554 </p>
<p>Physical Setting Ohio&#146;s coastal area covers 3,774 square miles bordering Lake Erie. </p>
<p>Ohio&#146;s Economy Depends on Clean Lake Water. Ohio&#146;s tourism and fishing industries are 
dependent upon clean water. According to a 1993 Sierra Club report, the Ohio Department of 
Development calculates that the Lake Erie recreation industry alone generates $8.5 billion per year 
and supports both directly and indirectly 152,080 jobs. </p>
<p>Three lakeshore counties - Erie, Lorain, and Ottawa - attract six to eight million visitors annually, an 
influx that generates $200 million per year. The Perry&#146;s Victory National Park alone has 186,172 
visitors annually, generating over $2 million in revenue. </p>
<p>According to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), Ohio commercial 
fishermen landed 3,438,000 pounds of fish, worth well over one million dollars, in 1988. </p>
<p>Recreational fishermen had bountiful catches, as well. A 1991 survey by the Department of Interior 
revealed that Ohio sport fishing has grown into a $862 million industry that provides 29,000 jobs. </p>
<p>All these fishermen need licenses, so it&#146;s not surprising that revenue from fishing licenses alone 
brought in $12 million, and registered boats in the state number 383,000. In fact, sales tax on all 
those goods brought by fishermen totals $49 million. </p>
<p>The fishing and tourism industries are completely dependent upon clean and healthy waters. 
Pollution leads to swimming advisories and fishing prohibitions. When the public perceives that the 
waters are not clean enough to be enjoyed, and the fish are not healthy enough to eat, tourism to 
Lake Erie&#146;s shore is dramatically affected. </p>
<p>The Ohio shipping industry also benefits form clean water. Ohio boasts four of the 10 busiest Great 
Lakes ports: Toledo, Cleveland, Lorain, and Ashtabula. A recent University of Toledo study 
showed that port-related activities generated 5,000 jobs and a $100 million payroll in the area. </p>
<p>But dredging costs in all four of these ports are dramatically affected by the additional expense of 
handling contaminated sediments. Pollution in water inevitably makes its way to the lakebottom, 
creating a human and ecological health problem and a threat to commerce. The dredging and 
disposal of contaminated sediments is and issue facing many of the Great Lake&#146;s ports, and many 
agree that pollution prevention is the best means of addressing this contentious issue. </p>
<p>Environmental Regulations Do Not Stop Development </p>
<p>Seventy-five percent of the Ohio shoreline is developed and that trend is expected to continue. A 
lot of that development took place in the years directly following Earth Day 1970 and the 
regulations that it prompted. According to NOAA, from 1970-1989, more than 206,000 
residential units were built in the coastal counties, and 14,492 retail, hotel, industrial and 
recreational buildings went up. </p>
<p>There are several hot spots of growth among Ohio&#146;s coastal counties. Cuyahoga, Lucas, Lake and 
Lorain counties are being developed most quickly. Obviously, regulations designed to protect 
water quality and habitat have not prohibited coastal development, as is often alleged. This puts to 
rest the myth that environmental management stops development or &quot;takes&quot; private property. </p>
<p><strong>Annual Economic Benefits of Clean Great Lakes Waters Along Ohio Sportfishing 
</strong>Expenditures-------.$862 million </p>
<p>Jobs Generated-----...29,000 </p>
<p>State Sales Tax----$49 million </p>
<p>State Income Tax---.$24 million </p>
<p>Registered Boats---..383,000 </p>
<p>Total Anglers------.629,000 </p>
<p>Recreation Industry, Total Income-------------$8.5 billion Jobs Generated-----152,080 </p>
<p>Tourism (3 counties)---...$200 million </p>
<p>Commercial Fishing Pounds Landed--------3.5 million </p>
<p>Income---------------.$1 million </p>
<p>Sources: 1991 National Survey of Fishing, Hunting and Wildlife Associated Recreation, U.S. 
Department of Interior; &quot;Clean Lakes, Clean Jobs,&quot; Sierra Club, 1993; &quot;Fisheries of the United 
States 1988&quot;, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. </p>
<p><strong>Population Pressures Threaten the Ohio Coast </strong></p>
<p>Ohio&#146;s coastal area has a population of 2,736,000, or 8,892 people per square mile. This is 25 
percent of the state&#146;s total population. In 1988, 8,892 people per mile lived along Ohio&#146;s coast. 
That number is expected to increase to 9,006 by the year 2010. This increase in coastal population 
will place additional pressures on the state&#146;s lands and water - areas that are already stressed from 
current uses. </p>
<p><strong>Great Lakes Pollution Threatens Ohio&#146;s Economy </strong></p>
<p>According to Ohio&#146;s 1992 Water Quality Report to the EPA, 236 miles of Ohio shore are only 
partially supporting of aquatic life, meaning that at times the water quality fails to meet designated 
use criteria. Metals, organics and low dissolved oxygen are the major causes of impairment. </p>
<p>Sediment contamination will raise dredging costs for Ohio ports unless measures are taken to 
prevent pollution. Runoff and contaminated sediments poison the fish that support the state&#146;s $862 
million sport fishing industry. Without a doubt, the coastal tourism and shipping industries will falter 
if they are unable to boast clean, healthy waters. </p>
<p><strong>Ohio&#146;s Shores Need Coastal Management </strong></p>
<p>Ohio has recognized the need to protect its coastal zone and is currently developing a Coastal Zone 
Management Plan which will make it eligible for federal funds needed to implement its coastal 
management measures. If its coastal zone plan is approved, the state will also develop a Coastal 
Nonpoint Pollution Control Program, dubbed &quot;Section 6217,&quot; which holds promise for the future. </p>
<p>But time is running out on both the CZMA and Section 6217 programs. The laws expire this year 
unless Congress continues them. [CZMA was reauthorized for three years.] </p>
<p>It is up to Congress to determine if protecting and restoring Ohio&#146;s Great Lakes coast is important 
enough to stay the course with these programs. At a time when Ohio has recognized the need for 
additional coastal management measures, it is important that the federal government provide the 
leadership needed to protect the Coastal Zone Management Act. The decision will directly impact 
the state&#146;s economy &#150; and its coasts. </p>
<hr>
