<head>
<title>Canoe - Alert</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Dear CANOE members,</p>
<p>As if Tinker's Creek wasn't insult enough, today we had to file comments to oppose a 404 permit 
by Martin Marietta to move Indian Creek in Butler County so that the company could enlarge their 
gravel mining operation!! This trendis outrageous. I thought you would find the comments we filed 
today to be of interest.</p>
<p>Stay tuned....</p>
<p>November 22, 1996</p>
<p>Lee Anne Devine, CEORL-OP-FN</p>
<p>U. S. Army Corps of Engineers, Louisville District</p>
<p>P. O. Box 59</p>
<p>Louisville, KY 40201-0059</p>
<p>Dear Ms. Devine:</p>
<p>We are writing regarding Public Notice Number 199601200 to register in the strongest way 
possible our complete opposition to this absurd idea to move a creek for the sake of a gravel 
mining operation. Nothing could be further from the intent of the federal Clean Water Act and 
therefore in more direct violation of federal law.</p>
<p>At the outset, we must also note that our comments would be more extensive if we had more time 
to prepare them. Despite several change of address notices, your office still sent the public notice to 
our old address. As a result, we did not even receive the notice until this week. With that <br>
said, we would like to offer a couple of points for consideration.</p>
<p>This proposal to actually move 1200 feet of Indian Creek, at the mouth of the waterway, seriously 
undermines the public interest. The &#147;benefits&#148; of this hair-brained scheme do not in any way begin 
to approach the devastating effects. Detrimental effects include:</p>
<p>&#183; This proposal is antithetical to the premise of conservation and assumesthat Indian Creek is 
nothing more than a movable sewer.</p>
<p>&#183; The aesthetic values of this stream would be totally destroyed by channelizing and putting in the 
eyesore that is riprap.</p>
<p>&#183; The economic detriments of loss of habitat, increased sedimentation and erosion costs to the 
creek and the Great Miami River and downstream water treatment concerns far outweigh the 
temporary economic benefits of one greedy company.</p>
<p>&#183; How do you place an historic value on a natural stream channel constructed by nature? What 
possible justification do we as humans have to play God?</p>
<p>&#183; Impacts to fish and wildlife would be enormous. The new stream channel being proposed is a 
simple ditch that would destroy aquatic habitat and produce devastating effects downstream.</p>
<p>&#183; This new stream channel would increase flood damage. By straightening the channel, flow would 
be increased, erosion would accelerate and any flood waters would surge through this opening into 
the Great Miami River with devastating results.</p>
<p>&#183; This whole project turns the whole concept of responsible land use on its head. There is no 
justification to move a natural stream channel purely for the economic gain of one private entity.</p>
<p>&#183; There is no benefit to navigation from this project.</p>
<p>&#183; Recreational detriments are numerous.</p>
<p>&#183; Increased sedimentation and erosion from this project will increase water supply treatment costs.</p>
<p>&#183; Water quality would be needlessly devastated.</p>
<p>&#183; There is no energy need benefit.</p>
<p>&#183; Safety concerns would soar. The new channel would be unstable and flood damage would 
increase.</p>
<p>&#183; This project does nothing for the overall needs and welfare of the people.</p>
<p>Overall, granting a 404 permit for this project would directly contradict the federal Clean Water 
Act. We urge the Corps to hold public hearings on this matter and ultimately to reject this absurd 
proposal. Our organization will not hesitate to fight this proposal with every resource at our 
disposal.</p>
<p>We respectfully ask the Army Corps of Engineers to deny this permit.</p>
<p>Sincerely,</p>
<p>Todd L. Ambs</p>
<p>Executive Director</p>
<hr>
