<HTML VERSION="-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nuclear
Power Deception</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>Nuclear Power Deception</H2>
</CENTER>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>&quot;I am sure we are agreed that the ultimate survival
of America</P>
<P>is dependent on intellectual vigor and on spiritual
deeprooting --</P>
<P>not on specific devices which are always for the moment.
The</P>
<P>atom has no ethics of its own any more than it has
politics. The</P>
<P>future of the scientists' America, and yours and mine,
lies</P>
<P>fundamentally with education -- that which is taught to
the young </P>
<P>in our schools -- that which is taught throughout life in
the media</P>
<P>of general communication by the contemporary writers.
Funda-</P>
<P>mental are respect and zeal for scholarship, a lively
regard for</P>
<P>moral values, and a love of truth. And of these the last
is, of</P>
<P>course, the greatest.&quot;</P>
<P>-- Lewis Strauss, AEC Chairman, 1954</P>
<HR>
<P>Society must face the harsh realities of an
environment and a way of life which is threatened by the
products and wastes of its own ingenuity. Technology alone
cannot tell what a quality of life is, nor can it provide
that life. It cannot tell what a just society is, nor can it
produce such a society apart from the insight and commitment
of those within it who value the life of people and the
environment. Personal choices, group choices, religious
influences, cultural factors including educational choices
all can affect societal quality.</P>
<P>A technology that is imposed upon a people, particularly
that which also imposes a waste of enormous toxic qualities
must awaken to the truth of its deeds. For example, of the
six disposal sites that have accepted low-level radioactive
wastes in the past or are currently accepting waste, all six
are leaking radioactivity to the environment. The six sites
are: Beatty, NV; Richland, WA; Barnwell, SC; West Valley, NY;
Maxey Flats, KY; and Sheffield, IL. The question can and
should be raised about the whole process of radioactive waste
disposal -- whether it is the disposal method, the
containment method, the siting process, the level of
radioactivity, or the licensing process. And then there is an
issue which has been kept until an appropriate time to go
public, i.e., the intent to press into effect an array of
&quot;Inherently Safe&quot; Reactors -- commercial nuclear
power's second generation of reactors -- before the public
becomes aware of the truth. Threats of varying levels of
energy shortage will be used as a promotion of revamped
reactors and new reactor systems regardless of the question
of safety and the nuclear waste disposal problems.</P>
<P>According to Thomas B. Johansson et al,* &quot;It will
not be possible to provide the energy needed to bring a
decent standard of living to the world's poor or to sustain
the economic well-being of the industrialized countries in
environmentally acceptable ways, if the present energy course
continues. The path to a sustainable society requires more
efficient energy use and a shift to a variety of renewable
energy sources.&quot; </P>
<P>Any society acquiring a technology should have the
democratic possibility to say yes or no, and should take on
the responsibility to think through its consequences and to
make the judgment as to whether it will really enhance life
for all people in the society. Simultaneously the full truth
about the technology should be revealed to the people as they
make their decision. This is the only way to have and
maintain an ethical and democratic society.</P>
<HR>
<P>*Thomas B. Johansson, Henry Kelly, Amulya K.N. Reddy,
Robert H. Williams, eds., Renewable Energy: Sources for Fuels
and Electricity, Washington, DC: Island Press, 1993.</P>
<P><CITE>Dr. Velma M. Shearer7/30/96</CITE></P>
<HR>
