<HTML VERSION="-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Commercial
Low-Level Radioactive Waste</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>Commercial Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Transportation Safety</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>According to R.S. Garcia, Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory, as reported in the &quot;Technical
Bulletin&quot; of March 1992, there were 53 transportation
accidents involving commercial low-level radioactive waste in
the years 1971-1991 as shown in the following Table:</P>
<HR>
<P> tab </P>
<PRE>
                        Number of               	    Number of
                        transportation          	    transportation
                        accidents               	    accidents
                        involving              		    involving
                        commercial             		    commercial
                        low-level              		    low-level
States        radioactive waste         	 States     radioactive waste
Arizona            	        1                       North Dakota            1
Colorado                        1                       Ohio                    2
Connecticut                     1                       Pennsylvania            2
Georgia                 	1                       S. Carolina*            10
Idaho                           2                       Tennessee               1
Illinois*                       2                       Utah                    1
Iowa                            1                       Virginia                2
Kentucky*                       2                       Washington*             2
Missouri                        2                       West Virginia           2
Montana                		5                       Wisconsin               1
New Jersy                       1                       Wyoming         	2
New York*                       5                       Washngton, D.C.		1
N. Carolina                     2                       All other states        </PRE> 


<P>*These States are currently host States or are
former host States to a commercial low-level radioactive
waste disposal facility.</P>
<HR>
<P>Approximately two million shipments classified as
radioactive materials are made each year. Of this amount only
a small fraction is classified as low-level radioactive waste
(Note that commercial low-level radioactive waste would be an
even smaller fraction. Garcia does not separate commercial
shipments from Department of Energy shipments.).</P>
<P>Of the 53 transportation accidents listed by Garcia, only
four involved the release of radioactive waste (for example,
a package opening). Out of a total of 48 packages in those
four shipments, 22 were damaged severely enough to release
some of the contents. All of these packages were Type A
packages designed for transport conditions, not accident
conditions.</P>
<P>However, in another report, the US Department of
Transportation, Radioactive Incident Reports, 62 radioactive
accidents for Ohio alone were recorded between 1971 and 1995;
the total for the United States was 1629 accidents during the
same years. The total for Ohio includes accidents, spills,
leaks, and theft. Of the 62 accidents in Ohio, at least 22
resulted in release and 7 were theft.</P>
<P>Prepared by<CITE> Dr. Velma M. Shearer7/26/96</CITE></P>
<HR>
