<HEAD>
<TITLE>AN
EMERGENCY RESOLUTION opposing the State of Ohio being
selected as the receiver of hazardous and radioactive wastes
from five Midwestern states.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><B>AN EMERGENCY RESOLUTION</B> opposing the State of Ohio
being selected as the receiver of hazardous and radioactive
wastes from five Midwestern states.</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>CITY OF ____________________________ (your city or
county) </P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>Resolution No. _______________________ </P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>Introduced By: ___________________________ </P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P><B>A RESOLUTION OPPOSING SENATE BILL 19 DESIGNATING THE
STATE OF OHIO AS THE FIRST LOW-LEVEL RADIOACTIVE WASTE
DISPOSAL SITE FOR</B></P>
<P><B> FIVE MIDWESTERN STATES AND DECLARING AN
EMERGENCY.</B></P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P><B>WHEREAS</B>, on June 9, 1995, Governor George
Voinovich signed Senate Bill 19 which designates the State of
Ohio as the first low-level radioactive waste disposal site
for five Midwestern States; and</P>
<P><B>WHEREAS</B>, the &quot;low-Level&quot; radioactive
wastes that will be put into this disposal site are very
highly toxic and long-lived radioactive materials, including
all wastes from nuclear power plants except the
&quot;high-level&quot; radioactive fuel rods and some Greater
than Class C wastes; and</P>
<P><B>WHEREAS</B>, there is no safe technology for disposal
of &quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste, and the taxpayers
in the State of Ohio will take permanent title to and
environmental and economic liability for a disposal site that
is damaging the environment and jeopardizing the health and
welfare of the citizens of the State of Ohio, therefore,</P>
<P><B>BE IT RESOLVED BY THE COUNCIL OF THE CITY OF</B> (your
city or county) :</P>
<P>__________________________________</P>
<P><B>SECTION 1</B>: That this Council strongly opposes the
State of Ohio being selected as the receiver of hazardous
radioactive waste from five Midwestern States and will not
serve as the five state disposal site.</P>
<P><B>SECTION 2</B>: That the Clerk of Council is hereby
directed to transmit copies of this resolution to the
Governor of the State of Ohio, the President of the Ohio
State Senate, the Speaker of the House of Representatives of
Ohio, the U.S. Senators from Ohio and the U.S. Representative
of this District.</P>
<P><B>SECTION 3</B>: It is found and determined that all
formal actions of this Council concerning and relating to
this Resolution were adopted in an open meeting of this
Council, and that all deliberations of this Council and any
of its committees that resulted in such formal actions were
in meetings open to the public in compliance will all legal
requirements, including Section 121.22 of the Ohio Revised
Code.</P>
<P><B>SECTION 4</B>: This Resolution is hereby declared to
be an emergency measure immediately necessary for the
preservation of the public peace, health, safety and welfare
of said City (or County), and further reason that Council
deems it necessary to oppose the selection of Ohio as the
disposal site for the low-level radioactive waste of five
Midwestern States; therefore, this Resolution shall take
effect and be in force immediately from and after its passage
and approval by the Mayor (or County).</P>
<P><BR>
 </P>
<P>PASSED:________________________________ </P>
<P>ATTEST: </P>
<P>________________________________________(President of
Council)</P>
<P>________________________________________ ( Mayor) </P>
<P>________________________________________ (Clerk of
Council)</P>
