<body>
<h3 align=center>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO ENVIRONMENT 
-- <a name="CANOE">CANOE</a></h3>
<p><a href="#PADDLERS AND PEDESTRIANS TO GATHER IN CLEVELAND FOR CLEAN WATER">PADDLERS AND PEDESTRIANS TO GATHER IN CLEVELAND FOR CLEAN WATER</a></p>
<p><a href="#PRESIDENT SIGNS BILL PROTECTING NATION'S WATERWAYS">PRESIDENT SIGNS BILL PROTECTING NATION'S WATERWAYS</a></p>
<p><a href="#BARBERTON ADDS $3.5 MILLION TO DEVELOP NATIONAL HERITAGE CORRIDOR">BARBERTON ADDS $3.5 MILLION TO DEVELOP NATIONAL HERITAGE CORRIDOR</a></p>
<p><a name="PADDLERS AND PEDESTRIANS TO GATHER IN CLEVELAND FOR CLEAN WATER">PADDLERS AND PEDESTRIANS TO GATHER IN CLEVELAND FOR CLEAN WATER</a></p>
<p>In the spirit of Thanksgiving, on Saturday, November 16, citizens will gather at Settler's Landing 
Park on the Cuyahoga River in downtown Cleveland to offer thanks for the life-giving benefits of 
clean water and to appeal for strengthening Ohio's Great Lakes Water Quality Rules. Ohio EPA is 
in the process of drafting rules for the implementation of the Great Lakes Water Quality Initiative. 
The rally will encourage stateofficials &quot;to take the high road&quot; and enact strong protections for <br>
human health. Sponsors of the rally are Ohio Citizen Action, Rivers Unlimited, Friends of the 
Crooked River, Ohio Environmental Council and others. The purpose of the rally is to attract 
media attention, and generate community support for stronger laws to regulate dumping into the 
Great Lakes. </p>
<p>Canoeists will arrive at the park by way of the old river channel. Pedestrians will arrive via the new 
RTA Waterfront rapid-transit line. Both walkers and paddlers are needed. Paddlers must have 
their own boats and be experienced. </p>
<p>For more information about the rally contact Elaine Marsh at 216/657-2055 [work] or 
330/666-4026 [home].</p>
<h6><a href="#CANOE">Return to Top of Page</a></h6>
<p><a name="PRESIDENT SIGNS BILL PROTECTING NATION'S WATERWAYS">PRESIDENT SIGNS BILL PROTECTING NATION'S WATERWAYS</a></p>
<p>President Clinton recently signed a bill that is designed to safeguard all of America's waterways 
from non-native species. The bill expands upon existing rules that already prohibit foreign ships 
from releasing ballast waters in the Great Lakes.</p>
<p>The &quot;National Invasive Species Act of 1996&quot; was introduced to protect American waters from 
foreign invaders. Lake Erie and its wetlands have been highly impacted by alien species, including 
zebra muscles, purple loosestrife and &quot;elephant grass.&quot; Invasive alien species, which can obliterate 
sensitive indigenous plant and animal life, have had a devastating effect on biodiversity in many 
areas of the Great Lakes. </p>
<p>For more information about the effects of alien species and what you can do, contact Ohio Sea 
Grant at 216/350-2582.</p>
<h6><a href="#CANOE">Return to Top of Page</a></h6>
<p><a name="BARBERTON ADDS $3.5 MILLION TO DEVELOP NATIONAL HERITAGE CORRIDOR">BARBERTON ADDS $3.5 MILLION TO DEVELOP NATIONAL HERITAGE CORRIDOR</a></p>
<p>In late September, Congress designated the Ohio &amp; Erie Canal corridor in northeast Ohio as a 
National Heritage Corridor. Early this week, the City of Barberton, a southern suburb of Akron, 
announced plans for its portion of this 87 mile federal corridor. The city's plan calls for improved 
trails,new visitor facilities, historic interpretative amenities and a new bike route. The City will seek 
federal, state and private funds to cover the $3.5 million price tag.</p>
<p>For information on other developments along the Ohio &amp; Erie Canal, contact Dan Rice, Executive 
Director of the Ohio &amp; Erie Canal Corridor Coalition at 330/434-5657.</p>
<p>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous funding from the 
Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI)</p>
<h6><a href="#CANOE">Return to Top of Page</a></h6>
