<title>CANOE- New Directory</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center><strong>RIVERS UNLIMITED NAMES NEW EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR</strong></h3>
<p>Rivers Unlimited, the nation&#146;s oldest statewide river protection group, today named Jeff Skelding to 
serve as executive director of the organization. Skelding will replace Todd Ambs who resigned to 
move to Madison, Wisconsin at the end of this month.</p>
<p>&#147;We are delighted to have someone of Jeff&#146;s experience and ability,&#148; said Rivers Unlimited 
President Mike Fremont. Todd has done an excellent job putting the organization in a position to 
lead the effort to protect Ohio&#146;s waterways. Jeff will be able to carry that momentum forward into 
the new year and beyond.&#148;</p>
<p>Skelding has spent a decade working on environmental and conservation issues for a variety of 
groups in New York, Pennsylvania and Ohio. Currently, Jeff is state program coordinator of the 
Ohio Chapter of the Sierra Club. Before that, he worked as communications coordinator for the 
Coalition for Sustainable Agriculture in Castile, N.Y. Prior to that, Skelding worked as program 
director for Pennsylvania Citizen Action and the Citizens Campaign for the Environment in Albany, 
N.Y.</p>
<p>Skelding said he was enthusiastic about the opportunity to work on behalf of Ohio&#146;s rivers and 
streams. &#147;I look forward to working with the Rivers Unlimited board and members as we battle to 
protect our natural rivers and streams. As an avid fly fisherman, I am particularly aware of the need 
for clean, healthy waterways,&#148; Skelding said.</p>
<p>Jeff has an MA in environmental communications from Antioch/New England Graduate School and 
a bachelor&#146;s degree from New England College in New Hampshire. He will start in his position on 
January 13 of next year. </p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited was founded in 1972. The organization has worked on over100 projects in 38 
counties in Ohio. Current projects include generating support for a statewide greenways initiative, 
writing to double the number of scenic rivers in Ohio by the year 2000 and fighting to invalidate the 
state antidegradation statute that will allow increased pollution in over 95% of Ohio&#146;s waterways 
with no requirement for public hearings or testimony. </p>
<p>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: Todd Ambs	(614) 487-7511</p>
<hr>
