<head>
<title>affinity - Right to Know</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>The Community has a Right-to-Know More about Toxic Pollution</p>
<p>By Andrea Askowitz</p>
<p>Ohio's very own Congress member, Representative Michael Oxley (R-4), among others, is bowing 
to polluter pressure in his attempt to block the public's right to know about toxic emissions. Rep. 
Oxley, of District 4, also home to British Petroleum which is ranked number one for toxic releases 
via underground injection, recently signed on to a letter urging President Clinton to keep the 
polluting practices of the oil and gas exploration and production industry hidden from the public.</p>
<p>Seventy-eight percent of Americans believe they have a right to know about toxic pollution in their 
communities, even if the cost is passed on to the consumer reveals a nationalsurvey taken by Peter 
D. Hart Research Associates&#160;and Research&#160;Strategy Management&#160;Inc. The administration, 
environmentalists and many industry leaders claim that the Community Right to Know Act provides 
the best source of public information about toxic pollution and is one of the best environmental 
protection laws on the books.</p>
<p>The Community Right to Know Act, passed in 1986, requires large manufacturing companies to 
track and report emissions of 343 toxic chemicals known or reasonably expected to cause acute or 
chronic health effects or environmental degradation. The EPA posts reports of a company's toxic 
emissions into water, land, air and off site transfers on a national on-line database called the Toxics 
Release Inventory. </p>
<p>By publicly exposing a facility's emissions, the Community Right to Know Act gives local 
community members and activists powerful information to pressure industry and has encouraged 
some companies to clean up their acts by lowering emissions.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, the Right-to-Know Act is currently limited and does not give the full pollution 
picture. More than 72,000 chemicals are on the market today, many of which may cause cancer, 
birth defects and the deterioration of the earth. Surprisingly, the public receives information about 
fewer than 1 percent of these toxics. Non-manufacturing facilities, many of which are major sources 
of toxic emissions, have been left out of the Right-to-Know reporting program. Also, chemical use 
within a facility and transportation of chemicals through a community are still carried out <br>
behind the public curtain.</p>
<p>Close examination of operating procedures shows that real pollution prevention is not happening. 
Instead of retooling and discontinuing the use of toxic chemicals, many companies simply alter the 
chemical properties of the toxics flowing out of smoke stacks or water pipes. The altered chemicals 
are no longer subject to TRI reporting lending the appearance of lowered emissions while blinding 
the public to the danger and quantity of releases of the altered chemicals.</p>
<p>Chemicals might also be transferred into products. Currently, consumers have no way of knowing 
the potential risks of toxic products they bring into their homes, such as children's toys made of 
plastics that may leech onto skin, or adhesives under carpets that may release harmful vapors that 
are then inhaled.</p>
<p>The Community Right to Know Act tells us that while toxic emissions to air and water may have 
decreased nationally, other types of toxic waste have increased by 5 percent. This is another great 
indication that pollution is not being prevented. Contrarily, in Massachusetts and New Jersey, 
where state law requires that information about toxic use be tracked and reported, waste has been 
reduced by 14 percent.</p>
<p>Even in the face of overwhelming public support and undeniable evidence of its worth, 
Right-to-Know is under constant political strain to survive and expand. Thechemical and 
manufacturing industries have launched a multi-million dollar lobby and media campaign to diminish 
the Right-to-Know Act. The most recent assault on Right-to-Know came up in the House 
Appropriations bill which attempted to axe $1.5 million from the EPA for Right-to-Know 
expansion and existing programs. An amendment to retain funding for Right-to-Know won by a 
voice vote. Of course citizens can not expect profit-motivated industry to put health and the 
environment first, but they can expect and demand that of their law makers.</p>
<p>Congress must not be bought by special interest polluters. Instead, Congress needs to support 
legislation to expand the Right-to-Know. Citizens have a right to know what toxics are used and 
produced in their neighborhoods, what chemicals are in the products they bring into their homes 
and what polluters are emitting toxic chemicals in their communities.</p>
<p>Call your Congress Members and urge them to support legislation to expand Right-to-Know to 
include toxics use reporting. Senate Switchboard (202) 224-3121; House Switchboard (202) 
225-3121.For more information contact Ohio PIRG at 791-1116.</p>
<hr>
