<title>Canoe 101596</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p align=center>News From October 9, 1996<br>
</p>
<p>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO ENVIRONMENT -- CANOE</p>
<p align=center><a href="#EIGHT AWARD WINNERS HONORED AT ANNUAL DINNER"><strong>EIGHT AWARD WINNERS HONORED AT ANNUAL DINNER</strong></a><br>
<a href="#OHIO EPA FAVORS PARKING LOT OVER WATERWAY"><strong>OHIO EPA FAVORS PARKING LOT OVER WATERWAY</strong></a></p>
<p><a name="EIGHT AWARD WINNERS HONORED AT ANNUAL DINNER"><strong>EIGHT AWARD WINNERS HONORED AT ANNUAL DINNER</strong></a></p>
<p>Eight individuals were honored at the Rivers Unlimited Annual Dinner and Auction this past 
Saturday, October 5. The winners were selected in six categories from a list of nominees received 
from a wide variety of groups from across Ohio. The fifteen member Rivers Unlimited Board of 
Trustees cast votes to select the winners. Those receiving awards included: </p>
<p><strong>Lifetime Achievement Award - Kay Boggs, George Palmite</strong></p>
<p>Kay Boggs and George Palmiter were selected to receive the organization's highest honor, a 
lifetime achievement award. Kay has spent over thirty years working to protect and preserve the 
Big and Little Darby Creeks in central Ohio. George has spent the last 35 years of his life 
developing and perfecting a stream restoration technique which is inexpensive, effective and<br>
has minimal adverse impact on the stream itself. </p>
<p><strong>Outstanding Legislator For River Protection - State Senator Rob Burch</strong></p>
<p>Senator Burch was selected for his leadership and support for the Rivers Unlimited position on the 
&quot;antidegradation rules at the Joint Committtee on Agency Rule Review (JCARR). He led the 
unsuccessful effort to invalidate the rules.</p>
<p>Other nominees in this category included State Senator Bob Boggs, StateSenator Merle Kearns 
and State Representative Bill Schuck. </p>
<p><strong>Outstanding Public Servant for River Protection - Paul Labovitz</strong></p>
<p>An employee of the National Park Service's Rivers, Trails and Conservation Assistance Program, 
Paul was selected for his enthusiasm and unflinching work across the state to protect river systems.</p>
<p>Other nominees in this category included Franklin County Commissioner ArleneShoemaker, 
ODNR employee Jerry Wager and Natural Resource Conservation Service staffer Doug Zehner.</p>
<p><strong>Excellence in Media Coverage - T.C. Brown</strong></p>
<p>A member of the Cleveland Plain Dealer's Statehouse Bureau, T.C. was selected for his excellent 
coverage of a variety of environmental issues at the Statehouse.</p>
<p>Other nominees in this category included Akron Beacon Journal Reporter Bob Downing, Cincinnati 
Enquirer reporter Ben Kaufman, Channel 6 TV in Columbus reporter Stu Nicholson and Columbus 
Dispatch reporter Scott Powers. </p>
<p><strong>Outstanding Rivers Unlimited Volunteer - Tom Ryther, Dr. David Stansbery </strong></p>
<p>Tom and Dr. Stansbery tied for this award. Tom was selected for his ongoing efforts to support the 
work of Rivers Unlimited, most recently through his service as treasurer for the organization. Dr. 
Stansbery continues to aid the organization in whatever ways he can - a commitment that goes 
back to his help in founding the organization in 1972.</p>
<p>Other nominees in this category included Justine Magsig and Salle Cleveland.</p>
<p><strong>Home River Advocate - Doug Hill (Black River)</strong></p>
<p>Doug was selected for his efforts to almost single-handedly secure support for a study of the Black 
River for inclusion in the state scenic river system.</p>
<p>Other nominees in this category included Susan Ferritto (Tinker's Creek),Brian Fleshsig (Mad 
River) and Steve Morris (Chagrin River).</p>
<p><a name="OHIO EPA FAVORS PARKING LOT OVER WATERWAY"><strong>OHIO EPA FAVORS PARKING LOT OVER WATERWAY</strong></a></p>
<p>In a devastating decision for the future of waterways in Ohio, the Ohio EPA last week approved a 
proposal for a developer to move 1000 feet of Tinker's Creek in Twinsburg. The developer plans 
to put in a parking lot for a strip mall where this natural stream corridor now exists. Rivers 
Unlimited, the Tinker's Creek Land Conservancy and a host of other organizations all testified in 
opposition to this hair-brained scheme, but Ohio EPA Director Don Schregardus decided that a 
parking lot for a strip mall was more important than the wishes of the overwhelming majority of 
people in the area or the health of the waterway. The organizations involved in the fight to stop the 
project are considering an appeal of the decision to the Environmental Board of Review.<br>
</p>
<p>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous<br>
funding from the Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI).<br>
</p>
