<body>
<p>September 23, 1996<br>
<br>
<strong>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO ENVIRONMENT -- CANOE</strong></p>
<p><a href="#SOUTHEASTERN OHIO STREAM RESTORATION PROJECT "><strong>SOUTHEASTERN OHIO STREAM RESTORATION PROJECT</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#NATIONAL RIVERS POLICY ACT "><strong>NATIONAL RIVERS POLICY ACT</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#OHIO'S WETLANDS: ECOSYSTEMS AT RISK"><strong>OHIO'S WETLANDS: ECOSYSTEMS AT RISK</strong></a><br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="SOUTHEASTERN OHIO STREAM RESTORATION PROJECT "><strong>SOUTHEASTERN OHIO STREAM RESTORATION PROJECT </strong></a><strong>RECEIVES BOOST<br>
</strong><br>
The Monday Creek Restoration Project recently received a 1996 EPA grant<br>
for $300,000 plus matching funds for 1996-98 to reduce stream bank erosion<br>
and acid mine runoff on Rock Run, a major tributary of Monday Creek. The<br>
Creek flows through Hocking and Perry Counties before draining into the<br>
Hocking River in northwest Athens County.<br>
<br>
&quot;We have a lot of work ahead of us,&quot; said Nancy Roberts, who helps to<br>
coordinate the Monday Creek Restoration Project. &quot;It will be great to see<br>
our plans finally put into action.&quot; The citizen driven project is<br>
coordinated by Rural Action, a Southeast Ohio community redevelopment<br>
organization.<br>
<br>
The Monday Creek Restoration project is a long-term effort to deal with<br>
the aftermath of dozens of abandoned underground coal mines. When material<br>
was extracted from these mines, the unused portion was typically dumped near<br>
the mine, creating what is referred to as a 'gob pile.' When water washed<br>
over these gob piles, it becomes highly acidic and once it washes into a<br>
waterway becomes a major pollutant. Monday Creek, like many streams in<br>
Southeast Ohio, have been severely impacted by this acid mine drainage.<br>
<br>
Contributing to the reclamation efforts in the grant are Rural Action,<br>
Ohio Department of Natural Resources-Division of Mines and Reclamation, USFS<br>
Wayne National Forest, Ohio University, American Electric Power, and the U.S.<br>
Bureau of Mines.<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="NATIONAL RIVERS POLICY ACT "><strong>NATIONAL RIVERS POLICY ACT </strong></a><strong>GAINS MOMENTUM FROM RIVERS 
UNLIMITED</strong><br>
<br>
Movement toward developing a National Rivers Policy gained momentum this<br>
month when Rivers Unlimited founder and President Mike Fremont released a<br>
draft policy statement to the national rivers community. Fremont stated that<br>
the thrust of a national rivers policy would be based on the understanding<br>
that natural river systems have significant economic value, in addition to<br>
the cultural and environmental benefits they provide.<br>
<br>
Very few rivers in the U. S. today provide more than a fraction of the<br>
functions that they could--high quality drinking water, a full range of<br>
recreational uses, a diverse collection of aquatic species, enhanced property<br>
values and thus tax base, and attractive park corridors that attract<br>
tourists, to name a few. Fremont stated that the National Wild and Scenic<br>
Rivers Act, protecting only one out of every 350 river miles in the country,<br>
is symbolic rather than consequential.<br>
<br>
&quot;The prospect of a national rivers policy could inspire support of river<br>
protection groups, environmental organizations, and many of the millions of<br>
Americans who fish,&quot; said Fremont. &quot;A national policy would permit Congress<br>
to legally recognize the practical values of rivers and enact laws<br>
accordingly.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="OHIO'S WETLANDS: ECOSYSTEMS AT RISK"><strong>OHIO'S WETLANDS: ECOSYSTEMS AT RISK</strong></a><br>
<br>
The Buckeye Forest Council, a statewide forest protection group based in<br>
Athens, Ohio, is sponsoring a seminar about Ohio Wetlands on October 5 at<br>
Bowling Green State University in Bowling Green, Ohio. The event, which is<br>
co-sponsored by Rivers Unlimited, will cover the values and functions of<br>
wetlands, a history of wetlands in Ohio, and a specific campaign to save an<br>
urban tract of wetlands in Toledo.<br>
<br>
Speakers from the National Audubon Society, Friends of Wetlands, and<br>
Citizens for Buckeye Basin Parks will be among the presenters at the event.<br>
For more information, contact the Buckeye Forest Council at 614/594-6400 or<br>
buckeye@envirolink.org<br>
<br>
The <strong>CANOE</strong> system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous<br>
funding from the Hastings<br>
Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI). Feel free to contact us:<br>
1207 Grandview Ave., Suite 205<br>
</p>
</body>

