<title>Canoe 102896 </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>C.A.N.O.E. News Update from Oct. 28, 1996</h3>
<p><a href="#COLUMBUS CITIZENS GIVE INPUT ON RIVERFRONT DEVELOPMENT">COLUMBUS CITIZENS GIVE INPUT ON RIVERFRONT DEVELOPMENT</a> | <a href="#STATEWIDE GREENWAYS INITIATIVE RECEIVES FUNDING BOOST">STATEWIDE 
GREENWAYS INITIATIVE RECEIVES FUNDING BOOST</a> | <a href="#PULP AND PAPER MILL CONTINUING SOURCE OF CONTROVERSY">PULP AND PAPER MILL 
CONTINUING SOURCE OF CONTROVERSY</a> | </p>
<p><a name="COLUMBUS CITIZENS GIVE INPUT ON RIVERFRONT DEVELOPMENT">COLUMBUS CITIZENS GIVE INPUT ON RIVERFRONT DEVELOPMENT</a></p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited joined a grassroots alliance of local residents,neighborhood organizations, and 
environmentalists to influence the plan for developing of the riverfront in downtown Columbus. The 
alliance, called the Urban Oasis Coalition, formed in response to the Riverfront Commons 
Corporation's project to redevelop six miles of the Olentangy River corridor from Ohio State 
University to south of downtown at Rt. 104.</p>
<p>Members of the coalition participated in the first of three Riverfront Forums this Tuesday, and 
requested that the City of Columbus do the following:</p>
<p>* Retain all public parks and natural areas and convert additional city properties to these uses;</p>
<p>* Complete the low impact recreational trail system along the river corridor;</p>
<p>* Create a 'Capital Park for the Capital City' on the Whittier Peninsula, with 1000 foot setbacks.</p>
<p>The Riverfront Commons Corporation is the non-profit group spearheading riverfront planning for 
the City of Columbus. One piece of the redevelopment already underway includes construction of a 
controversial floodwall around the Franklinton neighborhood, which is designed to allow further 
development in the area. Rivers Unlimited is urging the planners to enact 300 foot setbacks along 
the entire 6-mile length, and to protect the designated uses of the Olentangy for fishing and 
swimming.</p>
<p><a name="STATEWIDE GREENWAYS INITIATIVE RECEIVES FUNDING BOOST">STATEWIDE GREENWAYS INITIATIVE RECEIVES FUNDING BOOST</a></p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited received word yesterday that the Nord Family Foundation in Lorain has approved 
a grant request of $30,000 to help fund its statewide greenways initiative. This grant will 
complement funding received earlier this year from the George Gund Foundation that allowed 
Rivers Unlimited to hire a Greenways Coordinator to generate momentum for theproject.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Greenways Initiative was kicked off in early 1996 and has four goals:</p>
<p>* Complete a report that details the economics of greenways in Ohio; </p>
<p>* Collect case studies where greenways have been successfully developed in Ohio;</p>
<p>* Convene a statewide conference on greenways in 1997 to mobilize support for a statewide 
initiative;</p>
<p>* Create an Ohio Greenways Blueprint for Action that recommends a course of action.</p>
<p>This grant from the Nord Family Foundation's assures that the project will successfully accomplish 
its goals.</p>
<p><a name="PULP AND PAPER MILL CONTINUING SOURCE OF CONTROVERSY">PULP AND PAPER MILL CONTINUING SOURCE OF CONTROVERSY</a></p>
<p>After several years of debate, the Apple Grove Pulp and Paper Co. received its final permit this 
summer to build an integrated pulp and paper complex near the community of Apple Grove, WV. 
The town is situated near the banks of the Ohio River, 25 miles south and across the river from 
Gallipolis, OH. The Ohio Valley Environmental Coalition and the Buckeye Forest Council both 
filed appeals to contest inadequacies of the permit, including the failure of the West Virginia Office 
of Air Quality to adequately protect public health, wildlife, and forests.</p>
<p>The Mill, which would be situated on farmland along the Ohio River, is permitted to emit toxic 
chemicals such as dioxins and furans, both of which are known cancer-causing chemicals. Although 
other companies in the U.S. use methods other than chlorine to whiten wood fiber, the technology 
used by the mill relies on chlorine bleaching. Discharges into the river could further degrade the 
already highly polluted Ohio River, upon which millions of people rely for drinking water.</p>
<p>Labor unions, area citizens, and environmental advocates have raised concerns that the plant has 
made no commitments to providing quality jobs to local workers, and that it uses outdated, 
dioxin-producing technology.</p>
<p>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous funding from the 
Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI).</p>
<hr>
