<h3 align=center>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO ENVIRONMENT</h3>
<h3 align=center><a name="C.A.N.O.E.">C.A.N.O.E.</a> - Dec. 10, 1996</h3>
<p><a href="#RIVERS UNLIMITED WELCOMES A NEW STAFF MEMBER">Rivers Unlimited Welcomes a New Staff Member</a></p>
<p><a href="#FISH (AQUATIC TYPE) MAY BE IN THE FUTURE OF THE ">Fish (Aquatic Type) May be in the Future of the Cuyahoga River</a></p>
<p><a href="#GREENWAYS, RIVERS, FISH MAY GET ADDITIONAL ">Greenways, Rivers, Fish May Get Additional Protection From New Index developed for Riparian 
Corridor Study</a></p>
<p><a href="#SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME ">Save Money and Support the Work of RU at the Same Time</a></p>
<h3 align=center><a name="RIVERS UNLIMITED WELCOMES A NEW STAFF MEMBER">RIVERS UNLIMITED WELCOMES A NEW STAFF MEMBER</a></h3>
<p>What's in a name? Well, when the name is combined with excellent experienceand superb 
motivation, Jennifer Fish is RU's choice for the organization'snew Executive Assistant. Jennifer is 
currently a graduate student at OhioState University pursuing a dual Masters in Natural Resource 
and PublicPolicy and Management. Also currently, she is working with Ohio Greenways, assisting 
in conducting case studies of successful greenway projects. Prior to joining the RU team, Jennifer 
had administrative experience at Wendy's International where she managed the administrative 
operations for the Columbus Office. She has had extended experience in park interpretation. She 
served as a park ranger at Olympic National Park and at Wind Cave National Park and as a 
Naturalist for ODNR's Burr Oak State Park. She's the right person - with the right name - for the 
job. She will be working at the Rivers Unlimited, Columbus office Monday through Friday. Send 
her an e-mail or give her a call! </p>
<h5><a href="#C.A.N.O.E.">Return to Top of Page</a></h5>
<h3 align=center><a name="FISH (AQUATIC TYPE) MAY BE IN THE FUTURE OF THE ">FISH (AQUATIC TYPE) MAY BE IN THE FUTURE OF THE 
</a>CUYAHOGA RIVER </h3>
<p>The Cuyahoga River Remedial Action Plan (RAP) conducted a $105,000 study of the cost and 
methodology of reaerating the 5.6 mile navigation channel. This waterway is dredged to a depth of 
27 feet and has a number of problems. In 1991, the Stage One Report of the RAP identified 
several difficult issues in the navigation channel, including combined sewer overflows, habitat 
obliteration, industrial discharges and contaminated sediment which is constantly stirred up by ship 
passage. However, the report identified the altered hydrology as the primary dissolved oxygen 
problem. Without sufficient dissolved oxygen, migrating fish cannot survive the waterway. This 
situation hinders healthy fish populations both in the River and in Lake Erie. The RAP called for the 
reaeration study when Ohio EPA established a fish passage Use Designation.</p>
<p>The study reviews several strategies to increase the dissolved oxygen, including artificial waterfalls 
and bubblers. The capital investment for the three strategies outlined in the report range from $8 
million to $30 million. The annual operating costs are estimated at between $203,000 and 
$450,000. But given the costs and the fact that there are no identified funding sources, 
implementing the study may be difficult. One important cost not quoted in the study is the $2-$3 
million dollars taxpayers currently spend each year to dredge the navigation channel. </p>
<p>Reaerating the Navigation Channel is extremely Good News for the Cuyahoga River and for 
fisheries in all of Ohio&#146;s water. The study will be released at a public meeting on December 11, at 4 
PM at the Cleveland City Club, 850 Euclid Ave. State the case for Ohio&#146;s fish! Attend the meeting. 
Call 216 657-2055 for more information. </p>
<h5><a href="#C.A.N.O.E.">Return to Top of Page</a></h5>
<h3 align=center><a name="GREENWAYS, RIVERS, FISH MAY GET ADDITIONAL ">GREENWAYS, RIVERS, FISH MAY GET ADDITIONAL 
</a>PROTECTION FROM NEW INDEX DEVELOPED FOR RIPARIAN 
CORRIDOR STUDY. </h3>
<p>ACRT, Inc., an engineering firm in Cuyahoga Falls, recently released a riparian study of Tinkers 
Creek commissioned by the City of Twinsburgh. The firm developed a new methodology to 
identify and prioritize the land-based natural resources in the study area. The methodology, called 
the Index of Environmental Integrity, collects and interprets data gathered from studying the botany, 
soils and current development. Used in combination with existing indices, including various habitat 
evaluation models, this method will be a valuable tool in providing scientific basis for defining 
criteria for floodway zoning. What this may mean is that consistently applied zoning based on this 
model could stand its own ground in landuse conflicts. It could be just the help that municipalities 
need to protect river corridor.</p>
<p>For more information, contact Karen Wise at ACRT, Inc. 330 945-7500. </p>
<p>P.S. Too bad the study area did not include the 1000 feet of Tinkers Creek that is currently 
scheduled to be moved to make room for a parking lot for a strip mall.</p>
<h5><a href="#C.A.N.O.E.">Return to Top of Page</a></h5>
<h3 align=center><a name="SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME ">SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME 
</a>TIME</h3>
<p>People living in the Columbus area can order Entertainment '97 coupon books through Rivers 
Unlimited. Save up to 50% off dining, travel, shopping, theatre, sports events and more at 
thousands of locations throughout central Ohio. Each book costs only $35 and $7 of every sale 
goes to Rivers Unlimited to support our programs. Don't miss this opportunity to save lots of 
money and help Rivers Unlimited. Contact the RU office for more information.</p>
<h5><a href="#C.A.N.O.E.">Return to Top of Page</a></h5>
