<body>
<h3 align=center><strong>C.A.N.O.E News from Oct. 11, 1996</strong></h3>
<p><strong>STATE TURNS ITS BACK ON CLEAN WATER</strong></p>
<p>(The following is excerpted from a Rivers Unlimited press release that went<br>
out on October 1.)<br>
Thanks to a <strong>new law</strong> that went into effect today the most pristine waterways<br>
in Ohio may be subject to more pollution, Rivers Unlimited announced. High<br>
quality, scenic waters could all get further degraded despite assurances to<br>
the contrary by the Ohio EPA. This would include such Ohio treasures as the<br>
Darby Creeks in central Ohio, the Little Miami River in the Dayton area, the<br>
Chagrin River near Cleveland and Little Beaver Creek in eastern Ohio. This<br>
new law will allow more pollutants in the 61,000 miles of rivers and streams<br>
in Ohio. It is going into effect today even though none of these high quality rivers have been 
classified under the rules for the new system. Furthermore, thanks to the new statute<br>
and rules there will no longer be any requirement for public hearings for<br>
most of the requests to dump more pollution into Ohio water.<br>
<br>
&#147;<strong>This is a very sad day for people who care about clean water in Ohio</strong>,&#148;<br>
Rivers Unlimited President Mike Fremont said. &#147;We already knew that these<br>
rules stole the public&#146;s right to have a voice in most decisions to increase<br>
pollutants into the water they drink. Unfortunately, we have just learned<br>
that Ohio EPA is moving forward with this plan despite the fact that they<br>
have not yet created the water classifications needed to protect our most<br>
pristine waterways. Every scenic river in Ohio could get trashed because<br>
Ohio EPA is rushing this process before any of these rivers have been<br>
classified under the rules for the new system,&#148; Fremont continued.<br>
<br>
Under the new law and rules, known as the antidegradation law, all of the<br>
waterways in Ohio will be reclassified into six categories. Approximately<br>
95% of the waterways in the state will be classified into the bottom two<br>
categories -- either as general high quality waters or limited resource<br>
waters. From now on, when wastewater treatment operators or other industrial<br>
dischargers apply to dump more toxins into these waters there will no longer<br>
be any requirement for public hearings or testimony. The remaining 5% of the<br>
waterways in the state that are in the top four categories would receive<br>
additional protections, Ohio EPA has repeatedly assured the public.<br>
Unfortunately, those classifications are not yet completed. As a result,<br>
each waterway is still classified under the old system. This could subject<br>
even the ten rivers in the state scenic river system to more pollution.<br>
<br>
&#147;We are doing everything we can to stop this ill-conceived, polluters<br>
protection permitting process,&#148; stated Rivers Unlimited executive director<br>
Todd Ambs. &#147;Our lawsuit to stop this statute is still pending at the<br>
Franklin County Court of Common Pleas. We plan to demand a public hearing<br>
for every single permit application regardless of the stream category. At<br>
those hearings we will insist that a comprehensive cost benefit analysis be<br>
conducted and shared with the public.<br>
Any time there is a proposal to add more pollutants to a stream we want<br>
detailed information to justify how the benefits of more pollution will<br>
outweigh the detriments of lower water quality,&#148; Ambs concluded.	<br>
</p>
<p>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous<br>
funding from the Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI).<br>
Feel free to contact us:<br>
1207 Grandview Ave., Suite 205<br>
Columbus, OH 43212-3449<br>
voice: (614) 487-7511<br>
</p>
</body>

