<BODY>
<P><BR>
August 14, 1996 CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO ENVIRONMENT</P>
<CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">NEWS FROM AUGUST, 1996</H3>
</CENTER>
<P><A HREF="#Yellow">Yellowstone Averts Mining Project</A></P>
<P><A HREF="#Hocking">Hocking River and Route 50</A></P>
<P><A HREF="#401">Section 401 Water Quality Permit</A></P>
<P><BR>
<B><A NAME="Yellow">YELLOWSTONE SAVED FROM DISASTROUS MINING PROJECT</A></B></P>
<P>     Though the environment has been under attack by both the 104th Congress<BR>
and the White House, a landmark victory for the nation's natural resources<BR>
occurred on Monday when President Clinton rescued Yellowstone National Park<BR>
from a disastrous mining project on adjacent land.<BR>
     With the backdrop of Yellowstone Park, Clinton announced that the Crown<BR>
Butte Mining Company has agreed to abandon its mining project, slated for the<BR>
mountains next to Yellowstone Park, in exchange for other federal lands.<BR>
     The proposed mine was a threat to Yellowstone and the Clark's Fork Wild<BR>
and Scenic River because of acid mine drainage, an inevitable by-product of<BR>
hard rock mining.  Acid mine drainage lowers pH of water bodies.  This<BR>
creates an environment too acidic for life, and results in a &quot;dead&quot; waterway.<BR>
 This fate for the Clark's Fork Wild and Scenic River was narrowly averted by<BR>
the agreement.<BR>
     Rebecca Wodder, President of American Rivers said &quot;this agreement<BR>
protects natural resources treasured by the American people from the<BR>
nightmare of a large acid-generating mine in the mountains of Yellowstone.&quot;</P>
<P><BR>
<B><A NAME="Hocking">DO SAFER ROADS MEAN A COMPROMISE FOR QUALITY OF LIFE?</A></B></P>
<P>     At a public hearing on July 29, local environmental advocates from<BR>
Southeast Ohio urged the EPA to carefully consider a Section 401 Water<BR>
Quality Permit application by the Ohio Department of Transportation (ODOT).<BR>
 ODOT proposes to re-route 700 feet of the Hocking River and destroy 3 acres<BR>
of wetlands in order to widen Route 50 into a 4-lane highway.<BR>
     The permit is required by the federal Clean Water Act for any entity<BR>
that wishes to discharge dredged or fill material into bodies of water,<BR>
including wetlands.<BR>
     This stretch of Route 50 has a calculated fatality rate three times as<BR>
high as the state average.  Conservancy groups and citizens from the area and<BR>
across the state are supportive of the efforts to improve safety, but the<BR>
proposed project by ODOT does not work to prevent negative impacts to the<BR>
waterways that can be easily mitigated through minor changes in the proposed<BR>
plan.<BR>
     Mary Stoertz, President of the Hocking River Commission, expressed<BR>
concern about the part of ODOT's proposal to shorten the channel.  Stoertz<BR>
said that &quot;by shortening a channel, you create a hydrologically unstable<BR>
situation.&quot;  This instability causes sediment deposition which leads to<BR>
massive amounts of future dredging costs to keep the channel free from silt.<BR>
 &quot;There is a natural length of a channel that must be maintained to have a<BR>
self-maintaining system that won't cost taxpayers a fortune.&quot;<BR>
     At the public hearing, Jason Tockman of the Buckeye Forest Council<BR>
suggested that ODOT consider lifting the highway off the ground where it<BR>
crosses the rivers and creeks.  He calls this a common sense solution that<BR>
would make the road safe without jeopardizing the quality of the environment.<BR>
     The Ohio EPA is slated to make a decision on ODOT's permit sometime this<BR>
month.</P>
<P><BR>
<B><A NAME="401">NOTICES OF PUBLIC NOTICES</A></B></P>
<P>     According to the federal Clean Water Act, whenever an entity, be it<BR>
governmental or private, wishes to discharge dredged or fill material into<BR>
bodies of water, a Section 401 Water Quality Permit is required from the EPA.<BR>
     When it is determined by the Ohio EPA that a proposal would result in<BR>
the degradation of the existing water quality, as is the case with the<BR>
re-routing of the Hocking River as seen above, the Ohio EPA is required to<BR>
provide an opportunity for public comments on the proposed project.<BR>
     Weekly, Rivers Unlimited receives stacks of notices for public hearings<BR>
around the state.  We will be alerting you about public hearing opportunities<BR>
in counties around you.  <BR>
     Because of the magnitude of notices that Rivers Unlimited receives, we<BR>
will only alert you to public hearings for projects that we believe would<BR>
pose a serious threat to water quality.  If you would like a complete list of<BR>
all the public hearings, contact Rivers Unlimited at the address below.</P>
<P><B>SECTION 401 PERMIT APPLICATIONS:  </B></P>
<P>Applicant:  Bill Marcum</P>
<P>Project:  The applicant seeks authorization, after the fact, to dredge<BR>
approximately           200cubic yards of material from 1200 linear feet of<BR>
Middle Fork Salt Creek in Vinton County.  The 200 cubic yards of material<BR>
would be placed in an adjacent oxbow.</P>
<P>Public Hearing:  August 30, 1996 from 11:00 am to 2:00 pm at the Vinton<BR>
County Community Building, Route 93, located north of McArthur in Elk<BR>
Township</P>
<P>EPA Contact:  Southeast District Office, 2195 Front Street, Logan, OH 43138<BR>
(614) 385-8501</P>
<P><BR>
Applicant:  T.J. Asher, Jeta Enterprises</P>
<P>Project:  The applicant proposes to discharge approximately 57,000 cubic<BR>
yards of fill material into wetlands adjacent to the Chagrin River for the<BR>
purposes of constructing a seven unit subdivision, including roadways and<BR>
utilities.</P>
<P>Public Hearing:  Tuesday, September 3, 1996 from 6:00 to 7:00 at Frank J.<BR>
Lausche Office Building, 615 Superior Avenue, Cleveland, OH 44113</P>
<P>EPA Contact:  Lily Aaron, Northeast District Office, 2110 E. Aurora Rd.,<BR>
Twinsburg, OH 44087  (216) 963-1129</P>
<P>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by the<BR>
generous funding from the Hastings Foundation and Recreational Equipment Inc.<BR>
(REI).  Feel free to contact us:<BR>
3953 Indianola Avenue<BR>
Columbus, OH 43214-3153<BR>
(614) 262-3764<BR>
fax:  (614) 262-7750<BR>
e-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:riveruoh@aol.com">riveruoh@aol.com</A><BR>
