<body>
<h2 align=center>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO 
ENVIRONMENT -- CANOE</h2>
<p><strong>November 18, 1996</strong></p>
<p><a href="#ENVIRONMENT WINS HALF A LOAF IN THE LEGISLATURE"><strong>Environment Wins Half a Loaf in the Legislature</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#THE ECONOMICS OF RIVER PROTECTION"><strong>The Economics of River Protection</strong></a></p>
<p><a href="#RIVERS UNLIMITED ANNUAL MEETING THIS WEEKEND"><strong>Rivers Unlimited Annual Meeting This Weekend</strong></a></p>
<p><a name="ENVIRONMENT WINS HALF A LOAF IN THE LEGISLATURE"><strong>ENVIRONMENT WINS HALF A LOAF IN THE LEGISLATURE</strong></a></p>
<p>On the last day of this year's legislative session, Ohio's environment won one and lost one. The 
legislature failed to pass the ill-conceived &quot;takings&quot; legislation but passed the environmental audit 
bill. Rivers Unlimited worked closely with several groups including Citizen Action, Great Lakes 
Audubon, the Ohio Environmental Council and the Sierra Club to defeat both of these proposals.</p>
<p>In the end the takings bill could not get voted off the floor of the Ohio Senate. The bill will have to 
be officially reintroduced next session. The takings legislation nearly passed despite the fact that the 
proponents of the legislation were unable to produce one single example of a regulatory taking in 
Ohio. This prompted the environmental community to label this bill a, &quot;solution deparately seeking a 
problem.&quot;</p>
<p>Unfortunately the environmental audit bill, better known as the Polluter's Protection Act, did not 
meet the same fate. This secrecy measure will nowallow companies to conduct voluntary audits of 
their facilities and shield what they find behind a cloak of immunity from civil prosecution. In 
addition all violations, including criminal violations, can be labelled privileged information and kept 
from regulators and the public. This bill is sure to be a green light for unscrupulous companies that 
want to hide their environmental misdeeds behind a wall of immunity provisions, courtesy of the 
Ohio General Assembly. The bill passed 62-29 in the House and passed on party lines in the 
Senate with all Democrats opposing the bill.</p>
<p><a name="THE ECONOMICS OF RIVER PROTECTION"><strong>THE ECONOMICS OF RIVER PROTECTION</strong></a></p>
<p>People who enjoy using rivers for canoeing, fishing, and swimming typically do not need or want an 
economic study to justify why they are worth saving--for them, rivers are priceless. However, 
public officials who must choose between many competing interests need economic information to 
make decisions. Therefore, in addition to the obvious cultural, environmental, and recreational 
benefits they provide, the economics of our rivers and watersheds provide some of our strongest 
arguments for river protection.</p>
<p>It is becoming clear that natural environments, such as natural river systems, provide many values 
and functions free of charge. For instance, greenway corridors and river floodplains soak up and 
store stormwaters and reduce flood damage. When we eliminate these natural aspects of our rivers, 
we often create additional costs downstream as a result of flooding.</p>
<p>Fortunately, state and local governments are increasingly recognizing the value of leaving natural 
river corridors intact, and of restoring them to more natural states. Their decisions are not based on 
any environmental thinking but on the economic advantages to communities fortunate enough to 
have waterways flowing through them. Communities that have preserved and restored their 
waterways benefit economically in the following ways:</p>
<p>&#183; Increased Tax Base. Waterways that are clean and have forest cover along their banks have 
higher property values than polluted, human-altered streams.This is true not only of residential lands 
but also commercial, institutional and industrial properties.</p>
<p>&#183; Recreation and Tourism. Clean, natural waterways attract visitors and recreationists of all types. 
The Little Miami Scenic Trail is used by over 200,000 people per year and the river itself by over 
100,000 canoeists. These activities bolster the local economy and provide business for restaurants, 
motels, and specialty shops.</p>
<p>&#183; Lower Costs for Drinking Water. Most mid-size and large cities spend millions of dollars each 
year to purify water for drinking and for residential and commercial use. Natural stream corridors 
act as buffers by filtering toxic pollutants, highway salt, and agricultural runoff before these reach the 
waterway, which ultimately lowers the cost of treating the water for human consumption.</p>
<p>&#183; Minimize Flood Damage. Natural river systems absorb the energy of floods in their meanders and 
marshes and floodplains when allowed to flow freely. When rivers are straightened or dammed, or 
have their adjacent wetlands filled, their natural ability to limit flooding is severely limited. Thus, 
downstream landowners suffer much greater economic losses and taxpayers often foot the bill in 
the form of bailouts and federally subsidized insurance to flood victims.</p>
<p>Recognizing there is great value to having economic information about rivers and their watersheds, 
Rivers Unlimited is commissioning an economic study of specific greenways in Ohio. Greenways 
are linear open spaces that frequently run along river corridors, and have quantifiable economic 
value. The economic study is part of a larger two-year effort to build momentum for a statewide 
greenways initiative and to secure the necessary public and private funds to protect greenways in 
Ohio.</p>
<p>Very few urban, suburban, or rural waterways are enjoying more than a fraction of their economic 
potential, which is highest when rivers are not polluted, dammed, channelized, or cleared of trees. 
When we can collectively understand not only the environmental but the economic benefits of river 
protection, we can make the strongest argument for keeping rivers &#147;unlimited.&#148;</p>
<p><a name="RIVERS UNLIMITED ANNUAL MEETING THIS WEEKEND"><strong>RIVERS UNLIMITED ANNUAL MEETING THIS WEEKEND</strong></a></p>
<p>Don't miss the annual meeting of Rivers Unlimited! This Sunday from 1-4 p.m., Rivers Unlimited 
will hold its annual meeting at the Ohio State University Museum of Biodiversity located at 1315 
Kinnear Road in Columbus. Everyone is encouraged to attend and all RU members will have a 
chance to elect several new members of our Board of Trustees. For further information contact the 
RU office. </p>
<p>The CANOE system is a project of Rivers Unlimited, made possible by generous funding from the 
Storer Foundation and Recreational Equipment, Inc. (REI). </p>
