<body>
<h2 align=center>CITIZEN ACTIVIST NETWORK FOR THE OHIO 
ENVIRONMENT -- <a name="CANOE">CANOE</a></h2>
<p><a href="#IT'S NOT A PRECEDENT, IT'S A POLICY!!">It's Not a Precedent, It's a Policy!!</a></p>
<p><a href="#CONSERVING OHIO'S RIVERS AND WETLANDS: CITIZEN TRAINING "><u>Conserving Ohio's Rivers and Wetlands: Citizen Training Conference</u></a></p>
<p><a href="#STARTING UP: A HANDBOOK FOR NEW RIVER AND WATERSHED ">Starting Up: A Handbook for New River and Watershed Organizations</a></p>
<p><a href="#SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME ">Save Money and Support the Work of RU at the Same Time</a></p>
<p><strong></strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="IT'S NOT A PRECEDENT, IT'S A POLICY!!"><strong>IT'S NOT A PRECEDENT, IT'S A POLICY!!</strong></a></p>
<p>Yesterday, the preliminary hearing was held for the appeal of the Ohio EPA Director's decison to 
allow a developer to move 1000 feet of Tinker's Creek in Twinsburg. As faithful readers of 
CANOE will recall, this developer has a very good reason for wanting to destroy a natural stream 
channel - he wants to build a parking lot for a strip mall. The hearing before the Environmental 
Board of Review was rather uneventful as both parties agreed to review legal documents and 
gather more information before another hearing to be set in mid-January. </p>
<p>We did learn that the Tinker's Creek project is not precedent setting. Silly us, we thought such a 
ludicrous idea as moving a natural stream corridor solely so that an individual company could make 
more money would be a nasty new precedent. It would appear however, that this is a developing 
policy within the Ohio EPA. According to Colleen Crook, in the Division of Surface Water, Ohio 
EPA has approved two other projects. In 1995, the OH EPA approved the relocation of 2,600 
feet of Buckeye Fork in Muskingum County to allow a company to mine limestone. And in 1992, a 
coal company was permitted to relocate 650 feet of Crabapple Creek in Belmont County. Now 
that we know it is a policy instead of a precedent, we feel much better!</p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return to Top</a></h5>
<p align=center><a name="CONSERVING OHIO'S RIVERS AND WETLANDS: CITIZEN TRAINING "><strong>CONSERVING OHIO'S RIVERS AND WETLANDS: CITIZEN TRAINING 
</strong></a><strong>CONFERENCE</strong></p>
<p>Rivers Unlimited encourages anyone interested in gaining skills to help protect clean waters and 
healthy rivers in Ohio to attend the Conserving Ohio's Rivers and Wetlands, citizen training 
conference. The purpose of the conference is to provide information on the status of rivers and 
wetlands in Ohio, the problems associated with conserving them, and the tools needed to promote 
their protection and restoration.</p>
<p>Each participant will have a chance to receive in-depth training in two of three topics: wetlands, 
scenic rivers, and takings. In addition, you will learn about how to use the media effectively, how 
the legislative process works, and how to influence the legislature and state agencies. The 
conference will go from Sunday, January 26 to Tuesday, January 28.Sunday from 6:00pm to 
10:00pm will include a conference overview and welcome reception. Monday from 7:30am to 
9:00pm will include a breakfast buffet, overview of issues, sessions in wetlands, takings and rivers, 
lunch, media and lobbying training, and invited keynote speaker Wendel Berry. Tuesday from 
7:30am to 4:00pm will include a breakfast buffet, a panal discussion with invited guest Donald 
Schregardus, Director of Ohio EPA, Don Anderson, Director of Ohio DNR and a representive 
from the Governor's office, and meetings with state legislators.</p>
<p>Space is limited and if you register before January 3rd the conference is available at the very low 
price of $25. After January 3rd the price is $40. Sunday's reception, breakfasts, Monday's lunch, 
and all materials are included. Participants are asked to pay their own parking ($7.00 per day at 
hotel); other meals, and transportation to Columbus. To register mail check and registration to 
National Audubon Society, Great Lakes Regional Office, 692 N. High St., Suite 208, Columbus, 
Ohio 43215-1584, phone (614) 224-3303, fax (614) 224-3305. Feel free to call either the Great 
Lakes Regional Office of the Audubon Society or the Rivers Unlimited office for more information.</p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return to Top</a></h5>
<p align=center><a name="STARTING UP: A HANDBOOK FOR NEW RIVER AND WATERSHED "><strong>STARTING UP: A HANDBOOK FOR NEW RIVER AND WATERSHED 
</strong></a><strong>ORGANIZATIONS</strong></p>
<p>Rivers Network has put together a handbook for those who are thinking seriously about starting a 
new organization to conserve a local river or already are involved in a river or watershed 
organization. &quot;Starting Up&quot; provides a treasure trove of information about how to run a successful 
organization. The information is based on the invaluable experience of dozens of leaders in the river 
and watershed conservation movement. This handbook lays out the critical moves every newly 
forming organization needs to make in order to thrive and grow. This handbook has over 350 
pages of valuable information, including choosing a name, developing your mission statement, 
recruiting your board of directors, fundraising, creating a budget, working with the media, 
producing a newsletter, and much more!! Additionally, it provides you with specific concepts and 
tools for building a strong and healthy river organization with a specific focus on the watershed 
approach to river conservation. </p>
<p>The cost is $10 for River Network Partners (including shipping) and $25 for all others (including 
shipping). To order please send your check to River Network Publications, P.O. Box 8787, 
Portland, Oregon 97207.</p>
<h5><a href="#CANOE">Return to Top</a></h5>
<p align=center><a name="SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME "><strong>SAVE MONEY AND SUPPORT THE WORK OF RU AT THE SAME TIME </strong></a></p>
<p>People living in the Columbus area can order Entertainment '97 coupon books through Rivers 
Unlimited. Save up to 50% off dining, travel, shopping, theatre, sports events and more at 
thousands of locations throughout central Ohio. Each book costs only $35 and $7 of every sale 
goes to Rivers Unlimited to support our programs. Don't miss this opportunity to save lots of 
money and help Rivers Unlimited. Contact the RU office for more information.</p>
<hr>
