<body>

<h2 align="center"><font size="2">Environment Wins Half a Loaf in
the Legislature</font></h2>

<p><font size="2">On the last day of this year&#146;s legislative
session, Ohio&#146;s environment won one and lost one. The
legislature failed to pass the ill-conceived &quot;takings&quot;
legislation but passed the environmental audit bill. Rivers
Unlimited worked closely with several groups including Citizen
Action, Great Lakes Audubon, the Ohio Environmental Council and
the Sierra Club to defeat both of these proposals.</font></p>

<p><font size="2">In the end the takings bill could not get voted
off the floor of the Ohio Senate. The bill will have to be
officially reintroduced next session. The takings legislation
nearly passed despite the fact that the proponents of the
legislation were unable to produce one single example of a
regulatory taking in Ohio. This prompted the environmental
community to label this bill a, &quot;solution desperately
seeking a problem.&quot;</font></p>

<p><font size="2">Unfortunately the environmental audit bill,
better known as the Polluter&#146;s Protection Act, did not meet
the same fate. This secrecy measure will now allow companies to
conduct voluntary audits of their facilities and shield what they
find behind a cloak of immunity from civil prosecution. In
addition all violations, including criminal violations, can be
labeled privileged information an kept from regulators and the
public. This bill is sure to be a green light for unscrupulous
companies that want to hide their environmental misdeeds behind a
wall of immunity provisions, courtesy of the Ohio General
Assembly. The bill passed 62-29 in the House and passed on party
lines in the Senate with all Democrats opposing the bill.</font></p>

